entropy: "A certain property of a body  expressed as a measurable quantity such that when there is no communication of heat the quantity remains constant but when heat enters or leaves the body the quantity increases or diminishes. If a small amount h of heat enters the body when its temperature is t in the thermodynamic scale the entropy of the body is increased by h / t. The entropy is regarded as measured from some standard temperature and pressure. Sometimes called the thermodynamic function."
entry: "The act in addition to breaking essential to constitute the offense or burglary."
entwist: "To twist or wreathe round; to intwine."
envault: "To inclose in a vault; to entomb."
envelop: "A set of limits for the performance capabilities of some type of machine  originally used to refer to aircraft. Now also used metaphorically to refer to capabilities of any system in general including human organizations esp. in the phrase push the envelope. It is used to refer to the maximum performance available at the current state of the technology and therefore refers to a class of machines in general not a specific machine."
envenom: "To taint or impregnate with bitterness  malice or hatred; to imbue as with venom; to imbitter."
envier: "One who envies; one who desires inordinately what another possesses."
envoy: "An explanatory or commendatory postscript to a poem  essay or book; -- also in the French from l'envoi."
enwoman: "To endow with the qualities of a woman."
enwomb: "To bury  as it were in a womb; to hide as in a gulf pit or cavern."
enzyme: "An unorganized or unformed ferment  in distinction from an organized or living ferment; a soluble or chemical ferment. Ptyalin pepsin diastase and rennet are good examples of enzymes."
eolian: "Formed  or deposited by the action of wind as dunes."
eolis: "A genus of nudibranch mollusks having clusters of branchial papillae along the back. See Ceratobranchia."
eophyte: "A fossil plant which is found in the lowest beds of the Silurian age."
eosin: "A yellow or brownish red dyestuff obtained by the action of bromine on fluorescein  and named from the fine rose-red which it imparts to silk. It is also used for making a fine red ink. Its solution is fluorescent."
eozoic: "Of or pertaining to rocks or strata older than the Paleozoic  in many of which the eozoon has been found."
eozoon: "A peculiar structure found in the Archaean limestones of Canada and other regions. By some geologists it is believed to be a species of gigantic Foraminifera  but others consider it a concretion without organic structure."
epacris: "A genus of shrubs  natives of Australia New Zealand etc. having pretty white red or purple blossoms and much resembling heaths."
epact: "The moon's age at the beginning of the calendar year  or the number of days by which the last new moon has preceded the beginning of the year."
epagoge: "The adducing of particular examples so as to lead to a universal conclusion; the argument by induction."
epanody: "The abnormal change of an irregular flower to a regular form; -- considered by evolutionists to be a reversion to an ancestral condition."
eparch: "In ancient Greece  the governor or perfect of a province; in modern Greece the ruler of an eparchy."
eparchy: "A province  prefecture or territory under the jurisdiction of an eparch or governor; esp. in modern Greece one of the larger subdivisions of a monarchy or province of the kingdom; in Russia a diocese or archdiocese."
epaule: "The shoulder of a bastion  or the place where its face and flank meet and form the angle called the angle of the shoulder."
epaxial: "Above  or on the dorsal side of the axis of the skeleton; episkeletal."
epeira: "A genus of spiders  including the common garden spider (E. diadema). They spin geometrical webs. See Garden spider."
epergne: "A centerpiece for table decoration  usually consisting of several dishes or receptacles of different sizes grouped together in an ornamental design."
ephod: "A part of the sacerdotal habit among Jews  being a covering for the back and breast held together on the shoulders by two clasps or brooches of onyx stones set in gold and fastened by a girdle of the same stuff as the ephod. The ephod for the priests was of plain linen; that for the high priest was richly embroidered in colors. The breastplate of the high priest was worn upon the ephod in front."
ephor: "A magistrate; one of a body of five magistrates chosen by the people of ancient Sparta. They exercised control even over the king."
ephraim: "A hunter's name for the grizzly bear."
ephyra: "A stage in the development of discophorous medusae  when they first begin to swim about after being detached from the strobila. See Strobila."
epicarp: "The external or outermost layer of a fructified or ripened ovary. See Illust. under Endocarp."
epicede: "A funeral song or discourse; an elegy."
epicene: "Fig.: Sexless; neither one thing nor the other."
epicure: "One devoted to dainty or luxurious sensual enjoyments  esp. to the luxuries of the table."
epidote: "A mineral  commonly of a yellowish green (pistachio) color occurring granular massive columnar and in monoclinic crystals. It is a silicate of alumina lime and oxide of iron or manganese."
epigaea: "An American genus of plants  containing but a single species (E. repens) the trailing arbutus."
epigene: "Formed originating on the surface of the earth; -- opposed to hypogene; as  epigene rocks."
epihyal: "A segment next above the ceratohyal in the hyoidean arch."
epimere: "One of the segments of the transverse axis  or the so called homonymous parts; as for example one of the several segments of the extremities in vertebrates or one of the similar segments in plants such as the segments of a segmented leaf."
epiotic: "The upper and outer element of periotic bone  -- in man forming a part of the temporal bone."
episode: "A separate incident  story or action introduced for the purpose of giving a greater variety to the events related; an incidental narrative or digression separable from the main subject but naturally arising from it."
epistle: "To write; to communicate in a letter or by writing."
epitaph: "To write or speak after the manner of an epitaph."
epithem: "Any external topical application to the body  except ointments and plasters as a poultice lotion etc."
epitome: "A compact or condensed representation of anything."
epozoic: "Living upon the exterior of another animal; ectozoic; -- said of external parasites."
epizoon: "One of the artificial group of invertebrates of various kinds  which live parasitically upon the exterior of other animals; an ectozoon. Among them are the lice ticks many acari the lerneans or fish lice and other crustaceans."
epoch: "An arbitrary fixed date  for which the elements used in computing the place of a planet or other heavenly body at any other date are given; as the epoch of Mars; lunar elements for the epoch March 1st 1860."
epochal: "Belonging to an epoch; of the nature of an epoch."
epode: "A species of lyric poem  invented by Archilochus in which a longer verse is followed by a shorter one; as the Epodes of Horace. It does not include the elegiac distich."
eponyme: "A name  as of a people country and the like derived from that of an individual."
eponymy: "The derivation of the name of a race  tribe etc. from that of a fabulous hero progenitor etc."
epopt: "One instructed in the mysteries of a secret system."
epulary: "Of or pertaining to a feast or banquet."
epulis: "A hard tumor developed from the gums."
epure: "A draught or model from which to build; especially  one of the full size of the work to be done; a detailed drawing."
equable: "Uniform in action or intensity; not variable or changing; -- said of the feelings or temper."
equal: "To make equal or equal to; to equalize; hence  to compare or regard as equals; to put on equality."
equally: "In an equal manner or degree in equal shares or proportion; with equal and impartial justice; without difference; alike; evenly; justly; as  equally taxed furnished etc."
equant: "A circle around whose circumference a planet or the center of ann epicycle was conceived to move uniformly; -- called also eccentric equator."
equate: "To make equal; to reduce to an average; to make such an allowance or correction in as will reduce to a common standard of comparison; to reduce to mean time or motion; as  to equate payments; to equate lines of railroad for grades or curves; equated distances."
equator: "The great circle of the celestial sphere  coincident with the plane of the earth's equator; -- so called because when the sun is in it the days and nights are of equal length; hence called also the equinoctial and on maps globes etc. the equinoctial line."
equerry: "An officer of princes or nobles  charged with the care of their horses."
equi-: "A prefix  meaning equally; as equidistant; equiangular."
equine: "Of  pertaining to or resembling a horse."
equites: "An order of knights holding a middle place between the senate and the commonalty; members of the Roman equestrian order."
equity: "A system of jurisprudence  supplemental to law properly so called and complemental of it."
equus: "A genus of mammals  including the horse ass etc."
erased: "Represented with jagged and uneven edges  as is torn off; -- used esp. of the head or limb of a beast. Cf. Couped."
erase: "Fig.: To obliterate; to expunge; to blot out; -- used of ideas in the mind or memory."
eraser: "One who  or that which erases; esp. a sharp instrument or a piece of rubber used to erase writings drawings etc."
erasion: "The act of erasing; a rubbing out; obliteration."
erasure: "The act of erasing; a scratching out; obliteration."
erative: "Pertaining to the Muse Erato who presided over amatory poetry."
erato: "The Muse who presided over lyric and amatory poetry."
erbium: "A rare metallic element associated with several other rare elements in the mineral gadolinite from Ytterby in Sweden. Symbol Er. Atomic weight 165.9. Its salts are rose-colored and give characteristic spectra. Its sesquioxide is called erbia."
erebus: "The son of Chaos and brother of Nox  who dwelt in Erebus."
erecter: "An erector; one who raises or builds."
erector: "An attachment to a microscope  telescope or other optical instrument for making the image erect instead of inverted."
erelong: "Before the /apse of a long time; soon; -- usually separated  ere long."
ergotic: "Pertaining to  or derived from ergot; as ergotic acid."
erica: "A genus of shrubby plants  including the heaths many of them producing beautiful flowers."
ericius: "The Vulgate rendering of the Hebrew word qip/d  which in the """"Authorized Version"""" is translated bittern and in the Revised Version porcupine."
erinite: "A hydrous arseniate of copper  of an emerald-green color; -- so called from Erin or Ireland where it occurs."
erinys: "An avenging deity; one of the Furies; sometimes  conscience personified."
erlking: "A personification  in German and Scandinavian mythology of a spirit natural power supposed to work mischief and ruin esp. to children."
ermine: "To clothe with  or as with ermine."
ermined: "Clothed or adorned with the fur of the ermine."
eroded: "Having the edge worn away so as to be jagged or irregularly toothed."
erode: "To eat into or away; to corrode; as  canker erodes the flesh."
erodent: "A medicine which eats away extraneous growths; a caustic."
erogate: "To lay out  as money; to deal out; to expend."
erose: "Jagged or irregularly toothed  as if nibbled out or gnawed."
erosion: "The state of being eaten away; corrosion; canker."
erosive: "That erodes or gradually eats away; tending to erode; corrosive."
eroteme: "A mark indicating a question; a note of interrogation."
errancy: "A wandering; state of being in error."
errand: "A special business intrusted to a messenger; something to be told or done by one sent somewhere for the purpose; often  a verbal message; a commission; as the servant was sent on an errand; to do an errand. Also one's purpose in going anywhere."
erratic: "Any stone or material that has been borne away from its original site by natural agencies; esp.  a large block or fragment of rock; a bowlder."
erratum: "An error or mistake in writing or printing."
erthine: "Causing or increasing secretion of nasal mucus."
error: "A fault of a player of the side in the field which results in failure to put out a player on the other side  or gives him an unearned base."
eruca: "An insect in the larval state; a caterpillar; a larva."
erucic: "Pertaining to  or derived from a genus of cruciferous Mediterranean herbs (Eruca or Brassica); as erucic acid a fatty acid resembling oleic acid and found in colza oil mustard oil etc."
erudite: "Characterized by extensive reading or knowledge; well instructed; learned."
erupt: "To cause to burst forth; to eject; as  to erupt lava."
escalop: "A bearing or a charge consisting of an escalop shell."
escape: "Leakage or loss of currents from the conducting wires  caused by defective insulation."
escarp: "To make into  or furnish with a steep slope like that of a scrap."
eschar: "In Ireland  one of the continuous mounds or ridges of gravelly and sandy drift which extend for many miles over the surface of the country. Similar ridges in Scotland are called kames or kams."
eschara: "A genus of Bryozoa which produce delicate corals  often incrusting like lichens but sometimes branched."
escort: "To attend with a view to guard and protect; to accompany as safeguard; to give honorable or ceremonious attendance to; -- used esp. with reference to journeys or excursions on land; as  to escort a public functionary or a lady; to escort a baggage wagon."
escot: "To pay the reckoning for; to support; to maintain."
escroll: "In modern heraldry  a similar ribbon on which the motto is inscribed."
escrow: "A deed  bond or other written engagement delivered to a third person to be held by him till some act is done or some condition is performed and then to be by him delivered to the grantee."
escuage: "Service of the shield  a species of knight service by which a tenant was bound to follow his lord to war at his own charge. It was afterward exchanged for a pecuniary satisfaction. Called also scutage."
esculic: "Pertaining to  or obtained from the horse-chestnut; as esculic acid."
esculin: "A glucoside obtained from the Aesculus hippocastanum  or horse-chestnut and characterized by its fine blue fluorescent solutions."
eserine: "An alkaloid found in the Calabar bean  and the seed of Physostigma venenosum; physostigmine. It is used in ophthalmic surgery for its effect in contracting the pupil."
eskimo: "One of a peculiar race inhabiting Arctic America and Greenland. In many respects the Eskimos resemble the Mongolian race."
esloin: "To remove; to banish; to withdraw; to avoid; to eloign."
esnecy: "A prerogative given to the eldest coparcener to choose first after an inheritance is divided."
esodic: "Conveying impressions from the surface of the body to the spinal cord; -- said of certain nerves. Opposed to exodic."
espadon: "A long  heavy two-handed and two-edged sword formerly used by Spanish foot soldiers and by executioners."
esparto: "A species of Spanish grass (Macrochloa tenacissima)  of which cordage shoes baskets etc. are made. It is also used for making paper."
espial: "One who espies; a spy; a scout."
esplees: "The full profits or products which ground or land yields  as the hay of the meadows the feed of the pasture the grain of arable fields the rents services and the like."
espouse: "To take to one's self with a view to maintain; to make one's own; to take up the cause of; to adopt; to embrace."
esquire: "To wait on as an esquire or attendant in public; to attend."
essay: "To test the value and purity of (metals); to assay. See Assay."
essene: "One of a sect among the Jews in the time of our Savior  remarkable for their strictness and abstinence."
esteem: "High estimation or value; great regard; favorable opinion  founded on supposed worth."
ester: "An ethereal salt  or compound ether consisting of an organic radical united with the residue of any oxygen acid organic or inorganic; thus the natural fats are esters of glycerin and the fatty acids oleic etc."
estoile: "A six-pointed star whose rays are wavy  instead of straight like those of a mullet."
estrade: "A portion of the floor of a room raised above the general level  as a place for a bed or a throne; a platform; a dais."
estray: "Any valuable animal  not wild found wandering from its owner; a stray."
estre: "The inward part of a building; the interior."
estreat: "To bring in to the exchequer  as a fine."
estrepe: "To strip or lay bare  as land of wood houses etc.; to commit waste."
estuary: "Belonging to  or formed in an estuary; as estuary strata."
estuate: "To boil up; to swell and rage; to be agitated."
estufa: "An assembly room in dwelling of the Pueblo Indians."
esurine: "A medicine which provokes appetites  or causes hunger."
etacism: "The pronunciation of the Greek / (eta) like the Italian e long  that is like a in the English word ate. See Itacism."
etagere: "A piece of furniture having a number of uninclosed shelves or stages  one above another for receiving articles of elegance or use."
etching: "An impression on paper  parchment or other material taken in ink from an etched plate."
etesian: "Periodical; annual; -- applied to winds which annually blow from the north over the Mediterranean  esp. the eastern part for an irregular period during July and August."
ethal: "A white waxy solid  C16H33.OH; -- called also cetylic alcohol. See Cetylic alcohol under Cetylic."
ethane: "A gaseous hydrocarbon  C2H6 forming a constituent of ordinary illuminating gas. It is the second member of the paraffin series and its most important derivatives are common alcohol aldehyde ether and acetic acid. Called also dimethyl."
ethenic: "Pertaining to  derived from. or resembling ethene or ethylene; as ethenic ether."
ethenyl: "A univalent hydrocarbon radical of the ethylene series  CH2:CH; -- called also vinyl. See Vinyl."
ether: "Any similar oxide of hydrocarbon radicals; as  amyl ether; valeric ether."
etherin: "A white  crystalline hydrocarbon regarded as a polymeric variety of ethylene obtained in heavy oil of wine the residue left after making ether; -- formerly called also concrete oil of wine."
etherol: "An oily hydrocarbon regarded as a polymeric variety of ethylene  produced with etherin."
ethical: "Of  or belonging to morals; treating of the moral feelings or duties; containing percepts of morality; moral; as ethic discourses or epistles; an ethical system; ethical philosophy."
ethics: "The science of human duty; the body of rules of duty drawn from this science; a particular system of principles and rules concerting duty  whether true or false; rules of practice in respect to a single class of human actions; as political or social ethics; medical ethics."
ethide: "Any compound of ethyl of a binary type; as  potassium ethide."
ethiops: "A black substance; -- formerly applied to various preparations of a black or very dark color."
ethyl: "A monatomic  hydrocarbon radical C2H5 of the paraffin series forming the essential radical of ethane and of common alcohol and ether."
ethylic: "Pertaining to  derived from or containing ethyl; as ethylic alcohol."
ethylin: "Any one of the several complex ethers of ethyl and glycerin."
etoolin: "A yellowish coloring matter found in plants grown in darkness  which is supposed to be an antecedent condition of chlorophyll."
etnean: "Pertaining to Etna  a volcanic mountain in Sicily."
etude: "A study; an exercise; a piece for practice of some special point of technical execution."
etymic: "Relating to the etymon; as  an etymic word."
eucalyn: "An unfermentable sugar  obtained as an uncrystallizable sirup by the decomposition of melitose; also obtained from a Tasmanian eucalyptus -- whence its name."
euchre: "To defeat or foil thoroughly in any scheme."
euchymy: "A good state of the blood and other fluids of the body."
euclase: "A brittle gem occurring in light green  transparent crystals affording a brilliant clinodiagonal cleavage. It is a silicate of alumina and glucina."
euclid: "A Greek geometer of the 3d century b. c.; also  his treatise on geometry and hence the principles of geometry in general."
eucrasy: "Such a due mixture of qualities in bodies as constitutes health or soundness."
eugenia: "A genus of myrtaceous plants  mostly of tropical countries and including several aromatic trees and shrubs among which are the trees which produce allspice and cloves of commerce."
eugenin: "A colorless  crystalline substance extracted from oil of cloves; -- called also clove camphor."
eugenol: "A colorless  aromatic liquid hydrocarbon C10H12O2 resembling the phenols and hence also called eugenic acid. It is found in the oils of pimento and cloves."
eulogy: "A speech or writing in commendation of the character or services of a person; as  a fitting eulogy to worth."
eunomy: "Equal law  or a well-adjusted constitution of government."
eupepsy: "Soundness of the nutritive or digestive organs; good concoction or digestion; -- opposed to dyspepsia."
euphony: "A pleasing or sweet sound; an easy  smooth enunciation of sounds; a pronunciation of letters and syllables which is pleasing to the ear."
euphroe: "A block or long slat of wood  perforated for the passage of the crowfoot or cords by which an awning is held up."
eupione: "A limpid  oily liquid obtained by the destructive distillation of various vegetable and animal substances; -- specifically an oil consisting largely of the higher hydrocarbons of the paraffin series."
eupnaea: "Normal breathing where arterialization of the blood is normal  in distinction from dyspnaea in which the blood is insufficiently arterialized."
eureka: "The exclamation attributed to Archimedes  who is said to have cried out """"Eureka! eureka!"""" (I have found it! I have found it!) upon suddenly discovering a method of finding out how much the gold of King Hiero's crown had been alloyed. Hence an expression of triumph concerning a discovery."
euripus: "A strait; a narrow tract of water  where the tide or a current flows and reflows with violence as the ancient fright of this name between Eubaea and Baeotia. Hence a flux and reflux."
euritte: "A compact feldspathic rock; felsite. See Felsite."
euryale: "A genus of ophiurans with much-branched arms."
euterpe: "A genus of palms  some species of which are elegant trees."
evade: "To attempt to escape; to practice artifice or sophistry  for the purpose of eluding."
evangel: "Good news; announcement of glad tidings; especially  the gospel or a gospel."
evanid: "Liable to vanish or disappear; faint; weak; evanescent; as  evanid color."
evasion: "The act of eluding or avoiding  particularly the pressure of an argument accusation charge or interrogation; artful means of eluding."
evasive: "Tending to evade  or marked by evasion; elusive; shuffling; avoiding by artifice."
evening: "The latter portion  as of life; the declining period as of strength or glory."
evener: "In vehicles  a swinging crossbar to the ends of which other crossbars or whiffletrees are hung to equalize the draught when two or three horses are used abreast."
evenly: "With an even  level or smooth surface; without roughness elevations or depression; uniformly; equally; comfortably; impartially; serenely."
everych: "each one; every one; each of two. See Every."
evernic: "Pertaining to Evernia  a genus of lichens; as evernic acid."
evert: "To turn outwards  or inside out as an intestine."
evident: "Clear to the vision; especially  clear to the understanding and satisfactory to the judgment; as the figure or color of a body is evident to the senses; the guilt of an offender can not always be made evident."
evilly: "In an evil manner; not well; ill."
evince: "To show in a clear manner; to prove beyond any reasonable doubt; to manifest; to make evident; to bring to light; to evidence."
evocate: "To call out or forth; to summon; to evoke."
evoke: "To call away; to remove from one tribunal to another."
evolute: "A curve from which another curve  called the involute or evolvent is described by the end of a thread gradually wound upon the former or unwound from it. See Involute. It is the locus of the centers of all the circles which are osculatory to the given curve or evolvent."
evolve: "To become open  disclosed or developed; to pass through a process of evolution."
exactly: "In an exact manner; precisely according to a rule  standard or fact; accurately; strictly; correctly; nicely."
exactor: "One who exacts or demands by authority or right; hence  an extortioner; also one unreasonably severe in injunctions or demands."
exalted: "Raised to lofty height; elevated; extolled; refined; dignified; sublime."
exalt: "To render pure or refined; to intensify or concentrate; as  to exalt the juices of bodies."
exalter: "One who exalts or raises to dignity."
examine: "To interrogate as in a judicial proceeding; to try or test by question; as  to examine a witness in order to elicit testimony a student to test his qualifications a bankrupt touching the state of his property etc."
example: "To set an example for; to give a precedent for; to exemplify; to give an instance of; to instance."
exarate: "To plow up; also  to engrave; to write."
exarch: "A viceroy; in Ravenna  the title of the viceroys of the Byzantine emperors; in the Eastern Church the superior over several monasteries; in the modern Greek Church a deputy of the patriarch who visits the clergy investigates ecclesiastical cases etc."
exceed: "To be more or greater; to be paramount."
excel: "To surpass others in good qualities  laudable actions or acquirements; to be distinguished by superiority; as to excel in mathematics or classics."
except: "Unless; if it be not so that."
excern: "To excrete; to throw off through the pores; as  fluids are excerned in perspiration."
excerpt: "An extract; a passage selected or copied from a book or record."
excess: "The degree or amount by which one thing or number exceeds another; remainder; as  the difference between two numbers is the excess of one over the other."
excise: "To cut out or off; to separate and remove; as  to excise a tumor."
excite: "To call forth or increase the vital activity of an organism  or any of its parts."
exclave: "A portion of a country which is separated from the main part and surrounded by politically alien territory."
exclude: "To thrust out or eject; to expel; as  to exclude young animals from the womb or from eggs."
excoct: "To boil out; to produce by boiling."
excrete: "To separate and throw off; to excrete urine."
excur: "To run out or forth; to extend."
excuse: "That which excuses; that which extenuates or justifies a fault."
excuss: "To seize and detain by law  as goods."
exeat: "A permission which a bishop grants to a priest to go out of his diocese."
exect: "To cut off or out. [Obs.] See Exsect."
exedra: "Any out-of-door seat in stone  large enough for several persons; esp. one of curved form."
exempt: "To release or deliver from some liability which others are subject to; to except or excuse from he operation of a law; to grant immunity to; to free from obligation; to release; as  to exempt from military duty or from jury service; to exempt from fear or pain."
exequy: "A funeral rite (usually in the plural); the ceremonies of burial; obsequies; funeral procession."
exergue: "The small space beneath the base line of a subject engraved on a coin or medal. It usually contains the date  place engraver's name etc. or other subsidiary matter."
exert: "To put forth  as the result or exercise of effort; to bring to bear; to do or perform."
exesion: "The act of eating out or through."
exeunt: "They go out  or retire from the scene; as exeunt all except Hamlet. See 1st Exit."
exhale: "To rise or be given off  as vapor; to pass off or vanish."
exhaust: "The foul air let out of a room through a register or pipe provided for the purpose."
exhibit: "A document produced and identified in court for future use as evidence."
exhume: "To dig out of the ground; to take out of a place of burial; to disinter."
exigent: "The name of a writ in proceedings before outlawry."
exilic: "Pertaining to exile or banishment  esp. to that of the Jews in Babylon."
exist: "To live; to have life or the functions of vitality; as  men can not exist water nor fishes on land."
exocarp: "The outer portion of a fruit  as the flesh of a peach or the rind of an orange. See Illust. of Drupe."
exode: "An afterpiece of a comic description  either a farce or a travesty."
exodic: "Conducting influences from the spinal cord outward; -- said of the motor or efferent nerves. Opposed to esodic."
exodus: "The second of the Old Testament  which contains the narrative of the departure of the Israelites from Egypt."
exogamy: "The custom  or tribal law which prohibits marriage between members of the same tribe; marriage outside of the tribe; -- opposed to endogamy."
exogen: "A plant belonging to one of the greater part of the vegetable kingdom  and which the plants are characterized by having c wood bark and pith the wood forming a layer between the other two and increasing if at all by the animal addition of a new layer to the outside next to the bark. The leaves are commonly netted-veined and the number of cotyledons is two or very rarely several in a whorl. Cf. Endogen."
exogyra: "A genus of Cretaceous fossil shells allied to oysters."
exrable: "Capable of being moved by entreaty; pitiful; tender."
exorate: "To persuade  or to gain by entreaty."
exotery: "That which is obvious  public or common."
exotic: "Anything of foreign origin; something not of native growth  as a plant a word a custom."
expand: "To become widely opened  spread apart dilated distended or enlarged; as flowers expand in the spring; metals expand by heat; the heart expands with joy."
expire: "To burst forth; to fly out with a blast."
explode: "To drive out with violence and noise  as by powder."
exploit: "Hence: To draw an illegitimate profit from; to speculate on; to put upon."
explore: "To search through or into; to penetrate or range over for discovery; to examine thoroughly; as  to explore new countries or seas; to explore the depths of science."
expone: "To expound; to explain; also  to expose; to imperil."
export: "That which is exported; a commodity conveyed from one country or State to another in the way of traffic; -- used chiefly in the plural  exports."
expose: "A formal recital or exposition of facts; exposure  or revelation of something which some one wished to keep concealed."
expound: "To lay open the meaning of; to explain; to clear of obscurity; to interpret; as  to expound a text of Scripture a law a word a meaning or a riddle."
express: "To send by express messenger; to forward by special opportunity  or through the medium of an express; as to express a package."
expugn: "To take by assault; to storm; to overcome; to vanquish; as  to expugn cities; to expugn a person by arguments."
expunge: "To strike out; to wipe out or destroy; to annihilate; as  to expugne an offense."
exscind: "To cut off; to separate or expel from union; to extirpate."
exsect: "The removal by operation of a portion of a limb; particularly  the removal of a portion of a bone in the vicinity of a joint; the act or process of cutting out."
extancy: "The state of rising above others; a projection."
extend: "To value  as lands taken by a writ of extent in satisfaction of a debt; to assign by writ of extent."
extent: "A process of execution by which the lands and goods of a debtor are valued and delivered to the creditor."
externe: "An officer in attendance upon a hospital  but not residing in it; esp. one who cares for the out-patients."
extine: "The outer membrane of the grains of pollen of flowering plants."
extol: "To elevate by praise; to eulogize; to praise; to magnify; as  to extol virtue; to extol an act or a person."
extra-: "A Latin preposition  denoting beyond outside of; -- often used in composition as a prefix signifying outside of beyond besides or in addition to what is denoted by the word to which it is prefixed."
extra: "Something in addition to what is due  expected or customary; something in addition to the regular charge or compensation or for which an additional charge is made; as at European hotels lights are extras."
extract: "A draught or copy of writing; certified copy of the proceedings in an action and the judgement therein  with an order for execution."
extreme: "The first or the last term of a proportion or series."
extrude: "To thrust out; to force  press or push out; to expel; to drive off or away."
exude: "To flow from a body through the pores  or by a natural discharge as juice."
exult: "To be in high spirits; figuratively  to leap for joy; to rejoice in triumph or exceedingly; to triumph; as an exulting heart."
exuviae: "The fossil shells and other remains which animals have left in the strata of the earth."
ex-voto: "An offering to a church in fulfillment of a vow."
eyalet: "Formerly  one of the administrative divisions or provinces of the Ottoman Empire; -- now called a vilayet."
eyeball: "The ball or globe of the eye."
eyebar: "A bar with an eye at one or both ends."
eyebolt: "A bolt which a looped head  or an opening in the head."
eyebrow: "The brow or hairy arch above the eye."
eyecup: "A small oval porcelain or glass cup  having a rim curved to fit the orbit of the eye. it is used in the application of liquid remedies to eyes; -- called also eyeglass."
eyeful: "Filling or satisfying the eye; visible; remarkable."
eyehole: "A circular opening to recive a hook  cord ring or rope; an eyelet."
eyelash: "A hair of the fringe on the edge of the eyelid."
eyelet: "A metal ring or grommet  or short metallic tube the ends of which can be bent outward and over to fasten it in place; -- used to line an eyelet hole."
eyelid: "The cover of the eye; that portion of movable skin with which an animal covers or uncovers the eyeball at pleasure."
eyeshot: "Range  reach or glance of the eye; view; sight; as to be out of eyeshot."
eyesore: "Something offensive to the eye or sight; a blemish."
fabella: "One of the small sesamoid bones situated behind the condyles of the femur  in some mammals."
fabian: "Of  pertaining to or in the manner of the Roman general Quintus Fabius Maximus Verrucosus; cautious; dilatory; avoiding a decisive contest."
fable: "To feign; to invent; to devise  and speak of as true or real; to tell of falsely."
fabler: "A writer of fables; a fabulist; a dealer in untruths or falsehoods."
fabliau: "One of the metrical tales of the Trouveres  or early poets of the north of France."
fabrile: "Pertaining to a workman  or to work in stone metal wood etc.; as fabrile skill."
facade: "The front of a building; esp.  the principal front having some architectural pretensions. Thus a church is said to have its facade unfinished though the interior may be in use."
faced: "Having (such) a face  or (so many) faces; as smooth-faced two-faced."
facing: "The movement of soldiers by turning on their heels to the right  left or about; -- chiefly in the pl."
faser: "A blow in the face  as in boxing; hence any severe or stunning check or defeat as in controversy."
facet: "To cut facets or small faces upon; as  to facet a diamond."
facial: "Of or pertaining to the face; as  the facial artery vein or nerve."
facies: "The face of a bird  or the front of the head excluding the bill."
facile: "Ready; quick; expert; as  he is facile in expedients; he wields a facile pen."
facto: "In fact; by the act or fact."
factory: "A building  or collection of buildings appropriated to the manufacture of goods; the place where workmen are employed in fabricating goods wares or utensils; a manufactory; as a cotton factory."
faculae: "Groups of small shining spots on the surface of the sun which are brighter than the other parts of the photosphere. They are generally seen in the neighborhood of the dark spots  and are supposed to be elevated portions of the photosphere."
faculty: "The body of person to whom are intrusted the government and instruction of a college or university  or of one of its departments; the president professors and tutors in a college."
faded: "That has lost freshness  color or brightness; grown dim."
fading: "An Irish dance; also  the burden of a song."
fadge: "A small flat loaf or thick cake; also  a fagot."
faeces: "Excrement; ordure; also  settlings; sediment after infusion or distillation."
fagging: "Laborious drudgery; esp.  the acting as a drudge for another at an English school."
fagend: "The refuse or meaner part of anything."
fagot: "To make a fagot of; to bind together in a fagot or bundle; also  to collect promiscuously."
fagotto: "The bassoon; -- so called from being divided into parts for ease of carriage  making as it were a small fagot."
faham: "The leaves of an orchid (Angraecum fragrans)  of the islands of Bourbon and Mauritius used (in France) as a substitute for Chinese tea."
faience: "Glazed earthenware; esp.  that which is decorated in color."
failing: "The act of becoming insolvent of bankrupt."
faille: "A soft silk  heavier than a foulard and not glossy."
faint: "To cause to faint or become dispirited; to depress; to weaken."
faints: "The impure spirit which comes over first and last in the distillation of whisky; -- the former being called the strong faints  and the latter which is much more abundant the weak faints. This crude spirit is much impregnated with fusel oil."
fairing: "A present; originally  one given or purchased at a fair."
fairway: "The navigable part of a river  bay etc. through which vessels enter or depart; the part of a harbor or channel ehich is kept open and unobstructed for the passage of vessels."
faithed: "Having faith or a faith; honest; sincere."
faitour: "A doer or actor; particularly  an evil doer; a scoundrel."
fakir: "An Oriental religious ascetic or begging monk."
falcade: "The action of a horse  when he throws himself on his haunches two or three times bending himself as it were in very quick curvets."
falcer: "One of the mandibles of a spider."
faldage: "A privilege of setting up  and moving about folds for sheep in any fields within manors in order to manure them; -- often reserved to himself by the lord of the manor."
faldfee: "A fee or rent paid by a tenant for the privilege of faldage on his own ground."
fallacy: "An argument  or apparent argument which professes to be decisive of the matter at issue while in reality it is not; a sophism."
faller: "A part which acts by falling  as a stamp in a fulling mill or the device in a spinning machine to arrest motion when a thread breaks."
fallow: "To plow  harrow and break up as land without seeding for the purpose of destroying weeds and insects and rendering it mellow; as it is profitable to fallow cold strong clayey land."
falsely: "In a false manner; erroneously; not truly; perfidiously or treacherously."
falsify: "To tell lies; to violate the truth."
falsism: "That which is evidently false; an assertion or statement the falsity of which is plainly apparent; -- opposed to truism."
falsity: "That which is false; falsehood; a lie; a false assertion."
falter: "Hesitation; trembling; feebleness; an uncertain or broken sound; as  a slight falter in her voice."
faluns: "A series of strata  of the Middle Tertiary period of France abounding in shells and used by Lyell as the type of his Miocene subdivision."
family: "A group of organisms  either animal or vegetable related by certain points of resemblance in structure or development more comprehensive than a genus because it is usually based on fewer or less pronounced points of likeness. In zoology a family is less comprehesive than an order; in botany it is often considered the same thing as an order."
famine: "General scarcity of food; dearth; a want of provisions; destitution."
famous: "Celebrated in fame or public report; renowned; mach talked of; distinguished in story; -- used in either a good or a bad sense  chiefly the former; often followed by for; as famous for erudition for eloquence for military skill; a famous pirate."
fanal: "A lighthouse  or the apparatus placed in it for giving light."
fanatic: "A person affected by excessive enthusiasm  particularly on religious subjects; one who indulges wild and extravagant notions of religion."
fancier: "One who fancies or has a special liking for  or interest in a particular object or class or objects; hence one who breeds and keeps for sale birds and animals; as bird fancier dog fancier etc."
fanega: "A dry measure in Spain and Spanish America  varying from 1/ to 2/ bushels; also a measure of land."
fanfare: "A flourish of trumpets  as in coming into the lists etc.; also a short and lively air performed on hunting horns during the chase."
fanged: "Having fangs or tusks; as  a fanged adder. Also used figuratively."
fangled: "New made; hence  gaudy; showy; vainly decorated. [Obs. except with the prefix new.] See Newfangled."
fangot: "A quantity of wares  as raw silk etc. from one hundred weight."
fanion: "A small flag for marking the stations in surveying."
fanlike: "folded up like a fan  as certain leaves; plicate."
fanner: "A fan wheel; a fan blower. See under Fan."
fanon: "A term applied to various articles  as: (a) A peculiar striped scarf worn by the pope at mass and by eastern bishops. (b) A maniple."
fantail: "Any bird of the Australian genus Rhipidura  in which the tail is spread in the form of a fan during flight. They belong to the family of flycatchers."
fantast: "One whose manners or ideas are fantastic."
fantasy: "To have a fancy for; to be pleased with; to like; to fancy."
farad: "The standard unit of electrical capacity; the capacity of a condenser whose charge  having an electro-motive force of one volt is equal to the amount of electricity which with the same electromotive force passes through one ohm in one second; the capacity which charged with one coulomb gives an electro-motive force of one volt."
faradic: "Of or pertaining to Michael Faraday  the distinguished electrician; -- applied especially to induced currents of electricity as produced by certain forms of inductive apparatus on account of Faraday's investigations of their laws."
farce: "Ridiculous or empty show; as  a mere farce."
farcy: "A contagious disease of horses  associated with painful ulcerating enlargements esp. upon the head and limbs. It is of the same nature as glanders and is often fatal. Called also farcin and farcimen."
farlie: "An unusual or unexpected thing; a wonder. See Fearly."
farmer: "The lord of the field  or one who farms the lot and cope of the crown."
farmery: "The buildings and yards necessary for the business of a farm; a homestead."
farness: "The state of being far off; distance; remoteness."
faroese: "An inhabitant  or collectively inhabitants of the Faroe islands."
far-off: "Remote; as  the far-off distance. Cf. Far-off under Far adv."
farrago: "A mass composed of various materials confusedly mixed; a medley; a mixture."
farrier: "To practice as a farrier; to carry on the trade of a farrier."
farrow: "Not producing young in a given season or year; -- said only of cows."
farfow: "To bring forth (young); -- said only of swine."
farse: "An addition to  or a paraphrase of some part of the Latin service in the vernacular; -- common in English before the Reformation."
fasces: "A bundle of rods  having among them an ax with the blade projecting borne before the Roman magistrates as a badge of their authority."
fascet: "A wire basket on the end of a rod to carry glass bottles  etc. to the annealing furnace; also an iron rod to be thrust into the mouths of bottles and used for the same purpose; -- called also pontee and punty."
fascine: "A cylindrical bundle of small sticks of wood  bound together used in raising batteries filling ditches strengthening ramparts and making parapets; also in revetments for river banks and in mats for dams jetties etc."
fasten: "To fix one's self; to take firm hold; to clinch; to cling."
fatal: "Causing death or destruction; deadly; mortal; destructive; calamitous; as  a fatal wound; a fatal disease; a fatal day; a fatal error."
fatally: "In a manner issuing in death or ruin; mortally; destructively; as  fatally deceived or wounded."
fathead: "A labroid food fish of California; the redfish."
fathom: "The measure by a sounding line; especially  to sound the depth of; to penetrate measure and comprehend; to get to the bottom of."
fatigue: "To weary with labor or any bodily or mental exertion; to harass with toil; to exhaust the strength or endurance of; to tire."
fatling: "A calf  lamb kid or other young animal fattened for slaughter; a fat animal; -- said of such animals as are used for food."
fatten: "To grow fat or corpulent; to grow plump  thick or fleshy; to be pampered."
fatty: "Containing fat  or having the qualities of fat; greasy; gross; as a fatty substance."
fatuous: "Without reality; illusory  like the ignis fatuus."
faucal: "Pertaining to the fauces  or opening of the throat; faucial; esp. (Phon.) produced in the fauces as certain deep guttural sounds found in the Semitic and some other languages."
faucet: "The enlarged end of a section of pipe which receives the spigot end of the next section."
faugh: "An exclamation of contempt  disgust or abhorrence."
fauld: "The arch over the dam of a blast furnace; the tymp arch."
fault: "To err; to blunder  to commit a fault; to do wrong."
faulty: "Guilty of a fault  or of faults; hence blamable; worthy of censure."
fauna: "The animals of any given area or epoch; as  the fauna of America; fossil fauna; recent fauna."
faunist: "One who describes the fauna of country; a naturalist."
fautor: "A favorer; a patron; one who gives countenance or support; an abettor."
favella: "A group of spores arranged without order and covered with a thin gelatinous envelope  as in certain delicate red algae."
favor: "To resemble in features; to have the aspect or looks of; as  the child favors his father."
favored: "Having a certain favor or appearance; featured; as  well-favored; hard-favored etc."
favorer: "One who favors; one who regards with kindness or friendship; a well-wisher; one who assists or promotes success or prosperity."
favose: "Of or pertaining to the disease called favus."
favus: "A tile or flagstone cut into an hexagonal shape to produce a honeycomb pattern  as in a pavement; -- called also favas and sectila."
fealty: "Fidelity; constancy; faithfulness  as of a friend to a friend or of a wife to her husband."
fearful: "Inspiring fear or awe; exciting apprehension or terror; terrible; frightful; dreadful."
feast: "To delight; to gratify; as  to feast the soul."
feather: "To have the appearance of a feather or of feathers; to be or to appear in feathery form."
feaze: "A state of anxious or fretful excitement; worry; vexation."
febrile: "Pertaining to fever; indicating fever  or derived from it; as febrile symptoms; febrile action."
fecal: "relating to  or containing dregs feces or ordeure; faecal."
fecial: "Pertaining to heralds  declarations of war and treaties of peace; as fecial law."
feeding: "That which furnishes or affords food  especially for animals; pasture land."
feeder: "A device for supplying steam boilers with water as needed."
feeling: "That quality of a work of art which embodies the mental emotion of the artist  and is calculated to affect similarly the spectator."
feeler: "Anything  as a proposal observation etc. put forth or thrown out in order to ascertain the views of others; something tentative."
feere: "A consort  husband or wife; a companion; a fere."
feigned: "Not real or genuine; pretended; counterfeit; insincere; false."
feint: "To make a feint  or mock attack."
feitsui: "The Chinese name for a highly prized variety of pale green jade. See Jade."
feline: "Characteristic of cats; sly; stealthy; treacherous; as  a feline nature; feline manners."
felis: "A genus of carnivorous mammals  including the domestic cat the lion tiger panther and similar animals."
fellah: "A peasant or cultivator of the soil among the Egyptians  Syrians etc."
feller: "An appliance to a sewing machine for felling a seam."
fellow: "To suit with; to pair with; to match."
felly: "The exterior wooden rim  or a segment of the rim of a wheel supported by the spokes."
felon: "Characteristic of a felon; malignant; fierce; malicious; cruel; traitorous; disloyal."
felonry: "A body of felons; specifically  the convict population of a penal colony."
felony: "A heinous crime; especially  a crime punishable by death or imprisonment."
felsite: "A finegrained rock  flintlike in fracture consisting essentially of orthoclase feldspar with occasional grains of quartz."
felting: "The act of splitting timber by the felt grain."
felter: "To clot or mat together like felt."
felucca: "A small  swift-sailing vessel propelled by oars and lateen sails -- once common in the Mediterranean."
felwort: "A European herb (Swertia perennis) of the Gentian family."
female: "Having pistils and no stamens; pistillate; or  in cryptogamous plants capable of receiving fertilization."
femoral: "Pertaining to the femur or thigh; as  the femoral artery."
femur: "The proximal segment of the hind limb containing the thigh bone; the thigh. See Coxa."
fence: "Hence  to fight or dispute in the manner of fencers that is by thrusting guarding parrying etc."
fencing: "The aggregate of the fences put up for inclosure or protection; as  the fencing of a farm."
fencer: "One who fences; one who teaches or practices the art of fencing with sword or foil."
fender: "Anything set up to protect an exposed angle  as of a house from damage by carriage wheels."
fengite: "A kind of marble or alabaster  sometimes used for windows on account of its transparency."
fenks: "The refuse whale blubber  used as a manure and in the manufacture of Prussian blue."
fennec: "A small  African foxlike animal (Vulpes zerda) of a pale fawn color remarkable for the large size of its ears."
fennel: "A perennial plant of the genus Faeniculum (F. vulgare)  having very finely divided leaves. It is cultivated in gardens for the agreeable aromatic flavor of its seeds."
fenny: "Pertaining to  or inhabiting a fen; abounding in fens; swampy; boggy."
feodary: "An ancient officer of the court of wards."
feoffee: "The person to whom a feoffment is made; the person enfeoffed."
feoffer: "One who enfeoffs or grants a fee."
ferae: "A group of mammals which formerly included the Carnivora  Insectivora Marsupialia and lemurs but is now often restricted to the Carnivora."
ferding: "A measure of land mentioned in Domesday Book. It is supposed to have consisted of a few acres only."
feria: "A week day  esp. a day which is neither a festival nor a fast."
ferial: "Belonging to any week day  esp. to a day that is neither a festival nor a fast."
ferine: "A wild beast; a beast of prey."
ferme: "Rent for a farm; a farm; also  an abode; a place of residence; as he let his land to ferm."
ferment: "To be agitated or excited by violent emotions."
feroher: "A symbol of the solar deity  found on monuments exhumed in Babylon Nineveh etc."
ferrara: "A sword bearing the mark of one of the Ferrara family of Italy. These swords were highly esteemed in England and Scotland in the 16th and 17th centuries."
ferret: "The iron used for trying the melted glass to see if is fit to work  and for shaping the rings at the mouths of bottles."
ferri-: "A combining form indicating ferric iron as an ingredient; as  ferricyanide."
ferric: "Pertaining to  derived from or containing iron. Specifically (Chem.) denoting those compounds in which iron has a higher valence than in the ferrous compounds; as ferric oxide; ferric acid."
ferro-: "A prefix  or combining form indicating ferrous iron as an ingredient; as ferrocyanide."
ferrous: "Pertaining to  or derived from iron; -- especially used of compounds of iron in which the iron has its lower valence; as ferrous sulphate."
ferrugo: "A disease of plants caused by fungi  commonly called the rust from its resemblance to iron rust in color."
ferrule: "A bushing for expanding the end of a flue to fasten it tightly in the tube plate  or for partly filling up its mouth."
ferry: "A franchise or right to maintain a vessel for carrying passengers and freight across a river  bay etc. charging tolls."
ferula: "The imperial scepter in the Byzantine or Eastern Empire."
ferulic: "Pertaining to  or derived from asafetida (Ferula asafoetida); as ferulic acid."
fervent: "Warm in feeling; ardent in temperament; earnest; full of fervor; zealous; glowing."
fervor: "Intensity of feeling or expression; glowing ardor; passion; holy zeal; earnestness."
fescue: "To use a fescue  or teach with a fescue."
fesse: "A band drawn horizontally across the center of an escutcheon  and containing in breadth the third part of it; one of the nine honorable ordinaries."
festal: "Of or pertaining to a holiday or a feast; joyous; festive."
festive: "Pertaining to  or becoming a feast; festal; joyous; gay; mirthful; sportive."
festoon: "To form in festoons  or to adorn with festoons."
fetal: "Pertaining to  or connected with a fetus; as fetal circulation; fetal membranes."
fetch: "The apparation of a living person; a wraith."
fetlock: "The cushionlike projection  bearing a tuft of long hair on the back side of the leg above the hoof of the horse and similar animals. Also the joint of the limb at this point (between the great pastern bone and the metacarpus) or the tuft of hair."
fetter: "To restrain from motion; to impose restraints on; to confine; to enchain; as  fettered by obligations."
fetus: "The young or embryo of an animal in the womb  or in the egg; often restricted to the later stages in the development of viviparous and oviparous animals embryo being applied to the earlier stages."
fetwah: "A written decision of a Turkish mufti on some point of law."
feudal: "Consisting of  or founded upon feuds or fiefs; embracing tenures by military services; as the feudal system."
feudist: "A writer on feuds; a person versed in feudal law."
feuter: "To set close; to fix in rest  as a spear."
fever: "To put into a fever; to affect with fever; as  a fevered lip."
fiants: "The dung of the fox  wolf boar or badger."
fiasco: "A complete or ridiculous failure  esp. of a musical performance or of any pretentious undertaking."
fibre: "A tough vegetable fiber used as a substitute for bristles in making brushes. The piassava and the ixtle are both used under this name."
fibril: "A small fiber; the branch of a fiber; a very slender thread; a fibrilla."
fibrin: "An albuminous body  resembling animal fibrin in composition found in cereal grains and similar seeds; vegetable fibrin."
fibroin: "A variety of gelatin; the chief ingredient of raw silk  extracted as a white amorphous mass."
fibroma: "A tumor consisting mainly of fibrous tissue  or of same modification of such tissue."
fibrous: "Containing  or consisting of fibers; as the fibrous coat of the cocoanut; the fibrous roots of grasses."
fichu: "A light cape  usually of lace worn by women to cover the neck and throat and extending to the shoulders."
fickle: "Not fixed or firm; liable to change; unstable; of a changeable mind; not firm in opinion or purpose; inconstant; capricious; as  Fortune's fickle wheel."
fictile: "Molded  or capable of being molded into form by art; relating to pottery or to molding in any soft material."
fiction: "Any like assumption made for convenience  as for passing more rapidly over what is not disputed and arriving at points really at issue."
fictor: "An artist who models or forms statues and reliefs in any plastic material."
ficus: "A genus of trees or shrubs  one species of which (F. Carica) produces the figs of commerce; the fig tree."
fidalgo: "The lowest title of nobility in Portugal  corresponding to that of Hidalgo in Spain."
fiddler: "The common European sandpiper (Tringoides hypoleucus); -- so called because it continually oscillates its body."
fides: "Faith personified as a goddess; the goddess of faith."
fidget: "A general nervous restlessness  manifested by incessant changes of position; dysphoria."
fidia: "A genus of small beetles  of which one species (the grapevine Fidia F. longipes) is very injurious to vines in America."
field: "To catch  stop throw etc. (the ball) as a fielder."
fielder: "A ball payer who stands out in the field to catch or stop balls."
fiend: "An implacable or malicious foe; one who is diabolically wicked or cruel; an infernal being; -- applied specifically to the devil or a demon."
fiery: "heated by fire  or as if by fire; burning hot; parched; feverish."
fifteen: "A symbol representing fifteen units  as 15 or xv."
fifth: "The interval of three tones and a semitone  embracing five diatonic degrees of the scale; the dominant of any key."
fifthly: "In the fifth place; as the fifth in order."
fifty: "A symbol representing fifty units  as 50 or l."
fight: "A screen for the combatants in ships."
fighter: "One who fights; a combatant; a warrior."
figment: "An invention; a fiction; something feigned or imagined."
figure: "To calculate; to contrive; to scheme; as  he is figuring to secure the nomination."
figwort: "A genus of herbaceous plants (Scrophularia)  mostly found in the north temperate zones. See Brownwort."
filacer: "A former officer in the English Court of Common Pleas; -- so called because he filed the writs on which he made out process."
filar: "Of or pertaining to a thread or line; characterized by threads stretched across the field of view; as  a filar microscope; a filar micrometer."
filaria: "A genus of slender  nematode worms of many species parasitic in various animals. See Guinea worm."
filbert: "The fruit of the Corylus Avellana or hazel. It is an oval nut  containing a kernel that has a mild farinaceous oily taste agreeable to the palate."
filch: "To steal or take privily (commonly  that which is of little value); to pilfer."
filing: "A fragment or particle rubbed off by the act of filing; as  iron filings."
filiate: "To adopt as son or daughter; to establish filiation between."
filicic: "Pertaining to  or derived from ferns; as filicic acid."
filiety: "The relation of a son to a father; sonship; -- the correlative of paternity."
filling: "Prepared wort added to ale to cleanse it."
fillet: "To bind  furnish or adorn with a fillet."
filth: "Anything that sullies or defiles the moral character; corruption; pollution."
filthy: "Defiled with filth  whether material or moral; nasty; dirty; polluted; foul; impure; obscene."
fimbria: "A band of white matter bordering the hippocampus in the brain."
finned: "Having a fin  or fins or anything resembling a fin."
finable: "Liable or subject to a fine; as  a finable person or offense."
final: "Respecting an end or object to be gained; respecting the purpose or ultimate end in view."
finale: "The closing part  piece or scene in any public performance or exhibition."
finance: "The science of raising and expending the public revenue."
finback: "Any whale of the genera Sibbaldius  Balaenoptera and allied genera of the family Balaenopteridae characterized by a prominent fin on the back. The common finbacks of the New England coast are Sibbaldius tectirostris and S. tuberosus."
finch: "A small singing bird of many genera and species  belonging to the family Fringillidae."
found: "To take the ffirst steps or measures in erecting or building up; to furnish the materials for beginning; to begin to raise; to originate; as  to found a college; to found a family."
finding: "The result of a judicial examination or inquiry  especially into some matter of fact; a verdict; as the finding of a jury."
finder: "One who  or that which finds; specifically (Astron.) a small telescope of low power and large field of view attached to a larger telescope for the purpose of finding an object more readily."
fining: "That which is used to refine; especially  a preparation of isinglass gelatin etc. for clarifying beer."
finery: "A charcoal hearth or furnace for the conversion of cast iron into wrought iron  or into iron suitable for puddling."
finesse: "To attempt  when second or third player to make a lower card answer the purpose of a higher when an intermediate card is out risking the chance of its being held by the opponent yet to play."

fraught: "To freight; to load; to burden; to fill; to crowd."
fraxin: "A colorless crystalline substance  regarded as a glucoside and found in the bark of the ash (Fraxinus) and along with esculin in the bark of the horse-chestnut. It shows a delicate fluorescence in alkaline solutions; -- called also paviin."
fraying: "The skin which a deer frays from his horns."
freak: "A sudden causeless change or turn of the mind; a whim of fancy; a capricious prank; a vagary or caprice."
freckle: "To become covered or marked with freckles; to be spotted."
freckly: "Full of or marked with freckles; sprinkled with spots; freckled."
freely: "In a free manner; without restraint or compulsion; abundantly; gratuitously."
freeman: "A member of a corporation  company or city possessing certain privileges; a member of a borough town or State who has the right to vote at elections. See Liveryman."
freeze: "The act of congealing  or the state of being congealed."
freezer: "One who  or that which cools or freezes as a refrigerator or the tub and can used in the process of freezing ice cream."
freight: "To load with goods  as a ship or vehicle of any kind for transporting them from one place to another; to furnish with freight; as to freight a ship; to freight a car."
frenzy: "To affect with frenzy; to drive to madness"
freshen: "To grow brisk or strong; as  the wind freshens."
freshet: "A flood or overflowing of a stream caused by heavy rains or melted snow; a sudden inundation."
freshly: "In a fresh manner; vigorously; newly  recently; brightly; briskly; coolly; as freshly gathered; freshly painted; the wind blows freshly."
fretted: "Interlaced one with another; -- said of charges and ordinaries."
fretful: "Disposed to fret; ill-humored; peevish; angry; in a state of vexation; as  a fretful temper."
frett: "A vitreous compound  used by potters in glazing consisting of lime silica borax lead and soda."
fretten: "Rubbed; marked; as  pock-fretten marked with the smallpox."
fretum: "A strait  or arm of the sea."
freya: "The daughter of Njord  and goddess of love and beauty; the Scandinavian Venus; -- in Teutonic myths confounded with Frigga but in Scandinavian distinct."
friable: "Easily crumbled  pulverized or reduced to powder."
fricace: "An unguent; also  the act of rubbing with the unguent."
friday: "The sixth day of the week  following Thursday and preceding Saturday."
friend: "To act as the friend of; to favor; to countenance; to befriend."
friesic: "The language of the Frisians  a Teutonic people formerly occupying a large part of the coast of Holland and Northwestern Germany. The modern dialects of Friesic are spoken chiefly in the province of Friesland and on some of the islands near the coast of Germany and Denmark."
frieze: "To make a nap on (cloth); to friz. See Friz  v. t. 2."
friezed: "Gathered  or having the map gathered into little tufts knots or protuberances. Cf. Frieze v. t. and Friz v. t. 2."
friezer: "One who  or that which friezes or frizzes."
frigga: "The wife of Odin and mother of the gods; the supreme goddess; the Juno of the Valhalla. Cf. Freya."
fright: "To alarm suddenly; to shock by causing sudden fear; to terrify; to scare."
frigid: "Wanting natural heat or vigor sufficient to excite the generative power; impotent."
frill: "A border or edging secured at one edge and left free at the other  usually fluted or crimped like a very narrow flounce."
fringe: "To adorn the edge of with a fringe or as with a fringe."
fripper: "One who deals in frippery or in old clothes."
frisian: "A native or inhabitant of Friesland; also  the language spoken in Friesland. See Friesic n."
frisk: "To leap  skip dance or gambol in fronc and gayety."
frisker: "One who frisks; one who leaps of dances in gayety; a wanton; an inconstant or unsettled person."
frisket: "The light frame which holds the sheet of paper to the tympan in printing."
frisure: "The dressing of the hair by crisping or curling."
frith: "A small field taken out of a common  by inclosing it; an inclosure."
fritter: "To break into small pieces or fragments."
frizel: "A movable furrowed piece of steel struck by the flint  to throw sparks into the pan in an early form of flintlock."
frizzle: "A curl; a lock of hair crisped."
frock: "To make a monk of. Cf. Unfrock."
frogbit: "An American plant (Limnobium Spongia)  with similar habits."
frogged: "Provided or ornamented with frogs; as  a frogged coat. See Frog n. 4."
frolic: "To play wild pranks; to play tricks of levity  mirth and gayety; to indulge in frolicsome play; to sport."
frond: "The organ formed by the combination or union into one body of stem and leaf  and often bearing the fructification; as the frond of a fern or of a lichen or seaweed; also the peculiar leaf of a palm tree."
fronde: "A political party in France  during the minority of Louis XIV. who opposed the government and made war upon the court party."
frons: "The forehead; the part of the cranium between the orbits and the vertex."
front: "To have or turn the face or front in any direction; as  the house fronts toward the east."
fronted: "Formed with a front; drawn up in line."
frontal: "The frontal bone  or one of the two frontal bones of the cranium."
fronto-: "A combining form signifying relating to the forehead or the frontal bone; as  fronto-parietal relating to the frontal and the parietal bones; fronto-nasal etc."
frost: "To roughen or sharpen  as the nail heads or calks of horseshoes so as to fit them for frosty weather."
frosted: "Covered with hoarfrost or anything resembling hoarfrost; ornamented with frosting; also  frost-bitten; as a frosted cake; frosted glass."
frosty: "Appearing as if covered with hoarfrost; white; gray-haired; as  a frosty head."
frote: "To rub or wear by rubbing; to chafe."
froth: "To throw up or out spume  foam or bubbles; to foam; as beer froths; a horse froths."
frothy: "Of the nature of froth; light; empty; unsubstantial; as  a frothy speaker or harangue."
frounce: "An affection in hawks  in which white spittle gathers about the hawk's bill."
frouzy: "Fetid  musty; rank; disordered and offensive to the smell or sight; slovenly; dingy. See Frowzy."
froward: "Not willing to yield or compIy with what is required or is reasonable; perverse; disobedient; peevish; as  a froward child."
frowey: "Working smoothly  or without splitting; -- said of timber."
frown: "Any expression of displeasure; as  the frowns of Providence; the frowns of Fortune."
fructed: "Bearing fruit; -- said of a tree or plant so represented upon an escutcheon."
frugal: "Obtained by  or appropriate to economy; as a frugal fortune."
fruit'y: "Having the odor  taste or appearance of fruit; also fruitful."
frump: "A cross  old-fashioned person; esp. an old woman; a gossip."
frush: "A discharge of a fetid or ichorous matter from the frog of a horse's foot; -- also caled thrush."
frustum: "One of the drums of the shaft of a column."
frutex: "A plant having a woody  durable stem but less than a tree; a shrub."
frying: "The process denoted by the verb fry."
fubsy: "Plump; chubby; short and stuffy; as a fubsy sofa."
fucated: "Painted; disguised with paint  or with false show."
fuchsia: "A genus of flowering plants having elegant drooping flowers  with four sepals four petals eight stamens and a single pistil. They are natives of Mexico and South America. Double-flowered varieties are now common in cultivation."
fucoid: "A plant  whether recent or fossil which resembles a seaweed. See Fucoid a."
fucus: "A genus of tough  leathery seaweeds usually of a dull brownish green color; rockweed."
fucusol: "An oily liquid  resembling and possibly identical with furfurol and obtained from fucus and other seaweeds."
fueler: "One who  or that which supplies fuel."
fugle: "To maneuver; to move hither and thither."
fugue: "A polyphonic composition  developed from a given theme or themes according to strict contrapuntal rules. The theme is first given out by one voice or part and then while that pursues its way it is repeated by another at the interval of a fifth or fourth and so on until all the parts have answered one by one continuing their several melodies and interweaving them in one complex progressive whole in which the theme is often lost and reappears."
fuguist: "A musician who composes or performs fugues."
fulcrum: "The connective tissue supporting the framework of the retina of the eye."
fulfill: "To accomplish or carry into effect  as an intention promise or prophecy a desire prayer or requirement etc.; to complete by performance; to answer the requisitions of; to bring to pass as a purpose or design; to effectuate."
fulling: "The process of cleansing  shrinking and thickening cloth by moisture heat and pressure."
fullage: "The money or price paid for fulling or cleansing cloth."
fuller: "To form a groove or channel in  by a fuller or set hammer; as to fuller a bayonet."
fullery: "The place or the works where the fulling of cloth is carried on."
fully: "In a full manner or degree; completely; entirely; without lack or defect; adequately; satisfactorily; as  to be fully persuaded of the truth of a proposition."
fulmar: "One of several species of sea birds  of the family procellariidae allied to the albatrosses and petrels. Among the well-known species are the arctic fulmar (Fulmarus glacialis) (called also fulmar petrel malduck and mollemock) and the giant fulmar (Ossifraga gigantea)."
fulmine: "To shoot; to dart like lightning; to fulminate; to utter with authority or vehemence."
fulsome: "Lustful; wanton; obscene; also  tending to obscenity."
fulvous: "Tawny; dull yellow  with a mixture of gray and brown."
fumado: "A salted and smoked fish  as the pilchard."
fumaric: "Pertaining to  or derived from fumitory (Fumaria officinalis)."
fumble: "To handle or manage awkwardly; to crowd or tumble together."
fumette: "The stench or high flavor of game or other meat when kept long."
fumify: "To subject to the action of smoke."
funded: "Invested in public funds; as  funded money."
fundus: "The bottom or base of any hollow organ; as  the fundus of the bladder; the fundus of the eye."
funeral: "Per. taining to a funeral; used at the interment of the dead; as  funeral rites honors or ceremonies."
fungia: "A genus of simple  stony corals; -- so called because they are usually flat and circular with radiating plates like the gills of a mushroom. Some of them are eighteen inches in diameter."
fungic: "Pertaining to  or obtained from mushrooms; as fungic acid."
fungin: "A name formerly given to cellulose found in certain fungi and mushrooms."
fungous: "Growing suddenly  but not substantial or durable."
fungus: "A spongy  morbid growth or granulation in animal bodies as the proud flesh of wounds."
funicle: "The little stalk that attaches a seed to the placenta."
funis: "A cord; specifically  the umbilical cord or navel string."
funky: "Pertaining to  or characterized by great fear or funking."
funnel: "A passage or avenue for a fluid or flowing substance; specifically  a smoke flue or pipe; the iron chimney of a steamship or the like."
furring: "A deposit from water  as on the inside of a boiler; also the operation of cleaning away this deposit."
furbish: "To rub or scour to brightness; to clean; to burnish; as  to furbish a sword or spear."
furcula: "A forked process; the wishbone or furculum."
furdle: "To draw up into a bundle; to roll up."
furile: "A yellow  crystalline substance (C4H3O)2.C2O2 obtained by the oxidation of furoin."
furilic: "Pertaining to  or derived from furile; as furilic acid."
furious: "Rushing with impetuosity; moving with violence; as  a furious stream; a furious wind or storm."
furlong: "A measure of length; the eighth part of a mile; forty rods; two hundred and twenty yards."
furnace: "To throw out  or exhale as from a furnace; also to put into a furnace."
furnish: "That which is furnished as a specimen; a sample; a supply."
furoin: "A colorless  crystalline substance C10H8O4 from furfurol."
furrier: "A dealer in furs; one who makes or sells fur goods."
furrow: "To mark with channels or with wrinkles."
further: "To help forward; to promote; to advance; to forward; to help or assist."
furtive: "Stolen; obtained or characterized by stealth; sly; secret; stealthy; as  a furtive look."
furze: "A thorny evergreen shrub (Ulex Europaeus)  with beautiful yellow flowers very common upon the plains and hills of Great Britain; -- called also gorse and whin. The dwarf furze is Ulex nanus."
furzy: "bounding in  or overgrown with furze; characterized by furze."
fusain: "A drawing made with it. See Charcoal  n. 2 and Charcoal drawing under Charcoal."
fuscin: "A brown  nitrogenous pigment contained in the retinal epithelium; a variety of melanin."
fuscine: "A dark-colored substance obtained from empyreumatic animal oil."
fusee: "A similar wheel used in other machinery."
fusil: "A bearing of a rhomboidal figure; -- named from its shape  which resembles that of a spindle."
fusion: "The union  or binding together of adjacent parts or tissues."
fussy: "Making a fuss; disposed to make an unnecessary ado about trifles; overnice; fidgety."
fustet: "The wood of the Rhus Cptinus or Venice sumach  a shrub of Southern Europe which yields a fine orange color which however is not durable without a mordant."
fustian: "Pompous; ridiculously tumid; inflated; bombastic; as  fustian history."
fustic: "The wood of the Maclura tinctoria  a tree growing in the West Indies used in dyeing yellow; -- called also old fustic."
futchel: "The jaws between which the hinder end of a carriage tongue is inserted."
futile: "Of no importance; answering no useful end; useless; vain; worthless."
futtock: "One of the crooked timbers which are scarfed together to form the lower part of the compound rib of a vessel; one of the crooked transverse timbers passing across and over the keel."
fuzzle: "To make drunk; to intoxicate; to fuddle."
fuzzy: "Furnished with fuzz; having fuzz; like fuzz; as  the fuzzy skin of a peach."
fyllot: "A rebated cross  formerly used as a secret emblem and a common ornament. It is also called gammadion and swastika."
fyrdung: "The military force of the whole nation  consisting of all men able to bear arms."
gabble: "Inarticulate sounds rapidly uttered; as of fowls."
gabbro: "A name originally given by the Italians to a kind of serpentine  later to the rock called euphotide and now generally used for a coarsely crystalline igneous rock consisting of lamellar pyroxene (diallage) and labradorite with sometimes chrysolite (olivine gabbro)."
gabel: "A rent  service tribute custom tax impost or duty; an excise."
gabert: "A lighter  or vessel for inland navigation."
gabion: "An openwork frame  as of poles filled with stones and sunk to assist in forming a bar dyke etc. as in harbor improvement."
gable: "A decorative member having the shape of a triangular gable  such as that above a Gothic arch in a doorway."
gablet: "A small gable  or gable-shaped canopy formed over a tabernacle niche etc."
gablock: "A false spur or gaff  fitted on the heel of a gamecock."
gadding: "Going about much  needlessly or without purpose."
gadder: "One who roves about idly  a rambling gossip."
gadfly: "Any dipterous insect of the genus Oestrus  and allied genera of botflies."
gadic: "Pertaining to  or derived from the cod (Gadus); -- applied to an acid obtained from cod-liver oil viz. gadic acid."
gadsman: "One who uses a gad or goad in driving."
gaduin: "A yellow or brown amorphous substance  of indifferent nature found in cod-liver oil."
gadwall: "A large duck (Anas strepera)  valued as a game bird found in the northern parts of Europe and America; -- called also gray duck."
gaelic: "The language of the Gaels  esp. of the Highlanders of Scotland. It is a branch of the Celtic."
gaffer: "A foreman or overseer of a gang of laborers."
gagger: "A piece of iron imbedded in the sand of a mold to keep the sand in place."
gaidic: "Pertaining to hypogeic acid; -- applied to an acid obtained from hypogeic acid."
gainage: "The profit made by tillage; also  the land itself."
gainsay: "To contradict; to deny; to controvert; to dispute; to forbid."
gaited: "Having (such) a gait; -- used in composition; as  slow-gaited; heavy-gaited."
galago: "A genus of African lemurs  including numerous species."
galaxy: "A splendid assemblage of persons or things."
galea: "The anterior  outer process of the second joint of the maxillae in certain insects."
galei: "That division of elasmobranch fishes which includes the sharks."
galena: "Lead sulphide; the principal ore of lead. It is of a bluish gray color and metallic luster  and is cubic in crystallization and cleavage."
galilee: "A porch or waiting room  usually at the west end of an abbey church where the monks collected on returning from processions where bodies were laid previous to interment and where women were allowed to see the monks to whom they were related or to hear divine service. Also frequently applied to the porch of a church as at Ely and Durham cathedrals."
galiot: "A strong  light-draft Dutch merchant vessel carrying a mainmast and a mizzenmast and a large gaff mainsail."
galipot: "An impure resin of turpentine  hardened on the outside of pine trees by the spontaneous evaporation of its essential oil. When purified it is called yellow pitch white pitch or Burgundy pitch."
galling: "Fitted to gall or chafe; vexing; harassing; irritating."
gallant: "To handle with grace or in a modish manner; as  to gallant a fan."
gallego: "A native or inhabitant of Galicia  in Spain; a Galician."
gallein: "A red crystalline dyestuff  obtained by heating together pyrogallic and phthalic acids."
galleon: "A sailing vessel of the 15th and following centuries  often having three or four decks and used for war or commerce. The term is often rather indiscriminately applied to any large sailing vessel."
galley: "A proof sheet taken from type while on a galley; a galley proof."
gallfly: "An insect that deposits its eggs in plants  and occasions galls esp. any small hymenopteran of the genus Cynips and allied genera. See Illust. of Gall."
gallin: "A substance obtained by the reduction of gallein."
gallium: "A rare metallic element  found in certain zinc ores. It is white hard and malleable resembling aluminium and remarcable for its low melting point (86/ F. 30/C). Symbol Ga. Atomic weight 69.9."
gallnut: "A round gall produced on the leaves and shoots of various species of the oak tree. See Gall  and Nutgall."
gallon: "A measure of capacity  containing four quarts; -- used for the most part in liquid measure but sometimes in dry measure."
galloon: "A similar bordering or binding of rich material  such as gold lace."
gallop: "A mode of running by a quadruped  particularly by a horse by lifting alternately the fore feet and the hind feet in successive leaps or bounds."
gallow: "To fright or terrify. See Gally  v. t."
galoot: "A noisy  swaggering or worthless fellow; a rowdy."
galop: "A kind of lively dance  in 2-4 time; also the music to the dance."
gambet: "Any bird of the genuis Totanus. See Tattler."
gambist: "A performer upon the viola di gamba. See under Viola."
gambit: "A mode of opening the game  in which a pawn is sacrificed to gain an attacking position."
gamble: "To lose or squander by gaming; -- usually with away."
