locket: "A little case for holding a miniature or lock of hair  usually suspended from a necklace or watch chain."
lockjaw: "A contraction of the muscles of the jaw by which its motion is suspended; a variety of tetanus."
lockout: "The closing of a factory or workshop by an employer  usually in order to bring the workmen to satisfactory terms by a suspension of wages."
lockram: "A kind of linen cloth anciently used in England  originally imported from Brittany."
lockup: "A place where persons under arrest are temporarily locked up; a watchhouse."
locular: "Of or relating to the cell or compartment of an ovary  etc.; in composition having cells; as trilocular."
loculus: "One of the compartments of a several-celled ovary; loculament."
locus: "The line traced by a point which varies its position according to some determinate law; the surface described by a point or line that moves according to a given law."
locust: "The locust tree. See Locust Tree (definition  note and phrases)."
locusta: "The spikelet or flower cluster of grasses."
lodged: "Lying down; -- used of beasts of the chase  as couchant is of beasts of prey."
lodger: "One who  or that which lodges; one who occupies a hired room in another's house."
loess: "A quaternary deposit  usually consisting of a fine yellowish earth on the banks of the Rhine and other large rivers."
loftily: "In a lofty manner or position; haughtily."
lofty: "Fig.: Elevated in character  rank dignity spirit bearing language etc.; exalted; noble; stately; characterized by pride; haughty."
logged: "Made slow and heavy in movement; water-logged."
logging: "The business of felling trees  cutting them into logs and transporting the logs to sawmills or to market."
loggat: "An old game in England  played by throwing pieces of wood at a stake set in the ground."
logger: "One engaged in logging. See Log  v. i."
loggia: "A roofed open gallery. It differs from a veranda in being more architectural  and in forming more decidedly a part of the main edifice to which it is attached; from a porch in being intended not for entrance but for an out-of-door sitting-room."
logic: "A treatise on logic; as  Mill's Logic."
logical: "Skilled in logic; versed in the art of thinking and reasoning; as  he is a logical thinker."
logroll: "To engage in logrolling; to accomplish by logrolling."
logwood: "The heartwood of a tree (Haematoxylon Campechianum)  a native of South America It is a red heavy wood containing a crystalline substance called haematoxylin and is used largely in dyeing. An extract from this wood is used in medicine as an astringent. Also called Campeachy wood and bloodwood."
loimic: "Of or pertaining to the plague or contagious disorders."
locao: "A green vegetable dye imported from China."
loligo: "A genus of cephalopods  including numerous species of squids common on the coasts of America and Europe. They are much used for fish bait."
lollard: "One of the followers of Wyclif in England."
lollop: "To move heavily; to lounge or idle; to loll."
lombard: "A form of cannon formerly in use."
loment: "An elongated pod  consisting like the legume of two valves but divided transversely into small cells each containing a single seed."
lonely: "Having a feeling of depression or sadness resulting from the consciousness of being alone; lonesome."
longing: "An eager desire; a craving; a morbid appetite; an earnest wish; an aspiration."
longan: "A pulpy fruit related to the litchi  and produced by an evergreen East Indian tree (Nephelium Longan)."
longbow: "The ordinary bow  not mounted on a stock; -- so called in distinction from the crossbow when both were used as weapons of war. Also sometimes such a bow of about the height of a man as distinguished from a much shorter one."
looking: "The manner in which one looks; appearance; countenance; face."
lookout: "Object or duty of forethought and care; responsibility."
looming: "The indistinct and magnified appearance of objects seen in particular states of the atmosphere. See Mirage."
looper: "The larva of any species of geometrid moths. See Geometrid."
loosen: "To become loose; to become less tight  firm or compact."
lopping: "A cutting off  as of branches; that which is cut off; leavings."
loper: "A swivel at one end of a ropewalk  used in laying the strands."
lophine: "A nitrogenous organic base obtained by the oxidation of amarine  and regarded as a derivative of benzoic aldehyde. It is obtained in long white crystalline tufts -- whence its name."
loppard: "A tree  the top of which has been lopped off."
lopper: "To turn sour and coagulate from too long standing  as milk."
lopseed: "A perennial herb (Phryma Leptostachya)  having slender seedlike fruits."
loquat: "The fruit of the Japanese medlar (Photinia Japonica). It is as large as a small plum  but grows in clusters and contains four or five large seeds. Also the tree itself."
loral: "Of or pertaining to the lore; -- said of certain feathers of birds  scales of reptiles etc."
lorate: "Having the form of a thong or strap; ligulate."
lorcha: "A kind of light vessel used on the coast of China  having the hull built on a European model and the rigging like that of a Chinese junk."
lording: "A little lord; a lordling; a lord  in contempt or ridicule."
lorel: "A good for nothing fellow; a vagabond."
lorette: "In France  a name for a woman who is supported by her lovers and devotes herself to idleness show and pleasure; -- so called from the church of Notre Dame de Lorette in Paris near which many of them resided."
lorica: "The protective case or shell of an infusorian or rotifer."
loriner: "A maker of bits  spurs and metal mounting for bridles and saddles; hence a saddler."
loriot: "The golden oriole of Europe. See Oriole."
loris: "Any one of several species of small lemurs of the genus Stenops. They have long  slender limbs and large eyes and are arboreal in their habits. The slender loris (S. gracilis) of Ceylon in one of the best known species."
lorry: "A small cart or wagon  as those used on the tramways in mines to carry coal or rubbish; also a barrow or truck for shifting baggage as at railway stations."
losing: "Causing or incurring loss; as  a losing game or business."
lotion: "A liquid preparation for bathing the skin  or an injured or diseased part either for a medicinal purpose or for improving its appearance."
lotto: "A game of chance  played with cards on which are inscribed numbers and any contrivance (as a wheel containing numbered balls) for determining a set of numbers by chance. The player holding a card having on it the set of numbers drawn from the wheel takes the stakes after a certain percentage of them has been deducted for the dealer. A variety of lotto is called keno."
lotus: "An ornament much used in Egyptian architecture  generally asserted to have been suggested by the Egyptian water lily."
lounge: "A piece of furniture resembling a sofa  upon which one may lie or recline."
loups: "The Pawnees  a tribe of North American Indians whose principal totem was the wolf."
lousily: "In a lousy manner; in a mean  paltry manner; scurvily."
loutou: "A crested black monkey (Semnopithecus maurus) of Java."
lovable: "Having qualities that excite  or are fitted to excite love; worthy of love."
lovage: "An umbelliferous plant (Levisticum officinale)  sometimes used in medicine as an aromatic stimulant."
loving: "Expressing love or kindness; as  loving words."
lovely: "In a manner to please  or to excite love."
lowing: "The calling sound made by cows and other bovine animals."
lowborn: "Born in a low condition or rank; -- opposed to highborn."
lowbred: "Bred  or like one bred in a low condition of life; characteristic or indicative of such breeding; rude; impolite; vulgar; as a lowbred fellow; a lowbred remark."
lowery: "Cloudy; gloomy; lowering; as  a lowery sky; lowery weather."
lowland: "Land which is low with respect to the neighboring country; a low or level country; -- opposed to highland."
lowlily: "In a lowly place or manner; humbly."
lowness: "The state or quality of being low."
lowry: "An open box car used on railroads. Compare Lorry."
loyal: "True to any person or persons to whom one owes fidelity  especially as a wife to her husband lovers to each other and friend to friend; constant; faithful to a cause or a principle."
loyalty: "The state or quality of being loyal; fidelity to a superior  or to duty love etc."
lozenge: "A small cake of sugar and starch  flavored and often medicated. -- originally in the form of a lozenge."
lozengy: "Divided into lozenge-shaped compartments  as the field or a bearing by lines drawn in the direction of the bend sinister."
lubber: "A heavy  clumsy or awkward fellow; a sturdy drone; a clown."
lucid: "Bright with the radiance of intellect; not darkened or confused by delirium or madness; marked by the regular operations of reason; as  a lucid interval."
lucifer: "A genus of free-swimming macruran Crustacea  having a slender body and long appendages."
luckily: "In a lucky manner; by good fortune; fortunately; -- used in a good sense; as  they luckily escaped injury."
lucky: "Producing  or resulting in good by chance or unexpectedly; favorable; auspicious; fortunate; as a lucky mistake; a lucky cast; a lucky hour."
lucre: "Gain in money or goods; profit; riches; -- often in an ill sense."
lucule: "A spot or fleck on the sun brighter than the surrounding surface."
lucuma: "An American genus of sapotaceous trees bearing sweet and edible fruits."
luddite: "One of a number of riotous persons in England  who for six years (1811-17) tried to prevent the use of labor-saving machinery by breaking it burning factories etc.; -- so called from Ned Lud a half-witted man who some years previously had broken stocking frames."
luggage: "That which is lugged; anything cumbrous and heavy to be carried; especially  a traveler's trunks baggage etc. or their contents."
lugger: "An Indian falcon (Falco jugger)  similar to the European lanner and the American prairie falcon."
lugmark: "A mark cut into the ear of an animal to identify it; an earmark."
lugsail: "A square sail bent upon a yard that hangs obliquely to the mast and is raised or lowered with the sail."
lugworm: "A large marine annelid (Arenicola marina) having a row of tufted gills along each side of the back. It is found burrowing in sandy beaches  both in America and Europe and is used for bait by European fishermen. Called also lobworm and baitworm."
lumbago: "A rheumatic pain in the loins and the small of the back."
lumbal: "Of  pertaining to or near the loins; as the lumbar arteries."
lumber: "To cut logs in the forest  or prepare timber for market."
lumbric: "An earthworm  or a worm resembling an earthworm."
lummox: "A fat  ungainly stupid person; an awkward bungler."
lumper: "A laborer who is employed to load or unload vessels when in harbor."
lumpish: "Like a lump; inert; gross; heavy; dull; spiritless."
lumpy: "Full of lumps  or small compact masses."
lunacy: "A morbid suspension of good sense or judgment  as through fanaticism."
lunar: "The middle bone of the proximal series of the carpus; -- called also semilunar  and intermedium."
lunary: "A low fleshy fern (Botrychium Lunaria) with lunate segments of the leaf or frond."
lunated: "Crescent-shaped; as  a lunate leaf; a lunate beak; a lunated cross."
lunatic: "A person affected by lunacy; an insane person  esp. one who has lucid intervals; a madman; a person of unsound mind."
lunette: "An iron shoe at the end of the stock of a gun carriage."
lunged: "Having lungs  or breathing organs similar to lungs."
lungoor: "A long-tailed monkey (Semnopithecus schislaceus)  from the mountainous districts of India."
lunular: "Having a form like that of the new moon; shaped like a crescent."
lunule: "A special area in front of the beak of many bivalve shells. It sometimes has the shape of a double crescent  but is oftener heart-shaped. See Illust. of Bivalve."
lunulet: "A small spot  shaped like a half-moon or crescent; as the lunulet on the wings of many insects."
lupinin: "A glucoside found in the seeds of several species of lupine  and extracted as a yellowish white crystalline substance."
lupulin: "The fine yellow resinous powder found upon the strobiles or fruit of hops  and containing this bitter principle."
lupus: "The Wolf  a constellation situated south of Scorpio."
lurch: "To dodge; to shift; to play tricks."
lurid: "Of a color tinged with purple  yellow and gray."
lurry: "A confused heap; a throng  as of persons; a jumble as of sounds."
lustrum: "A lustration or purification  especially the purification of the whole Roman people which was made by the censors once in five years. Hence: A period of five years."
luteic: "Pertaining to  or designating an acid resembling luteolin but obtained from the flowers of Euphorbia cyparissias."
lutein: "A substance of a strongly marked yellow color  extracted from the yelk of eggs and from the tissue of the corpus luteum."
luteo-: "A combining form signifying orange yellow or brownish yellow."
luxate: "To displace  or remove from its proper place as a joint; to put out of joint; to dislocate."
lyceum: "An association for debate and literary improvement."
lychnis: "A genus of Old World plants belonging to the Pink family (Caryophyllaceae). Most of the species have brilliantly colored flowers and cottony leaves  which may have anciently answered as wicks for lamps. The botanical name is in common use for the garden species. The corn cockle (Lychnis Githago) is a common weed in wheat fields."
lycine: "A weak base identical with betaine; -- so called because found in the boxthorn (Lycium barbarum). See Betaine."
lydian: "Of or pertaining to Lydia  a country of Asia Minor or to its inhabitants; hence soft; effeminate; -- said especially of one of the ancient Greek modes or keys the music in which was of a soft pathetic or voluptuous character."
lymph: "A fibrinous material exuded from the blood vessels in inflammation. In the process of healing it is either absorbed  or is converted into connective tissue binding the inflamed surfaces together."
lynch: "To inflict punishment upon  especially death without the forms of law as when a mob captures and hangs a suspected person. See Lynch law."
lyrated: "Shaped like a lyre  as the tail of the blackcock or that of the lyre bird."
lyrical: "Fitted to be sung to the lyre; hence  also appropriate for song; -- said especially of poetry which expresses the individual emotions of the poet."
lyrid: "One of the group of shooting stars which come into the air in certain years on or about the 19th of April; -- so called because the apparent path among the stars the stars if produced back wards crosses the constellation Lyra."
lyrie: "A European fish (Peristethus cataphractum)  having the body covered with bony plates and having three spines projecting in front of the nose; -- called also noble pluck pogge sea poacher and armed bullhead."
lyrism: "The act of playing on a lyre or harp."
lyrist: "A musician who plays on the harp or lyre; a composer of lyrical poetry."
lysis: "The resolution or favorable termination of a disease  coming on gradually and not marked by abrupt change."
lytta: "A fibrous and muscular band lying within the longitudinal axis of the tongue in many mammals  as the dog."
ma'am: "Madam; my lady; -- a colloquial contraction of madam often used in direct address  and sometimes as an appellation."
maasha: "An East Indian coin  of about one tenth of the weight of a rupee."
mabby: "A spirituous liquor or drink distilled from potatoes; -- used in the Barbadoes."
mabolo: "A kind of persimmon tree (Diospyros discolor) from the Philippine Islands  now introduced into the East and West Indies. It bears an edible fruit as large as a quince."
macaco: "Any one of several species of lemurs  as the ruffed lemur (Lemur macaco) and the ring-tailed lemur (L. catta)."
macacus: "A genus of monkeys  found in Asia and the East Indies. They have short tails and prominent eyebrows."
macaque: "Any one of several species of short-tailed monkeys of the genus Macacus; as  M. maurus the moor macaque of the East Indies."
macauco: "Any one of several species of small lemurs  as Lemur murinus which resembles a rat in size."
macaw: "Any parrot of the genus Sittace  or Macrocercus. About eighteen species are known all of them American. They are large and have a very long tail a strong hooked bill and a naked space around the eyes. The voice is harsh and the colors are brilliant and strongly contrasted."
macco: "A gambling game in vogue in the eighteenth century."
macer: "A mace bearer; an officer of a court."
machete: "A large heavy knife resembling a broadsword  often two or three feet in length -- used by the inhabitants of Spanish America as a hatchet to cut their way through thickets and for various other purposes."
machine: "To subject to the action of machinery; to effect by aid of machinery; to print with a printing machine."
macho: "The striped mullet of California (Mugil cephalus  / Mexicanus)."
mackle: "To blur  or be blurred in printing as if there were a double impression."
macro-: "A combining form signifying long  large great; as macrodiagonal macrospore."
macron: "A short  straight horizontal mark [-] placed over vowels to denote that they are to be pronounced with a long sound; as a in dame; / in s/am etc."
macrura: "A subdivision of decapod Crustacea  having the abdomen largely developed. It includes the lobster prawn shrimp and many similar forms. Cf. Decapoda."
mactra: "Any marine bivalve shell of the genus Mactra  and allied genera. Many species are known. Some of them are used as food as Mactra stultorum of Europe. See Surf clam under Surf."
macula: "A rather large spot or blotch of color."
macule: "To blur; especially (Print.)  to blur or double an impression from type. See Mackle."
madam: "A gentlewoman; -- an appellation or courteous form of address given to a lady  especially an elderly or a married lady; -- much used in the address at the beginning of a letter to a woman. The corresponding word in addressing a man is Sir."
madame: "My lady; -- a French title formerly given to ladies of quality; now  in France given to all married women."
madcap: "A person of wild behavior; an excitable  rash violent person."
madden: "To become mad; to act as if mad."
madder: "A plant of the Rubia (R. tinctorum). The root is much used in dyeing red  and formerly was used in medicine. It is cultivated in France and Holland. See Rubiaceous."
madeira: "A rich wine made on the Island of Madeira."
madia: "A genus of composite plants  of which one species (Madia sativa) is cultivated for the oil yielded from its seeds by pressure. This oil is sometimes used instead of olive oil for the table."
madjoun: "An intoxicating confection from the hemp plant; -- used by the Turks and Hindoos."
madly: "In a mad manner; without reason or understanding; wildly."
madman: "A man who is mad; lunatic; a crazy person."
madonna: "A picture of the Virgin Mary (usually with the babe)."
madoqua: "A small Abyssinian antelope (Neotragus Saltiana)  about the size of a hare."
madrier: "A plank or beam used for supporting the earth in mines or fortifications."
madrina: "An animal (usually an old mare)  wearing a bell and acting as the leader of a troop of pack mules."
madwort: "A genus of cruciferous plants (Alyssum) with white or yellow flowers and rounded pods. A. maritimum is the commonly cultivated sweet alyssum  a fragrant white-flowered annual."
maestro: "A master in any art  especially in music; a composer."
magdala: "Designating an orange-red dyestuff obtained from naphthylamine  and called magdala red naphthalene red etc."
magenta: "An aniline dye obtained as an amorphous substance having a green bronze surface color  which dissolves to a shade of red; also the color; -- so called from Magenta in Italy in allusion to the battle fought there about the time the dye was discovered. Called also fuchsine roseine etc."
maghet: "A name for daisies and camomiles of several kinds."
magian: "One of the Magi  or priests of the Zoroastrian religion in Persia; an adherent of the Zoroastrian religion."
magical: "Performed by  or proceeding from occult and superhuman agencies; done by or seemingly done by enchantment or sorcery. Hence: Seemingly requiring more than human power; imposing or startling in performance; producing effects which seem supernatural or very extraordinary; having extraordinary properties; as a magic lantern; a magic square or circle."
magma: "The amorphous or homogenous matrix or ground mass  as distinguished from well-defined crystals; as the magma of porphyry."
magnate: "One of the nobility  or certain high officers of state belonging to the noble estate in the national representation of Hungary and formerly of Poland."
magnet: "A bar or mass of steel or iron to which the peculiar properties of the loadstone have been imparted; -- called  in distinction from the loadstone an artificial magnet."
magnify: "To have effect; to be of importance or significance."
magnum: "A bone of the carpus at the base of the third metacarpal bone."
magpie: "Any one of numerous species of the genus Pica and related genera  allied to the jays but having a long graduated tail."
maguari: "A South American stork (Euxenara maguari)  having a forked tail."
maguey: "The century plant  a species of Agave (A. Americana). See Agave."
mahaled: "A cherry tree (Prunus Mahaleb) of Southern Europe. The wood is prized by cabinetmakers  the twigs are used for pipe stems the flowers and leaves yield a perfume and from the fruit a violet dye and a fermented liquor (like kirschwasser) are prepared."
maharif: "An African antelope (Hippotragus Bakeri). Its face is striped with black and white."
mahdi: "Among Mohammedans  the last imam or leader of the faithful. The Sunni the largest sect of the Mohammedans believe that he is yet to appear."
mahoe: "A name given to several malvaceous trees (species of Hibiscus  Ochroma etc.) and to their strong fibrous inner bark which is used for strings and cordage."
maholi: "A South African lemur (Galago maholi)  having very large ears."
mahonia: "The Oregon grape  a species of barberry (Berberis Aquifolium) often cultivated for its hollylike foliage."
mahori: "One of the dark race inhabiting principally the islands of Eastern Polynesia. Also used adjectively."
mahound: "A contemptuous name for Mohammed; hence  an evil spirit; a devil."
mahout: "The keeper and driver of an elephant."
mahovo: "A device for saving power in stopping and starting a railroad car  by means of a heavy fly wheel."
mahrati: "The language of the Mahrattas; the language spoken in the Deccan and Concan."
maian: "Any spider crab of the genus Maia  or family Maiadae."
maiden: "To act coyly like a maiden; -- with it as an indefinite object."
maigre: "Belonging to a fast day or fast; as  a maigre day."
maikel: "A South American carnivore of the genus Conepatus  allied to the skunk but larger and having a longer snout. The tail is not bushy."
maikong: "A South American wild dog (Canis cancrivorus); the crab-eating dog."
mainor: "A thing stolen found on the person of the thief."
mains: "The farm attached to a mansion house."
maintop: "The platform about the head of the mainmast in square-rigged vessels."
maioid: "Of or pertaining to the genus Maia  or family Maiadeae."
maize: "A large species of American grass of the genus Zea (Z. Mays)  widely cultivated as a forage and food plant; Indian corn. Also its seed growing on cobs and used as food for men animals."
majorat: "Property  landed or funded so attached to a title of honor as to descend with it."
make-up: "The way in which the parts of anything are put together; often  the way in which an actor is dressed painted etc. in personating a character."
malabar: "A region in the western part of the Peninsula of India  between the mountains and the sea."
malacca: "A town and district upon the seacoast of the Malay Peninsula."
malady: "A moral or mental defect or disorder."
malaga: "A city and a province of Spain  on the Mediterranean. Hence Malaga grapes Malaga raisins Malaga wines."
malaise: "An indefinite feeling of uneasiness  or of being sick or ill at ease."
malambo: "A yellowish aromatic bark  used in medicine and perfumery said to be from the South American shrub Croton Malambo."
malamic: "Of or pertaining an acid intermediate between malic acid and malamide  and known only by its salts."
malar: "The cheek bone  which forms a part of the lower edge of the orbit."
malaria: "A morbid condition produced by exhalations from decaying vegetable matter in contact with moisture  giving rise to fever and ague and many other symptoms characterized by their tendency to recur at definite and usually uniform intervals."
malefic: "Doing mischief; causing harm or evil; nefarious; hurtful."
maleic: "Pertaining to  or designating an acid of the ethylene series metameric with fumaric acid and obtained by heating malic acid."
maleo: "A bird of Celebes (megacephalon maleo)  allied to the brush turkey. It makes mounds in which to lay its eggs."
maleyl: "A hypothetical radical derived from maleic acid."
malic: "Pertaining to  or obtained from apples; as malic acid."
malkin: "A mop or sponge attached to a jointed staff for swabbing out a cannon."
mallard: "A large wild duck (Anas boschas) inhabiting both America and Europe. The domestic duck has descended from this species. Called also greenhead."
mallet: "A small maul with a short handle  -- used esp. for driving a tool as a chisel or the like; also a light beetle with a long handle -- used in playing croquet."
malleus: "A genus of bivalve shells; the hammer shell."
mallows: "A genus of plants (Malva) having mucilaginous qualities. See Malvaceous."
malma: "A spotted trout (Salvelinus malma)  inhabiting Northern America west of the Rocky Mountains; -- called also Dolly Varden trout bull trout red-spotted trout and golet."
malmsey: "A kind of sweet wine from Crete  the Canary Islands etc."
malodor: "An Offensive to the sense of smell; ill-smelling."
malonic: "Pertaining to  or designating an acid produced artifically as a white crystalline substance CH2.(CO2H)2 and so called because obtained by the oxidation of malic acid."
malonyl: "A hydrocarbon radical  CH2.(CO)2 from malonic acid."
malting: "The process of making  or of becoming malt."
maltese: "A native or inhabitant of Malta; the people of Malta."
maltine: "The fermentative principle of malt; malt diastase; also  a name given to various medicinal preparations made from or containing malt."
maltman: "A man whose occupation is to make malt."
maltose: "A crystalline sugar formed from starch by the action of distance of malt  and the amylolytic ferment of saliva and pancreatic juice. It resembles dextrose but rotates the plane of polarized light further to the right and possesses a lower cupric oxide reducing power."
mamelon: "A rounded hillock; a rounded elevation or protuberance."
mamma: "A glandular organ for secreting milk  characteristic of all mammals but usually rudimentary in the male; a mammary gland; a breast; under; bag."
mammary: "Of or pertaining to the mammae or breasts; as  the mammary arteries and veins."
mammee: "A fruit tree of tropical America  belonging to the genus Mammea (M. Americana); also its fruit. The latter is large covered with a thick tough ring and contains a bright yellow pulp of a pleasant taste and fragrant scent. It is often called mammee apple."
mammon: "Riches; wealth; the god of riches; riches  personified."
mammose: "Having the form of the breast; breast-shaped."
mammoth: "Resembling the mammoth in size; very large; gigantic; as  a mammoth ox."
mamzer: "A person born of relations between whom marriage was forbidden by the Mosaic law; a bastard."
manacle: "To put handcuffs or other fastening upon  for confining the hands; to shackle; to confine; to restrain from the use of the limbs or natural powers."
manage: "To direct affairs; to carry on business or affairs; to administer."
manatee: "Any species of Trichechus  a genus of sirenians; -- called alsosea cow."
manbote: "A sum paid to a lord as a pecuniary compensation for killing his man (that is  his vassal servant or tenant)."
manchet: "Fine white bread; a loaf of fine bread."
manchu: "A native or inhabitant of Manchuria; also  the language spoken by the Manchus."
mancus: "An old Anglo Saxon coin both of gold and silver  and of variously estimated values. The silver mancus was equal to about one shilling of modern English money."
mandate: "A contract by which one employs another to manage any business for him. By the Roman law  it must have been gratuitous."
mandil: "A loose outer garment worn the 16th and 17th centuries."
mandrel: "The live spindle of a turning lathe; the revolving arbor of a circular saw. It is usually driven by a pulley."
manege: "A school for teaching horsemanship  and for training horses."
maneh: "A Hebrew weight for gold or silver  being one hundred shekels of gold and sixty shekels of silver."
manes: "The benevolent spirits of the dead  especially of dead ancestors regarded as family deities and protectors."
manful: "Showing manliness  or manly spirit; hence brave courageous resolute noble."
mange: "The scab or itch in cattle  dogs and other beasts."
manger: "The fore part of the deck  having a bulkhead athwart ships high enough to prevent water which enters the hawse holes from running over it."
mangle: "To smooth with a mangle  as damp linen or cloth."
manhole: "A hole through which a man may descend or creep into a drain  sewer steam boiler parts of machinery etc. for cleaning or repairing."
mania: "Excessive or unreasonable desire; insane passion affecting one or many people; as  the tulip mania."
manid: "Any species of the genus Manis  or family Manidae."
manikin: "A model of the human body  made of papier-mache or other material commonly in detachable pieces for exhibiting the different parts and organs their relative position etc."
manioc: "The tropical plants (Manihot utilissima  and M. Aipi) from which cassava and tapioca are prepared; also cassava."
maniple: "Originally  a napkin; later an ornamental band or scarf worn upon the left arm as a part of the vestments of a priest in the Roman Catholic Church. It is sometimes worn in the English Church service."
manis: "A genus of edentates  covered with large hard triangular scales with sharp edges that overlap each other like tiles on a roof. They inhabit the warmest parts of Asia and Africa and feed on ants. Called also Scaly anteater. See Pangolin."
manitu: "A name given by tribes of American Indians to a great spirit  whether good or evil or to any object of worship."
manks: "The language spoken in the Isle of Man. See Manx."
manlike: "Like man  or like a man in form or nature; having the qualities of a man esp. the nobler qualities; manly."
manly: "In a manly manner; with the courage and fortitude of a manly man; as  to act manly."
manna: "A sweetish exudation in the form of pale yellow friable flakes  coming from several trees and shrubs and used in medicine as a gentle laxative as the secretion of Fraxinus Ornus and F. rotundifolia the manna ashes of Southern Europe."
manner: "Sort; kind; style; -- in this application sometimes having the sense of a plural  sorts or kinds."
mannide: "A white amorphous or crystalline substance  obtained by dehydration of mannite and distinct from but convertible into mannitan."
mannish: "Fond of men; -- said of a woman."
mannite: "A sweet white efflorescence from dried fronds of kelp  especially from those of the Laminaria saccharina or devil's apron."
manor: "A tract of land occupied by tenants who pay a free-farm rent to the proprietor  sometimes in kind and sometimes by performing certain stipulated services."
manrent: "Homage or service rendered to a superior  as to a lord; vassalage."
manrope: "One of the side ropes to the gangway of a ship."
mantel: "The finish around a fireplace  covering the chimney-breast in front and sometimes on both sides; especially a shelf above the fireplace and its supports."
mantic: "Of or pertaining to divination  or to the condition of one inspired or supposed to be inspired by a deity; prophetic."
mantis: "Any one of numerous species of voracious orthopterous insects of the genus Mantis  and allied genera. They are remarkable for their slender grotesque forms and for holding their stout anterior legs in a manner suggesting hands folded in prayer. The common American species is M. Carolina."
mantle: "To gather  assume or take on a covering as froth scum etc."
mantra: "A prayer; an invocation; a religious formula; a charm."
mantrap: "A dangerous place  as an open hatch into which one may fall."
mantua: "A woman's cloak or mantle; also  a woman's gown."
manual: "A prescribed exercise in the systematic handing of a weapon; as  the manual of arms; the manual of the sword; the manual of the piece (cannon mortar etc.)."
manul: "A wild cat (Felis manul)  having long soft light-colored fur. It is found in the mountains of Central Asia and dwells among rocks."
manumit: "To release from slavery; to liberate from personal bondage or servitude; to free  as a slave."
manure: "Any matter which makes land productive; a fertilizing substance  as the contents of stables and barnyards dung decaying animal or vegetable substances etc."
manus: "The distal segment of the fore limb  including the carpus and fore foot or hand."
manway: "A small passageway  as in a mine that a man may pass through."
maori: "Of or pertaining to the Maoris or to their language."
maple: "A tree of the genus Acer  including about fifty species. A. saccharinum is the rock maple or sugar maple from the sap of which sugar is made in the United States in great quantities by evaporation; the red or swamp maple is A. rubrum; the silver maple A. dasycarpum having fruit wooly when young; the striped maple A. Pennsylvanium called also moosewood. The common maple of Europe is A. campestre the sycamore maple is A. Pseudo-platanus
maplike: "Having or consisting of lines resembling a map; as  the maplike figures in which certain lichens grow."
maqui: "A Chilian shrub (Aristotelia Maqui). Its bark furnishes strings for musical instruments  and a medicinal wine is made from its berries."
marabou: "One having five eighths negro blood; the offspring of a mulatto and a griffe."
marai: "A sacred inclosure or temple; -- so called by the islanders of the Pacific Ocean."
maranta: "A genus of endogenous plants found in tropical America  and some species also in India. They have tuberous roots containing a large amount of starch and from one species (Maranta arundinacea) arrowroot is obtained. Many kinds are cultivated for ornament."
marble: "To stain or vein like marble; to variegate in color; as  to marble the edges of a book or the surface of paper."
marbled: "Varied with irregular markings  or witch a confused blending of irregular spots and streaks."
marbler: "One who colors or stains in imitation of marble."
marcato: "In a marked emphatic manner; -- used adverbially as a direction."
march: "A piece of music designed or fitted to accompany and guide the movement of troops; a piece of music in the march form."
marcher: "The lord or officer who defended the marches or borders of a territory."
merchet: "In old English and in Scots law  a fine paid to the lord of the soil by a tenant upon the marriage of one the tenant's daughters."
marcian: "Under the influence of Mars; courageous; bold."
marena: "A European whitefish of the genus Coregonus."
margay: "An American wild cat (Felis tigrina)  ranging from Mexico to Brazil. It is spotted with black. Called also long-tailed cat."
margent: "To enter or note down upon the margin of a page; to margin."
margin: "To enter in the margin of a page."
margosa: "A large tree of genus Melia (M. Azadirachta) found in India. Its bark is bitter  and used as a tonic. A valuable oil is expressed from its seeds and a tenacious gum exudes from its trunk. The M. Azedarach is a much more showy tree and is cultivated in the Southern United States where it is known as Pride of India Pride of China or bead tree. Various parts of the tree are considered anthelmintic."
marian: "Pertaining to the Virgin Mary  or sometimes to Mary Queen of England daughter of Henry VIII."
mariet: "A kind of bellflower  Companula Trachelium once called Viola Mariana; but it is not a violet."
marimba: "A musical istrument of percussion  consisting of bars yielding musical tones when struck."
marined: "Having the lower part of the body like a fish."
mariner: "One whose occupation is to assist in navigating ships; a seaman or sailor."
marital: "Of or pertaining to a husband; as  marital rights duties authority."
marked: "Designated or distinguished by  or as by a mark; hence; noticeable; conspicuous; as a marked card; a marked coin; a marked instance."
marking: "The act of one who  or that which marks; the mark or marks made; arrangement or disposition of marks or coloring; as the marking of a bird's plumage."
marker: "An attachment to a sewing machine for marking a line on the fabric by creasing it."
market: "To expose for sale in a market; to traffic in; to sell in a market  and in an extended sense to sell in any manner; as most of the farmes have marketed their crops."
marlin: "The American great marbled godwit (Limosa fedoa). Applied also to the red-breasted godwit (Limosa haematica)."
marline: "To wind marline around; as  to marline a rope."
marly: "Consisting or partaking of marl; resembling marl; abounding with marl."
marmose: "A species of small opossum (Didelphus murina) ranging from Mexico to Brazil."
marmot: "Any one of several species of ground squirrels or gophers of the genus Spermophilus; also  the prairie dog."
marplot: "One who  by his officious /nterference mars or frustrates a design or plot."
marque: "A license to pass the limits of a jurisdiction  or boundary of a country for the purpose of making reprisals."
marquee: "A large field tent; esp.  one adapted to the use of an officer of high rank."
marquis: "A nobleman in England  France and Germany of a rank next below that of duke. Originally the marquis was an officer whose duty was to guard the marches or frontiers of the kingdom. The office has ceased and the name is now a mere title conferred by patent."
marram: "A coarse grass found on sandy beaches (Ammophila arundinacea). See Beach grass  under Beach."
marron: "A paper or pasteboard box or shell  wound about with strong twine filled with an explosive and ignited with a fuse -- used to make a noise like a cannon."
marrow: "To fill with  or as with marrow of fat; to glut."
marry: "Indeed ! in truth ! -- a term of asseveration said to have been derived from the practice of swearing by the Virgin Mary."
marsala: "A kind of wine exported from Marsala in Sicily."
marsh: "A tract of soft wet land  commonly covered partially or wholly with water; a fen; a swamp; a morass."
marshal: "To dispose in due order  as the different quarterings on an escutcheon or the different crests when several belong to an achievement."
marshy: "Pertaining to  or produced in marshes; as a marshy weed."
martel: "To make a blow with  or as with a hammer."
marten: "The fur of the marten  used for hats muffs etc."
martial: "Pertaining to  or containing iron; chalybeate; as martial preparations."
martin: "One of several species of swallows  usually having the tail less deeply forked than the tail of the common swallows."
martite: "Iron sesquioxide in isometric form  probably a pseudomorph after magnetite."
martlet: "A bird without beak or feet; -- generally assumed to represent a martin. As a mark of cadency it denotes the fourth son."
marvel: "To cause to marvel  or be surprised; -- used impersonally."
marver: "A stone  or cast-iron plate or former on which hot glass is rolled to give it shape."
mascled: "Composed of  or covered with lozenge-shaped scales; having lozenge-shaped divisions."
mashy: "Produced by crushing or bruising; resembling  or consisting of a mash."
masked: "Having the anterior part of the head differing decidedly in color from the rest of the plumage; -- said of birds."
maskery: "The dress or disguise of a maske/; masquerade."
maslach: "An excitant containing opium  much used by the Turks."
maslin: "Composed of different sorts; as  maslin bread which is made of rye mixed with a little wheat."
mason: "To build stonework or brickwork about  under in over etc.; to construct by masons; -- with a prepositional suffix; as to mason up a well or terrace; to mason in a kettle or boiler."
masonic: "Of or pertaining to Freemasons or to their craft or mysteries."
masonry: "The craft  institution or mysteries of Freemasons; freemasonry."
masora: "A Jewish critical work on the text of the Hebrew Scriptures  composed by several learned rabbis of the school of Tiberias in the eighth and ninth centuries."
massage: "A rubbing or kneading of the body  especially when performed as a hygienic or remedial measure."
massive: "In mass; not necessarily without a crystalline structure  but having no regular form; as a mineral occurs massive."
massy: "Compacted into  or consisting of a mass; having bulk and weight ot substance; ponderous; bulky and heavy; weight; heavy; as a massy shield; a massy rock."
masted: "Furnished with a mast or masts; -- chiefly in composition; as  a three-masted schooner."
masting: "The act or process of putting a mast or masts into a vessel; also  the scientific principles which determine the position of masts and the mechanical methods of placing them."
mastery: "The act process of mastering; the state of having mastered."
mastful: "Abounding in mast; producing mast in abundance; as  the mastful forest; a mastful chestnut."
mastic: "A kind of cement composed of burnt clay  litharge and linseed oil used for plastering walls etc."
mastiff: "A breed of large dogs noted for strength and courage. There are various strains  differing in form and color and characteristic of different countries."
mastoid: "Pertaining to  or in the region of the mastoid process; mastoidal."
masty: "Full of mast; abounding in acorns  etc."
matted: "Tangled closely together; having its parts adhering closely together; as  matted hair."
matting: "A dull  lusterless surface in certain of the arts as gilding metal work glassmaking etc."
mataco: "The three-banded armadillo (Tolypeutis tricinctus). See Illust. under Loricata."
matador: "In the game of quadrille or omber  the three principal trumps the ace of spades being the first the ace of clubs the third and the second being the deuce of a black trump or the seven of a red one."
matanza: "A place where animals are slaughtered for their hides and tallow."
match: "To be of equal  or similar size figure color or quality; to tally; to suit; to correspond; as these vases match."
matcher: "One who  or that which matches; a matching machine. See under 3d Match."
mater: "See Alma mater  Dura mater and Pia mater."
matico: "A Peruvian plant (Piper  / Artanthe elongatum) allied to the pepper the leaves of which are used as a styptic and astringent."
matin: "Of or pertaining to the morning  or to matins; used in the morning; matutinal."
matinal: "Relating to the morning  or to matins; matutinal."
matinee: "A reception  or a musical or dramatic entertainment held in the daytime. See SoirEe."
matrass: "A round-bottomed glass flask having a long neck; a bolthead."
matrix: "A rectangular arrangement of symbols in rows and columns. The symbols may express quantities or operations."
matron: "A housekeeper; esp.  a woman who manages the domestic economy of a public instution; a head nurse in a hospital; as the matron of a school or hospital."
matross: "Formerly  in the British service a gunner or a gunner's mate; one of the soldiers in a train of artillery who assisted the gunners in loading firing and sponging the guns."
matte: "A dead or dull finish  as in gilding where the gold leaf is not burnished or in painting where the surface is purposely deprived of gloss."
matter: "To regard as important; to take account of; to care for."
mattock: "An implement for digging and grubbing. The head has two long steel blades  one like an adz and the other like a narrow ax or the point of a pickax."
mature: "Hence  to become due as a note."
matweed: "A name of several maritime grasses  as the sea sand-reed (Ammophila arundinacea) which is used in Holland to bind the sand of the seacoast dikes (see Beach grass under Beach); also the Lygeum Spartum a Mediterranean grass of similar habit."
matzoth: "A cake of unleavened bread eaten by the Jews at the feast of the Passover."
maucaco: "A lemur; -- applied to several species  as the White-fronted the ruffed and the ring-tailed lemurs."
maudle: "To throw onto confusion or disorder; to render maudlin."
mauling: "A severe beating with a stick  cudgel or the fist."
maurist: "A member of the Congregation of Saint Maur  an offshoot of the Benedictines originating in France in the early part of the seventeenth century. The Maurists have been distinguished for their interest in literature."
mauther: "A girl; esp.  a great awkward girl; a wench."
mauve: "A color of a delicate purple  violet or lilac."
mavis: "The European throstle or song thrush (Turdus musicus)."
mawmet: "A puppet; a doll; originally  an idol because in the Middle Ages it was generally believed that the Mohammedans worshiped images representing Mohammed."
mawworm: "One of the larvae of botflies of horses; a bot."
maxilla: "One of the lower or outer jaws of arthropods."
maxim: "The longest note formerly used  equal to two longs or four breves; a large."
maximum: "Greatest in quantity or highest in degree attainable or attained; as  a maximum consumption of fuel; maximum pressure; maximum heat."
might: "Force or power of any kind  whether of body or mind; energy or intensity of purpose feeling or action; means or resources to effect an object; strength; force; power; ability; capacity."
mayduke: "A large dark-red cherry of excellent quality."
mayfish: "A common American minnow (Fundulus majalis). See Minnow."
mayhem: "The maiming of a person by depriving him of the use of any of his members which are necessary for defense or protection. See Maim."
mayor: "The chief magistrate of a city or borough; the chief officer of a municipal corporation. In some American cities there is a city court of which the major is chief judge."
mayoral: "The conductir of a mule team; also  a head shepherd."
maypole: "A tall pole erected in an open place and wreathed with flowers  about which the rustic May-day sports were had."
maypop: "The edible fruit of a passion flower  especially that of the North American Passiflora incarnata an oval yellowish berry as large as a small apple."
mazame: "A goatlike antelope (Haplocerus montanus) which inhabits the Rocky Mountains  frequenting the highest parts; -- called also mountain goat."
mazdean: "Of or pertaining to Ahura-Mazda  or Ormuzd the beneficent deity in the Zoroastrian dualistic system; hence Zoroastrian."
mazer: "A large drinking bowl; -- originally made of maple."
mazurka: "A Polish dance  or the music which accompanies it usually in 3-4 or 3-8 measure with a strong accent on the second beat."
meadow: "Of or pertaining to a meadow; of the nature of a meadow; produced  growing or living in a meadow."
meadowy: "Of or pertaining to meadows; resembling  or consisting of meadow."
meagre: "A large European sciaenoid fish (Sciaena umbra or S. aquila)  having white bloodless flesh. It is valued as a food fish."
meaking: "The process of picking out the oakum from the seams of a vessel which is to be recalked."
mealies: "Maize or Indian corn; -- the common name in South Africa."
mealy: "Overspread with something that resembles meal; as  the mealy wings of an insect."
meander: "To wind or turn in a course or passage; to be intricate."
meanly: "In a mean manner; unworthily; basely; poorly; ungenerously."
mease: "Five hundred; as  a mease of herrings."
measled: "Infected or spotted with measles  as pork."
measles: "The larvae of any tapeworm (Taenia) in the cysticerus stage  when contained in meat. Called also bladder worms."
measly: "Containing larval tapeworms; -- said of pork and beef."
measure: "To be of a certain size or quantity  or to have a certain length breadth or thickness or a certain capacity according to a standard measure; as cloth measures three fourths of a yard; a tree measures three feet in diameter."
meatal: "Of or pertaining to a meatus; resembling a meatus."
meated: "Having (such) meat; -- used chiefly in composition; as  thick-meated."
meatus: "A natural passage or canal; as  the external auditory meatus. See Illust. of Ear."
mecate: "A rope of hair or of maguey fiber  for tying horses etc."
mechlin: "A kind of lace made at  or originating in Mechlin in Belgium."
meconic: "Pertaining to  or obtained from the poppy or opium; specif. (Chem.) designating an acid related to aconitic acid found in opium and extracted as a white crystalline substance."
meconin: "A substance regarded as an anhydride of meconinic acid  existing in opium and extracted as a white crystalline substance. Also erroneously called meconina meconia etc. as though it were an alkaloid."
medal: "To honor or reward with a medal."
meddler: "One who meddles; one who interferes or busies himself with things in which he has no concern; an officious person; a busybody."
mediacy: "The state or quality of being mediate."
mediant: "The third above the keynote; -- so called because it divides the interval between the tonic and dominant into two thirds."
medical: "Containing medicine; used in medicine; medicinal; as  the medical properties of a plant."
medium: "Having a middle position or degree; mean; intermediate; medial; as  a horse of medium size; a decoction of medium strength."
medius: "The third or middle finger; the third digit  or that which corresponds to it."
medlar: "A tree of the genus Mespilus (M. Germanica); also  the fruit of the tree. The fruit is something like a small apple but has a bony endocarp. When first gathered the flesh is hard and austere and it is not eaten until it has begun to decay."
medoc: "A class of claret wines  including several varieties from the district of Medoc in the department of Gironde."
medulla: "A soft tissue  occupying the center of the stem or branch of a plant; pith."
meedful: "Worthy of meed  reward or recompense; meritorious."
meeken: "To make meek; to nurture in gentleness and humility."
meerkat: "A South African carnivore (Cynictis penicillata)  allied to the ichneumons."
meeting: "An assembly for worship; as  to attend meeting on Sunday; -- in England applied distinctively and disparagingly to the worshiping assemblies of Dissenters."
megaric: "Belonging  or pertaining to Megara a city of ancient Greece."
megerg: "One of the larger measures of work  amounting to one million ergs; -- called also megalerg."
megilph: "A gelatinous compound of linseed oil and mastic varnish  used by artists as a vehicle for colors."
megohm: "One of the larger measures of electrical resistance  amounting to one million ohms."
megrim: "The British smooth sole  or scaldfish (Psetta arnoglossa)."
meiosis: "Diminution; a species of hyperbole  representing a thing as being less than it really is."
melado: "A mixture of sugar and molasses; crude sugar as it comes from the pans without being drained."
melaena: "A discharge from the bowels of black matter  consisting of altered blood."
melain: "The dark coloring matter of the liquid of the cuttlefish."
melam: "A white or buff-colored granular powder  C6H9N11 obtained by heating ammonium sulphocyanate."
melanic: "Of or pertaining to the black-haired races."
melanin: "A black pigment found in the pigment-bearing cells of the skin (particularly in the skin of the negro)  in the epithelial cells of the external layer of the retina (then called fuscin) in the outer layer of the choroid and elsewhere. It is supposed to be derived from the decomposition of hemoglobin."
melasma: "A dark discoloration of the skin  usually local; as Addison's melasma or Addison's disease."
melee: "A fight in which the combatants are mingled in one confused mass; a hand to hand conflict; an affray."
melene: "An unsaturated hydrocarbon  C30H60 of the ethylene series obtained from beeswax as a white scaly crystalline wax; -- called also melissene and melissylene."
melic: "Of or pertaining to song; lyric; tuneful."
melilot: "Any species of Melilotus  a genus of leguminous herbs having a vanillalike odor; sweet clover; hart's clover. The blue melilot (Melilotus caerulea) is used in Switzerland to give color and flavor to sapsago cheese."
melissa: "A genus of labiate herbs  including the balm or bee balm (Melissa officinalis)."
mellite: "A mineral of a honey color  found in brown coal and partly the result of vegetable decomposition; honeystone. It is a mellitate of alumina."
mellone: "A yellow powder  C6H3N9 obtained from certain sulphocyanates. It has acid properties and forms compounds called mellonides."
mellow: "To become mellow; as  ripe fruit soon mellows."
melluco: "A climbing plant (Ullucus officinalis) of the Andes  having tuberous roots which are used as a substitute for potatoes."
melodic: "Of the nature of melody; relating to  containing or made up of melody; melodious."
melody: "The air or tune of a musical piece."
meloe: "A genus of beetles without wings  but having short oval elytra; the oil beetles. These beetles are sometimes used instead of cantharides for raising blisters. See Oil beetle under Oil."
melon: "A large  ornamental marine univalve shell of the genus Melo."
molten: "Made by melting and casting the substance or metal of which the thing is formed; as  a molten image."
melting: "Causing to melt; becoming melted; -- used literally or figuratively; as  a melting heat; a melting appeal; a melting mood."
melton: "A kind of stout woolen cloth with unfinished face and without raised nap. A commoner variety has a cotton warp."
member: "One of the persons composing a society  community or the like; an individual forming part of an association; as a member of the society of Friends."
memento: "A hint  suggestion token or memorial to awaken memory; that which reminds or recalls to memory; a souvenir."
meminna: "A small deerlet  or chevrotain of India."
memnon: "A celebrated Egyptian statue near Thebes  said to have the property of emitting a harplike sound at sunrise."
memoirs: "An account of something deemed noteworthy; an essay; a record of investigations of any subject; the journals and proceedings of a society."
menace: "To act in threatening manner; to wear a threatening aspect."
menaion: "A work of twelve volumes  each containing the offices in the Greek Church for a month; also each volume of the same."
menhir: "A large stone set upright in olden times as a memorial or monument. Many  of unknown date are found in Brittany and throughout Northern Europe."
menial: "A person of a servile character or disposition."
menses: "The catamenial or menstrual discharge  a periodic flow of blood or bloody fluid from the uterus or female generative organs."
mental: "Of or pertaining to the mind; intellectual; as  mental faculties; mental operations conditions or exercise."
mentha: "A widely distributed genus of fragrant herbs  including the peppermint spearmint etc. The plants have small flowers usually arranged in dense axillary clusters."
menthol: "A white  crystalline aromatic substance resembling camphor extracted from oil of peppermint (Mentha); -- called also mint camphor or peppermint camphor."
menthyl: "A compound radical forming the base of menthol."
mention: "To make mention of; to speak briefly of; to name."
mentor: "A wise and faithful counselor or monitor."
mentum: "The front median plate of the labium in insects. See Labium."
merce: "To subject to fine or amercement; to mulct; to amerce."
mercer: "Originally  a dealer in any kind of goods or wares; now restricted to a dealer in textile fabrics as silks or woolens."
mercery: "The trade of mercers; the goods in which a mercer deals."
mercury: "To wash with a preparation of mercury."
mercy: "A blessing regarded as a manifestation of compassion or favor."
merge: "To be sunk  swallowed up or lost."
merger: "An absorption of one estate  or one contract in another or of a minor offense in a greater."
meride: "A permanent colony of cells or plastids which may remain isolated  like Rotifer or may multiply by gemmation to form higher aggregates termed zoides."
merils: "A boy's play  called also fivepenny morris. See Morris."
merit: "To acquire desert; to gain value; to receive benefit; to profit."
meritot: "A play of children  in swinging on ropes or the like till they are dizzy."
merkin: "Originally  a wig; afterwards a mop for cleaning cannon."
merlin: "A small European falcon (Falco lithofalco  or F. aesalon)."
merlon: "One of the solid parts of a battlemented parapet; a battlement. See Illust. of Battlement."
merluce: "The European hake; -- called also herring hake and sea pike."
mermaid: "A fabled marine creature  typically represented as having the upper part like that of a woman and the lower like a fish; a sea nymph sea woman or woman fish."
merman: "The male corresponding to mermaid; a sea man  or man fish."
meros: "The proximal segment of the hind limb; the thigh."
merrily: "In a merry manner; with mirth; with gayety and laughter; jovially. See Mirth  and Merry."
mescal: "A distilled liquor prepared in Mexico from a species of agave. See Agave."
mesiad: "Toward  or on the side toward the mesial plane; mesially; -- opposed to laterad."
mesial: "Middle; median; in  or in the region of the mesial plane; internal; -- opposed to lateral."
mesityl: "A hypothetical radical formerly supposed to exist in mesityl oxide."
mesne: "Middle; intervening; as  a mesne lord that is a lord who holds land of a superior but grants a part of it to another person in which case he is a tenant to the superior but lord or superior to the second grantee and hence is called the mesne lord."
meson: "The mesial plane dividing the body of an animal into similar right and left halves. The line in which it meets the dorsal surface has been called the dorsimeson  and the corresponding ventral edge the ventrimeson."
mesozoa: "A group of very lowly organized  wormlike parasites including the Dicyemata. They are found in cephalopods. See Dicyemata."
mesquit: "A name for two trees of the southwestern part of North America  the honey mesquite and screw-pod mesquite."
messiad: "A German epic poem on the Messiah  by Klopstock."
messiah: "The expected king and deliverer of the Hebrews; the Savior; Christ."
mestee: "The offspring of a white person and a quadroon; -- so called in the West Indies."
mestizo: "The offspring of an Indian or a negro and a European or person of European stock."
metal: "To cover with metal; as  to metal a ship's bottom; to metal a road."
metamer: "Any one of several metameric forms of the same substance  or of different substances having the same composition; as xylene has three metamers viz. orthoxylene metaxylene and paraxylene."
metayer: "One who cultivates land for a share (usually one half) of its yield  receiving stock tools and seed from the landlord."
metazoa: "Those animals in which the protoplasmic mass  constituting the egg is converted into a multitude of cells which are metamorphosed into the tissues of the body. A central cavity is commonly developed and the cells around it are at first arranged in two layers -- the ectoderm and endoderm. The group comprises nearly all animals except the Protozoa."
metely: "According to measure or proportion; proportionable; proportionate."
meteor: "Specif.: A transient luminous body or appearance seen in the atmosphere  or in a more elevated region."
methal: "A white waxy substance  found in small quantities in spermaceti as an ethereal salt of several fatty acids and regarded as an alcohol of the methane series."
methane: "A light  colorless gaseous inflammable hydrocarbon CH4; marsh gas. See Marsh gas under Gas."
methide: "A binary compound of methyl with some element; as  aluminium methide Al2(CH3)6."
method: "Classification; a mode or system of classifying natural objects according to certain common characteristics; as  the method of Theophrastus; the method of Ray; the Linnaean method."
methol: "The technical name of methyl alcohol or wood spirit; also  by extension the class name of any of the series of alcohols of the methane series of which methol proper is the type. See Methyl alcohol under Methyl."
methyl: "A hydrocarbon radical  CH3 not existing alone but regarded as an essential residue of methane and appearing as a component part of many derivatives; as methyl alcohol methyl ether methyl amine etc."
metic: "A sojourner; an immigrant; an alien resident in a Grecian city  but not a citizen."
metisse: "The offspring of a white person and a quadroon; an octoroon."
metonic: "Pertaining to  or discovered by Meton the Athenian."
metopic: "Of or pertaining to the forehead or frontal bones; frontal; as  the metopic suture."
metric: "Of or pertaining to the meter as a standard of measurement; of or pertaining to the decimal system of measurement of which a meter is the unit; as  the metric system; a metric measurement."
mettle: "Substance or quality of temperament; spirit  esp. as regards honor courage fortitude ardor etc.; disposition; -- usually in a good sense."
mettled: "Having mettle; high-spirited; ardent; full of fire."
meute: "A cage for hawks; a mew. See 4th Mew  1."
miamis: "A tribe of Indians that formerly occupied the country between the Wabash and Maumee rivers."
miasma: "Infectious particles or germs floating in the air; air made noxious by the presence of such particles or germs; noxious effluvia; malaria."
micella: "A theoretical aggregation of molecules constituting a structural particle of protoplasm  capable of increase or diminution without change in chemical nature."
miche: "To lie hid; to skulk; to act  or carry one's self sneakingly."
micher: "One who skulks  or keeps out of sight; hence a truant; an idler; a thief etc."
micmacs: "A tribe of Indians inhabiting Nova Scotia and New Brunswick."
micr-: "A millionth part of; as  microfarad microohm micrometer."
micron: "A measure of length; the thousandth part of one millimeter; the millionth part of a meter."
midas: "A genus of longeared South American monkeys  including numerous species of marmosets. See Marmoset."
midday: "Of or pertaining to noon; meridional; as  the midday sun."
midden: "An accumulation of refuse about a dwelling place; especially  an accumulation of shells or of cinders bones and other refuse on the supposed site of the dwelling places of prehistoric tribes -- as on the shores of the Baltic Sea and in many other places. See Kitchen middens."
middler: "One of a middle or intermediate class in some schools and seminaries."
midgard: "The middle space or region between heaven and hell; the abode of human beings; the earth."
midge: "A very small fly  abundant in many parts of the United States and Canada noted for the irritating quality of its bite."
midgut: "The middle part of the alimentary canal from the stomach  or entrance of the bile duct to or including the large intestine."
midland: "The interior or central region of a country; -- usually in the plural."
midmain: "The middle part of the main or sea."
midrash: "A talmudic exposition of the Hebrew law  or of some part of it."
midrib: "A continuation of the petiole  extending from the base to the apex of the lamina of a leaf."
mid-sea: "The middle part of the sea or ocean."
midship: "Of or pertaining to  or being in the middle of a ship."
midway: "In the middle of the way or distance; half way."
midweek: "The middle of the week. Also used adjectively."
migrate: "To pass periodically from one region or climate to another for feeding or breeding; -- said of certain birds  fishes and quadrupeds."
mikado: "The popular designation of the hereditary sovereign of Japan."
mileage: "Aggregate length or distance in miles; esp.  the sum of lengths of tracks or wires of a railroad company telegraph company etc."
milfoil: "A common composite herb (Achillea Millefolium) with white flowers and finely dissected leaves; yarrow."
miliary: "One of the small tubercles of Echini."
miliola: "A genus of Foraminifera  having a porcelanous shell with several longitudinal chambers."
milker: "A cow or other animal that gives milk."
milkman: "A man who sells milk or delivers is to customers."
milksop: "A piece of bread sopped in milk; figuratively  an effeminate or weak-minded person."
milled: "Having been subjected to some process of milling."
milling: "The act or employment of grinding or passing through a mill; the process of fulling; the process of making a raised or intented edge upon coin  etc.; the process of dressing surfaces of various shapes with rotary cutters. See Mill."
milldam: "A dam or mound to obstruct a water course  and raise the water to a height sufficient to turn a mill wheel."
millet: "The name of several cereal and forage grasses which bear an abundance of small roundish grains. The common millets of Germany and Southern Europe are Panicum miliaceum  and Setaria Italica."
milli-: "A prefix denoting a thousandth part of; as  millimeter milligram milliampere."
millier: "A weight of the metric system  being one million grams; a metric ton."
million: "The mass of common people; -- with the article the."
milreis: "A Portuguese money of account rated in the treasury department of the United States at one dollar and eight cents; also  a Brazilian money of account rated at fifty-four cents and six mills."
milvus: "A genus of raptorial birds  including the European kite."
mimic: "To assume a resemblance to (some other organism of a totally different nature  or some surrounding object) as a means of protection or advantage."
mimical: "Imitative; characterized by resemblance to other forms; -- applied to crystals which by twinning resemble simple forms of a higher grade of symmetry."
mimicry: "Protective resemblance; the resemblance which certain animals and plants exhibit to other animals and plants or to the natural objects among which they live  -- a characteristic which serves as their chief means of protection against enemies; imitation; mimesis; mimetism."
mimosa: "A genus of leguminous plants  containing many species and including the sensitive plants (Mimosa sensitiva and M. pudica)."
minable: "Such as can be mined; as  minable earth."
minaret: "A slender  lofty tower attached to a mosque and surrounded by one or more projecting balconies from which the summon to prayer is cried by the muezzin."
mince: "A short  precise step; an affected manner."
mincing: "That minces; characterized by primness or affected nicety."
minder: "One to be attended; specif.  a pauper child intrusted to the care of a private person."
mindful: "Bearing in mind; regardful; attentive; heedful; observant."
mining: "Of or pertaining to mines; as  mining engineer; mining machinery; a mining region."
miner: "The chattering  or garrulous honey eater of Australia (Myzantha garrula)."
minerva: "The goddess of wisdom  of war of the arts and sciences of poetry and of spinning and weaving; -- identified with the Grecian Pallas Athene."
minette: "The smallest of regular sizes of portrait photographs."
miniate: "Of or pertaining to the color of red lead or vermilion; painted with vermilion."
minibus: "A kind of light passenger vehicle  carrying four persons."
minimum: "The least quantity assignable  admissible or possible in a given case; hence a thing of small consequence; -- opposed to maximum."
minimus: "The little finger; the fifth digit  or that corresponding to it in either the manus or pes."
minious: "Of the color of red or vermilion."
minium: "A heavy  brilliant red pigment consisting of an oxide of lead Pb3O4 obtained by exposing lead or massicot to a gentle and continued heat in the air. It is used as a cement as a paint and in the manufacture of flint glass. Called also red lead."
miniver: "A fur esteemed in the Middle Ages as a part of costume. It is uncertain whether it was the fur of one animal only or of different animals."
minivet: "A singing bird of India of the family Campephagidae."
minnow: "Any of numerous small American cyprinodont fishes of the genus Fundulus  and related genera. They live both in fresh and in salt water. Called also killifish minny and mummichog."
minos: "A king and lawgiver of Crete  fabled to be the son of Jupiter and Europa. After death he was made a judge in the Lower Regions."
minster: "A church of a monastery. The name is often retained and applied to the church after the monastery has ceased to exist (as Beverly Minster  Southwell Minster etc.) and is also improperly used for any large church."
mintage: "The duty paid to the mint for coining."
mintman: "One skilled in coining  or in coins; a coiner."
minuend: "The number from which another number is to be subtracted."
minuet: "A tune or air to regulate the movements of the dance so called; a movement in suites  sonatas symphonies etc. having the dance form and commonly in 3-4 sometimes 3-8 measure."
minus: "Less; requiring to be subtracted; negative; as  a minus quantity."
minute: "Attentive to small things; paying attention to details; critical; particular; precise; as  a minute observer; minute observation."
minutia: "A minute particular; a small or minor detail; -- used chiefly in the plural."
miocene: "The Miocene period. See Chart of Geology."
mirage: "An optical effect  sometimes seen on the ocean but more frequently in deserts due to total reflection of light at the surface common to two strata of air differently heated. The reflected image is seen commonly in an inverted position while the real object may or may not be in sight. When the surface is horizontal and below the eye the appearance is that of a sheet of water in which the object is seen reflected; when the reflecting surface is above the eye the image is seen projected against the sky. The fata Morgana and looming are species of mirage."
mirza: "The common title of honor in Persia  prefixed to the surname of an individual. When appended to the surname it signifies Prince."
misbear: "To carry improperly; to carry (one's self) wrongly; to misbehave."
miscall: "To call by a bad name; to abuse."
miscue: "A false stroke with a billiard cue  the cue slipping from the ball struck without impelling it as desired."
misdeal: "The act of misdealing; a wrong distribution of cards to the players."
misdo: "To do wrong; to commit a fault."
miserly: "Like a miser; very covetous; sordid; niggardly."
misfall: "To befall  as ill luck; to happen to unluckily."
misfit: "Something that fits badly  as a garment."
misgive: "To give out doubt and apprehension; to be fearful or irresolute."
mishna: "A collection or digest of Jewish traditions and explanations of Scripture  forming the text of the Talmud."
misknow: "To have a mistaken notion of or about."
mislay: "To lay in a place not recollected; to lose."
misle: "A fine rain; a thick mist; mizzle."
mislead: "To lead into a wrong way or path; to lead astray; to guide into error; to cause to mistake; to deceive."
mistake: "Misconception  error which when non-negligent may be ground for rescinding a contract or for refusing to perform it."
mismate: "To mate wrongly or unsuitably; as  to mismate gloves or shoes; a mismated couple."
misname: "To call by the wrong name; to give a wrong or inappropriate name to."
misread: "To read amiss; to misunderstand in reading."
missing: "Absent from the place where it was expected to be found; lost; wanting; not present when called or looked for."
missa: "The service or sacrifice of the Mass."
missal: "Of or pertaining to the Mass  or to a missal or Mass book."
missile: "A weapon thrown or projected or intended to be projcted  as a lance an arrow or a bullet."
missis: "A mistress; a wife; -- so used by the illiterate."
missit: "To sit badly or imperfectly upon; to misbecome."
misstep: "To take a wrong step; to go astray."
misterm: "To call by a wrong name; to miscall."
mistico: "A kind of small sailing vessel used in the Mediterranean. It is rigged partly like a xebec  and partly like a felucca."
mistide: "To happen or come to pass unfortunately; also  to suffer evil fortune."
mistime: "To time wrongly; not to adapt to the time."
mistle: "To fall in very fine drops  as rain."
mistral: "A violent and cold northwest wind experienced in the Mediterranean provinces of France  etc."
mistura: "Sometimes  a liquid medicine containing very active substances and which can only be administered by drops."
misty: "Obscured as if by mist; dim; obscure; clouded; as  misty sight."
misuser: "Unlawful use of a right; use in excess of  or varying from one's right."
misween: "To ween amiss; to misjudge; to distrust; to be mistaken."
misword: "A word wrongly spoken; a cross word."
miting: "A little one; -- used as a term of endearment."
mitome: "The denser part of the protoplasm of a cell."
mitral: "Pertaining to a miter; resembling a miter; as  the mitral valve between the left auricle and left ventricle of the heart."
mitten: "A cover for the wrist and forearm."
mixed: "Formed by mixing; united; mingled; blended. See Mix  v. t. & i."
mixtion: "A kind of cement made of mastic  amber etc. used as a mordant for gold leaf."
mixtly: "With mixture; in a mixed manner; mixedly."
mixture: "An organ stop  comprising from two to five ranges of pipes used only in combination with the foundation and compound stops; -- called also furniture stop. It consists of high harmonics or overtones of the ground tone."
mizzen: "The hindmost of the fore and aft sails of a three-masted vessel; also  the spanker."
moabite: "One of the posterity of Moab  the son of Lot. (Gen. xix. 37.) Also used adjectively."
moate: "To void the excrement  as a bird; to mute."
mobbish: "Like a mob; tumultuous; lawless; as  a mobbish act."
mobcap: "A plain cap or headdress for women or girls; especially  one tying under the chin by a very broad band generally of the same material as the cap itself."
moble: "To wrap the head of in a hood."
mocha: "An Abyssinian weight  equivalent to a Troy grain."
mochila: "A large leather flap which covers the saddletree."
mocking: "Imitating  esp. in derision or so as to cause derision; mimicking; derisive."
mockado: "A stuff made in imitation of velvet; -- probably the same as mock velvet."
modal: "Indicating  or pertaining to some mode of conceiving existence or of expressing thought."
model: "To make a copy or a pattern; to design or imitate forms; as  to model in wax."
modeler: "One who models; hence  a worker in plastic art."
modern: "A person of modern times; -- opposed to ancient."
modest: "Evincing modestly in the actor  author or speaker; not showing presumption; not excessive or extreme; moderate; as a modest request; modest joy."
modesty: "Natural delicacy or shame regarding personal charms and the sexual relation; purity of thought and manners; due regard for propriety in speech or action."
modicum: "A little; a small quantity; a measured simply."
modify: "To limit or reduce in extent or degree; to moderate; to qualify; to lower."
modish: "According to the mode  or customary manner; conformed to the fashion; fashionable; hence conventional; as a modish dress; a modish feast."
modiste: "A female maker of  or dealer in articles of fashion especially of the fashionable dress of ladies; a woman who gives direction to the style or mode of dress."
modius: "A dry measure  containing about a peck."
modocs: "A tribe of warlike Indians formerly inhabiting Northern California. They are nearly extinct."
modular: "Of or pertaining to mode  modulation module or modius; as modular arrangement; modular accent; modular measure."
modulus: "A quantity or coefficient  or constant which expresses the measure of some specified force property or quality as of elasticity strength efficiency etc.; a parameter."
modus: "A fixed compensation or equivalent given instead of payment of tithes in kind  expressed in full by the phrase modus decimandi."
moebles: "Movables; furniture; -- also used in the singular (moeble)."
moggan: "A closely fitting knit sleeve; also  a legging of knitted material."
mogul: "A heavy locomotive for freight traffic  having three pairs of connected driving wheels and a two-wheeled truck."
mohair: "The long silky hair or wool of the Angora goat of Asia Minor; also  a fabric made from this material or an imitation of such fabric."
mohawk: "One of certain ruffians who infested the streets of London in the time of Addison  and took the name from the Mohawk Indians."
mohur: "A British Indian gold coin  of the value of fifteen silver rupees or $7.21."
moidore: "A gold coin of Portugal  valued at about 27s. sterling."
moile: "A kind of high shoe anciently worn."
moineau: "A small flat bastion  raised in the middle of an overlong curtain."
moira: "The deity who assigns to every man his lot."
moire: "A watered  clouded or frosted appearance produced upon either textile fabrics or metallic surfaces."
moisten: "To soften by making moist; to make tender."
molar: "Any one of the teeth back of the incisors and canines. The molar which replace the deciduous or milk teeth are designated as premolars  and those which are not preceded by deciduous teeth are sometimes called true molars. See Tooth."
molasse: "A soft Tertiary sandstone; -- applied to a rock occurring in Switzerland. See Chart of Geology."
molech: "The fire god of the Ammonites  to whom human sacrifices were offered; Moloch."
moline: "The crossed iron that supports the upper millstone by resting on the spindle; a millrind."
mollah: "One of the higher order of Turkish judges; also  a Turkish title of respect for a religious and learned man."
molle: "Lower by a semitone; flat; as  E molle that is E flat."
mollify: "To assuage  as pain or irritation to appease as excited feeling or passion; to pacify; to calm."
molly: "A pet or colloquial name for Mary."
moloch: "A spiny Australian lizard (Moloch horridus). The horns on the head and numerous spines on the body give it a most formidable appearance."
molto: "Much; very; as  molto adagio very slow."
moment: "Tendency  or measure of tendency to produce motion esp. motion about a fixed point or axis."
momier: "A name given in contempt to strict Calvinists in Switzerland  France and some parts of Germany in the early part of the 19th century."
monacid: "Having one hydrogen atom replaceable by a negative or acid atom or radical; capable of neutralizing a monobasic acid; -- said of bases  and of certain metals."
monad: "An atom or radical whose valence is one  or which can combine with be replaced by or exchanged for one atom of hydrogen."
monal: "Any Asiatic pheasant of the genus Lophophorus  as the Impeyan pheasant."
monas: "A genus of minute flagellate Infusoria of which there are many species  both free and attached. See Illust. under Monad."
monday: "The second day of the week; the day following Sunday."
monde: "The world; a globe as an ensign of royalty."
monesia: "The bark  or a vegetable extract brought in solid cakes from South America and believed to be derived from the bark of the tree Chrysophyllum glycyphloeum. It is used as an alterative and astringent."
monesin: "The acrid principle of Monesia  sometimes used as a medicine."
monger: "To deal in; to make merchandise of; to traffic in; -- used chiefly of discreditable traffic."
mongol: "Of or pertaining to Mongolia or the Mongols."
mongoos: "A species of ichneumon (Herpestes griseus)  native of India. Applied also to other allied species as the African banded mongoose (Crossarchus fasciatus)."
