rectus: "A straight muscle; as  the recti of the eye."
recur: "To resort; to have recourse; to go for help."
recurve: "To curve in an opposite or unusual direction; to bend back or down."
recuse: "To refuse or reject  as a judge; to challenge that the judge shall not try the cause."
redact: "To reduce to form  as literary matter; to digest and put in shape (matter for publication); to edit."
redan: "A step or vertical offset in a wall on uneven ground  to keep the parts level."
redbud: "A small ornamental leguminous tree of the American species of the genus Cercis. See Judas tree  under Judas."
redcap: "A specter having long teeth  popularly supposed to haunt old castles in Scotland."
redcoat: "One who wears a red coat; specifically  a red-coated British soldier."
redden: "To grow or become red; to blush."
redeem: "To pay the penalty of; to make amends for; to serve as an equivalent or offset for; to atone for; to compensate; as  to redeem an error."
redfin: "A small North American dace (Minnilus cornutus  or Notropis megalops). The male in the breeding season has bright red fins. Called also red dace and shiner. Applied also to Notropis ardens of the Mississippi valley."
redfish: "The red bass  red drum or drumfish. See the Note under Drumfish."
red-gum: "A name of rust on grain. See Rust."
redhead: "A kind of milkweed (Asclepias Curassavica) with red flowers. It is used in medicine."
redhorn: "Any species of a tribe of butterflies (Fugacia) including the common yellow species and the cabbage butterflies. The antennae are usually red."
red-hot: "Red with heat; heated to redness; as  red-hot iron; red-hot balls. Hence figuratively excited; violent; as a red-hot radical."
redia: "A kind of larva  or nurse which is prroduced within the sporocyst of certain trematodes by asexual generation. It in turn produces in the same way either another generation of rediae or else cercariae within its own body. Called also proscolex and nurse. See Illustration in Appendix."
redness: "The quality or state of being red; red color."
redoubt: "To stand in dread of; to regard with fear; to dread."
redowa: "A Bohemian dance of two kinds  one in triple time like a waltz the other in two-four time like a polka. The former is most in use."
redraft: "A new bill of exchange which the holder of a protected bill draws on the drawer or indorsers  in order to recover the amount of the protested bill with costs and charges."
redraw: "To draw a new bill of exchange  as the holder of a protested bill on the drawer or indorsers."
redress: "One who  or that which gives relief; a redresser."
redroot: "A name of several plants having red roots  as the New Jersey tea (see under Tea) the gromwell the bloodroot and the Lachnanthes tinctoria an endogenous plant found in sandy swamps from Rhode Island to Florida."
redsear: "To be brittle when red-hot; to be red-short."
redskin: "A common appellation for a North American Indian; -- so called from the color of the skin."
redtop: "A kind of grass (Agrostis vulgaris) highly valued in the United States for pasturage and hay for cattle; -- called also English grass  and in some localities herd's grass. See Illustration in Appendix. The tall redtop is Triodia seslerioides."
redub: "To refit; to repair  or make reparation for; hence to repay or requite."
reduce: "To restore to its proper place or condition  as a displaced organ or part; as to reduce a dislocation a fracture or a hernia."
reduit: "A central or retired work within any other work."
reduvid: "Any hemipterous insect of the genus Redivius  or family Reduvidae. They live by sucking the blood of other insects and some species also attack man."
redwing: "A European thrush (Turdus iliacus). Its under wing coverts are orange red. Called also redwinged thrush. (b) A North American passerine bird (Agelarius ph/niceus) of the family Icteridae. The male is black  with a conspicuous patch of bright red bordered with orange on each wing. Called also redwinged blackbird red-winged troupial marsh blackbird and swamp blackbird."
redwood: "An East Indian dyewood  obtained from Pterocarpus santalinus Caesalpinia Sappan and several other trees."
reecho: "The echo of an echo; a repeated or second echo."
reeded: "Formed with channels and ridges like reeds."
reedify: "To edify anew; to build again after destruction."
reeding: "The nurling on the edge of a coin; -- commonly called milling."
reedy: "Having the quality of reed in tone  that is ///// and thin^ as some voices."
reefing: "The process of taking in a reef."
reefer: "A close-fitting lacket or short coat of thick cloth."
reelect: "To elect again; as  to reelect the former governor."
reeler: "The grasshopper warbler; -- so called from its note."
reentry: "A resuming or retaking possession of what one has lately foregone; -- applied especially to land; the entry by a lessor upon the premises leased  on failure of the tenant to pay rent or perform the covenants in the lease."
reeve: "an officer  steward bailiff or governor; -- used chiefly in compounds; as shirereeve now written sheriff; portreeve etc."
refect: "To restore after hunger or fatigue; to refresh."
refel: "To refute; to disprove; as  to refel the tricks of a sophister."
refer: "To direct inquiry for information or a guarantee of any kind  as in respect to one's integrity capacity pecuniary ability and the like; as I referred to his employer for the truth of his story."
referee: "One to whom a thing is referred; a person to whom a matter in dispute has been referred  in order that he may settle it."
refind: "To find again; to get or experience again."
refined: "Freed from impurities or alloy; purifed; polished; cultured; delicate; as; refined gold; refined language; refined sentiments."
refine: "To affect nicety or subtilty in thought or language."
refit: "To obtain repairs or supplies; as  the fleet returned to refit."
refix: "To fix again or anew; to establish anew."
reflect: "To cast reproach; to cause censure or dishonor."
reflux: "A flowing back  as the return of a fluid; ebb; reaction; as the flux and reflux of the tides."
reforge: "To forge again or anew; hence  to fashion or fabricate anew; to make over."
reform: "Amendment of what is defective  vicious corrupt or depraved; reformation; as reform of elections; reform of government."
re-form: "To give a new form to; to form anew; to take form again  or to take a new form; as to re-form the line after a charge."
refound: "imp. & p. p. of Refind  v. t."
refract: "To break the natural course of  as rays of light orr heat when passing from one transparent medium to another of different density; to cause to deviate from a direct course by an action distinct from reflection; as a dense medium refrcts the rays of light as they pass into it from a rare medium."
refrain: "The burden of a song; a phrase or verse which recurs at the end of each of the separate stanzas or divisions of a poetic composition."
refugee: "Especially  one who in times of persecution or political commotion flees to a foreign power or country for safety; as the French refugees who left France after the revocation of the edict of Nantes."
refund: "To supply again with funds; to reimburse."
refusal: "The right of taking in preference to others; the choice of taking or refusing; option; as  to give one the refusal of a farm; to have the refusal of an employment."
refuse: "Refused; rejected; hence; left as unworthy of acceptance; of no value; worthless."
refute: "To disprove and overthrow by argument  evidence or countervailing proof; to prove to be false or erroneous; to confute; as to refute arguments; to refute testimony; to refute opinions or theories; to refute a disputant."
regain: "To gain anew; to get again; to recover  as what has escaped or been lost; to reach again."
regal: "A small portable organ  played with one hand the bellows being worked with the other -- used in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries."
regalia: "A kind of cigar of large size and superior quality; also  the size in which such cigars are classed."
regatta: "Originally  a gondola race in Venice; now a rowing or sailing race or a series of such races."
regency: "A body of men intrusted with vicarious government; as  a regency constituted during a king's minority absence from the kingdom or other disability."
regent: "A resident master of arts of less than five years' standing  or a doctor of less than twwo. They were formerly privileged to lecture in the schools."
regian: "An upholder of kingly authority; a royalist."
regime: "The condition of a river with respect to the rate of its flow  as measured by the volume of water passing different cross sections in a given time uniform regime being the condition when the flow is equal and uniform at all the cross sections."
regius: "Of or pertaining to a king; royal."
reglet: "A strip of wood or metal of the height of a quadrat  used for regulating the space between pages in a chase and also for spacing out title-pages and other open matter. It is graded to different sizes and designated by the name of the type that it matches; as nonpareil reglet pica reglet and the like."
regma: "A kind of dry fruit  consisting of three or more cells each which at length breaks open at the inner angle."
regnal: "Of or pertaining to the reign of a monarch; as  regnal years."
regnant: "Having the chief power; ruling; predominant; prevalent."
regrant: "A renewed of a grant; as  the regrant of a monopoly."
regrate: "To buy in large quantities  as corn provisions etc. at a market or fair with the intention of selling the same again in or near the same place at a higher price -- a practice which was formerly treated as a public offense."
regrede: "To go back; to retrograde  as the apsis of a planet's orbit."
regress: "To go back; to return to a former place or state."
regret: "To experience regret on account of; to lose or miss with a sense of regret; to feel sorrow or dissatisfaction on account of (the happening or the loss of something); as  to regret an error; to regret lost opportunities or friends."
regular: "A soldier belonging to a permanent or standing army; -- chiefly used in the plural."
regulus: "A star of the first magnitude in the constellation Leo; -- called also the Lion's Heart."
rehash: "Something hashed over  or made up from old materials."
rehear: "To hear again; to try a second time; as  to rehear a cause in Chancery."
reign: "To have superior or uncontrolled dominion; to rule."
reins: "The inward impulses; the affections and passions; -- so called because formerly supposed to have their seat in the part of the body where the kidneys are."
reiter: "A German cavalry soldier of the fourteenth and fifteenth centuries."
reject: "To refuse to grant; as  to reject a prayer or request."
rejoin: "To answer  as the defendant to the plaintiff's replication."
rejoint: "Specifically (Arch.)  to fill up the joints of as stones in buildings when the mortar has been dislodged by age and the action of the weather."
rejudge: "To judge again; to reexamine; to review; to call to a new trial and decision."
relais: "A narrow space between the foot of the rampart and the scarp of the ditch  serving to receive the earth that may crumble off or be washed down and prevent its falling into the ditch."
reland: "To go on shore after having embarked; to land again."
relapse: "One who has relapsed  or fallen back into error; a backslider; specifically one who after recanting error returns to it again."
relator: "A private person at whose relation  or in whose behalf the attorney-general allows an information in the nature of a quo warranto to be filed."
relay: "In various forms of telegraphic apparatus  a magnet which receives the circuit current and is caused by it to bring into into action the power of a local battery for performing the work of making the record; also a similar device by which the current in one circuit is made to open or close another circuit in which a current is passing."
relbun: "The roots of the Chilian plant Calceolaria arachnoidea  -- used for dyeing crimson."
release: "The act of opening the exhaust port to allow the steam to escape."
reliant: "Having  or characterized by reliance; confident; trusting."
relic: "Hence  a memorial; anything preserved in remembrance; as relics of youthful days or friendships."
relict: "A woman whose husband is dead; a widow."
relief: "The elevations and surface undulations of a country."
relieve: "To ease of any imposition  burden wrong or oppression by judicial or legislative interposition as by the removal of a grievance by indemnification for losses or the like; to right."
relish: "The projection or shoulder at the side of  or around a tenon on a tenoned piece."
reloan: "A second lending of the same thing; a renewal of a loan."
reluct: "To strive or struggle against anything; to make resistance; to draw back; to feel or show repugnance or reluctance."
remain: "The posthumous works or productions  esp. literary works of one who is dead; as Cecil's"
remand: "The act of remanding; the order for recommitment."
remanet: "A case for trial which can not be tried during the term; a postponed case."
re-mark: "To mark again  or a second time; to mark anew."
remark: "The expression  in speech or writing of something remarked or noticed; the mention of that which is worthy of attention or notice; hence also a casual observation comment or statement; as a pertinent remark."
remast: "To furnish with a new mast or set of masts."
remblai: "Earth or materials made into a bank after having been excavated."
remean: "To give meaning to; to explain the meaning of; to interpret."
remedy: "To apply a remedy to; to relieve; to cure; to heal; to repair; to redress; to correct; to counteract."
remiges: "The quill feathers of the wings of a bird."
remind: "To put (one) in mind of something; to bring to the remembrance of; to bring to the notice or consideration of (a person)."
remiped: "One of a group of aquatic beetles having tarsi adapted for swimming. See Water beetle."
remise: "A giving or granting back; surrender; return; release  as of a claim."
remiss: "The act of being remiss; inefficiency; failure."
remnant: "An unsold end of piece goods  as cloth ribbons carpets etc."
remodel: "To model or fashion anew; to change the form of."
remora: "An instrument formerly in use  intended to retain parts in their places."
remount: "The opportunity of  or things necessary for remounting; specifically a fresh horse with his equipments; as to give one a remount."
removal: "The act of removing  or the state of being removed."
removed: "Distant by degrees in relationship; as  a cousin once removed."
remove: "The act of resetting a horse's shoe."
remover: "One who removes; as  a remover of landmarks."
renal: "Of or pertaining to the kidneys; in the region of the kidneys."
renard: "A fox; -- so called in fables or familiar tales  and in poetry."
renerve: "To nerve again; to give new vigor to; to reinvigorate."
renew: "To become new  or as new; to grow or begin again."
renewal: "The act of renewing  or the state of being renewed; as the renewal of a treaty."
rennet: "The inner  or mucous membrane of the fourth stomach of the calf or other young ruminant; also an infusion or preparation of it used for coagulating milk."
rennin: "A milk-clotting enzyme obtained from the true stomach (abomasum) of a suckling calf. Mol. wt. about 31 000. Also called chymosin rennase and abomasal enzyme."
renown: "To make famous; to give renown to."
rental: "A sum total of rents; as  an estate that yields a rental of ten thousand dollars a year."
rente: "In France  interest payable by government on indebtedness; the bonds shares stocks etc. which represent government indebtedness."
renter: "To restore the original design of  by working in new warp; -- said with reference to tapestry."
rentier: "One who has a fixed income  as from lands stocks or the like."
repace: "To pace again; to walk over again in a contrary direction."
repack: "To pack a second time or anew; as  to repack beef; to repack a trunk."
repaint: "To paint anew or again; as  to repaint a house; to repaint the ground of a picture."
repair: "Condition with respect to soundness  perfectness etc.; as a house in good or bad repair; the book is out of repair."
repand: "Having a slightly undulating margin; -- said of leaves."
reparel: "A change of apparel; a second or different suit."
repass: "To pass or go back; to move back; as  troops passing and repassing before our eyes."
repast: "To supply food to; to feast; to take food."
repay: "To pay anew  or a second time as a debt."
repeal: "Revocation; abrogation; as  the repeal of a statute; the repeal of a law or a usage."
repeat: "A mark  or series of dots placed before and after or often only at the end of a passage to be repeated in performance."
repel: "To act with force in opposition to force impressed; to exercise repulsion."
repent: "To cause to have sorrow or regret; -- used impersonally."
replace: "To put in a new or different place."
replait: "To plait or fold again; to fold  as one part over another again and again."
replum: "The framework of some pods  as the cress which remains after the valves drop off."
reply: "That which is said  written or done in answer to what is said written or done by another; an answer; a response."
repose: "That harmony or moderation which affords rest for the eye; -- opposed to the scattering and division of a subject into too many unconnected parts  and also to anything which is overstrained; as a painting may want repose."
reposit: "To cause to rest or stay; to lay away; to lodge  as for safety or preservation; to place; to store."
reprint: "A second or a new impression or edition of any printed work; specifically  the publication in one country of a work previously published in another."
reproof: "An expression of blame or censure; especially  blame expressed to the face; censure for a fault; chiding; reproach."
reprove: "To express disapprobation of; as  to reprove faults."
reptant: "Creeping; crawling; -- said of reptiles  worms etc."
repugn: "To fight against; to oppose; to resist."
repute: "Specifically: Good character or reputation; credit or honor derived from common or public opinion; -- opposed to disrepute."
request: "To address with a request; to ask."
requin: "The man-eater  or white shark (Carcharodon carcharias); -- so called on account of its causing requiems to be sung."
require: "To ask as a favor; to request."
requite: "To repay; in a good sense  to recompense; to return (an equivalent) in good; to reward; in a bad sense to retaliate; to return (evil) for evil; to punish."
reredos: "The open hearth  upon which fires were lighted immediately under the louver in the center of ancient halls."
resail: "To sail again; also  to sail back as to a former port."
resale: "A sale at second hand  or at retail; also a second sale."
resaw: "To saw again; specifically  to saw a balk or a timber which has already been squared into dimension lumber as joists boards etc."
rescind: "Specifically  to vacate or make void as an act by the enacting authority or by superior authority; to repeal; as to rescind a law a resolution or a vote; to rescind a decree or a judgment."
rescue: "The retaking by a party captured of a prize made by the enemy."
reseat: "To put a new seat  or new seats in; as to reseat a theater; to reseat a chair or trousers."
resect: "To cut or pare off; to remove by cutting."
reseda: "A grayish green color  like that of the flowers of mignonette."
reseize: "To take possession of  as lands and tenements which have been disseized."
resell: "To sell again; to sell what has been bought or sold; to retail."
resend: "To send on from an intermediate station by means of a repeater."
resent: "To give forth an odor; to smell; to savor."
reserve: "Funds kept on hand to meet liabilities."
reset: "To harbor or secrete; to hide  as stolen goods or a criminal."
reship: "To engage one's self again for service on board of a vessel after having been discharged."
residue: "Any positive or negative number that differs from a given number by a multiple of a given modulus; thus  if 7 is the modulus and 9 the given number the numbers -5 2 16 23 etc. are residues."
re-sign: "To affix one's signature to  a second time; to sign again."
resign: "To commit to the care of; to consign."
resile: "To start back; to recoil; to recede from a purpose."
resin: "Any one of a class of yellowish brown solid inflammable substances  of vegetable origin which are nonconductors of electricity have a vitreous fracture and are soluble in ether alcohol and essential oils but not in water; specif. pine resin (see Rosin)."
resinic: "Pertaining to  or obtained from resin; as the resinic acids."
resist: "A substance used to prevent a color or mordant from fixing on those parts to which it has been applied  either by acting machanically in preventing the color etc. from reaching the cloth or chemically in changing the color so as to render it incapable of fixing itself in the fibers.. The pastes prepared for this purpose are called resist pastes."
resolve: "That which has been resolved on or determined; decisive conclusion; fixed purpose; determination; also  legal or official determination; a legislative declaration; a resolution."
resort: "That to which one resorts or looks for help; resource; refuge."
respite: "To relieve by a pause or interval of rest."
respond: "A half pier or pillar attached to a wall to support an arch."
resting: "a. & n. from Rest  v. t. & i."
restem: "To stem  or move against; as to restem a current."
restful: "Giving rest; freeing from toil  trouble etc."
restive: "Uneasy; restless; averse to standing still; fidgeting about; -- applied especially to horses."
resty: "Disposed to rest; indisposed toexercton; sluggish; also  restive."
result: "The decision or determination of a council or deliberative assembly; a resolve; a decree."
resume: "To begin again; to recommence  as something which has been interrupted; as to resume an argument or discourse."
retable: "A shelf behind the altar  for display of lights vases of wlowers etc."
retail: "To distribute in small portions or at second hand; to tell again or to many (what has been told or done); to report; as  to retail slander."
retake: "To take from a captor; to recapture; as  to retake a ship or prisoners."
retaker: "One who takes again what has been taken; a recaptor."
retch: "To care for; to heed; to reck."
retene: "A white crystalline hydrocarbon  polymeric with benzene. It is extracted from pine tar and is also found in certain fossil resins."
retiary: "Armed with a net; hence  skillful to entangle."
retina: "The delicate membrane by which the back part of the globe of the eye is lined  and in which the fibers of the optic nerve terminate. See Eye."
retinic: "Of or pertaining to resin; derived from resin; specifically  designating an acid found in certain fossil resins and hydrocarbons."
retinol: "A hydrocarbon oil obtained by the distillation of resin  -- used in printer's ink."
retinue: "The body of retainers who follow a prince or other distinguished person; a train of attendants; a suite."
retiped: "A bird having small polygonal scales covering the tarsi."
retired: "Withdrawn from active duty or business; as  a retired officer; a retired physician."
retire: "A call sounded on a bugle  announcing to skirmishers that they are to retire or fall back."
retort: "A vessel in which substances are subjected to distillation or decomposition by heat. It is made of different forms and materials for different uses  as a bulb of glass with a curved beak to enter a receiver for general chemical operations or a cylinder or semicylinder of cast iron for the manufacture of gas in gas works."
retouch: "A partial reworking as of a painting a sculptor's clay model or the like."
retrace: "To trace over again  or renew the outline of as a drawing; to draw again."
retract: "The pricking of a horse's foot in nailing on a shoe."
retreat: "To make a retreat; to retire from any position or place; to withdraw; as  the defeated army retreated from the field."
retrial: "A secdond trial  experiment or test; a second judicial trial as of an accused person."
retro-: "A prefix or combining form signifying backward  back; as retroact to act backward; retrospect a looking back."
retry: "To try (esp. judicially) a second time; as  to retry a case; to retry an accused person."
rettery: "A place or establishment where flax is retted. See Ret."
retting: "A place where flax is retted; a rettery."
retund: "To blunt; to turn  as an edge; figuratively to cause to be obtuse or dull; as to retund confidence."
return: "The turnings and windings of a trench or mine."
retuse: "Having the end rounded and slightly indented; as  a retuse leaf."
reunion: "An assembling of persons who have been separated  as of a family or the members of a disbanded regiment; an assembly so composed."
reunite: "To unite again; to join after separation or variance."
revamp: "To vamp again; hence  to patch up; to reconstruct."
reveal: "The side of an opening for a window  doorway or the like between the door frame or window frame and the outer surface of the wall; or where the opening is not filled with a door etc. the whole thickness of the wall; the jamb."
revelry: "The act of engaging in a revel; noisy festivity; reveling."
revenge: "The disposition to revenge; a malignant wishing of evil to one who has done us an injury."
revenue: "The annual yield of taxes  excise customs duties rents etc. which a nation state or municipality collects and receives into the treasury for public use."
revere: "To regard with reverence  or profound respect and affection mingled with awe or fear; to venerate; to reverence; to honor in estimation."
revest: "To take effect or vest again  as a title; to revert to former owner; as the title or right revests in A after alienation."
revet: "To face  as an embankment with masonry wood or other material."
revie: "To make a retort; to bandy words."
review: "A lesson studied or recited for a second time."
revisal: "The act of revising  or reviewing and reexamining for correction and improvement; revision; as the revisal of a manuscript; the revisal of a proof sheet; the revisal of a treaty."
revise: "A second proof sheet; a proof sheet taken after the first or a subsequent correction."
revival: "Revivification  as of a metal. See Revivification 2."
revive: "To restore or reduce to its natural or metallic state; as  to revive a metal after calcination."
revivor: "Revival of a suit which is abated by the death or marriage of any of the parties  -- done by a bill of revivor."
revoice: "To refurnish with a voice; to refit  as an organ pipe so as to restore its tone."
revolve: "Hence  to turn over and over in the mind; to reflect repeatedly upon; to consider all aspects of."
reward: "Compensation or remuneration for services; a sum of money paid or taken for doing  or forbearing to do some act."
reword: "To alter the wording of; to restate in other words; as  to reword an idea or a passage."
reynard: "An appelation applied after the manner of a proper name to the fox. Same as Renard."
rhabdom: "One of numerous minute rodlike structures formed of two or more cells situated behind the retinulae in the compound eyes of insects  etc. See Illust. under Ommatidium."
rhachis: "A central cord of the ovary of nematodes."
rh/tic: "Pertaining to  or of the same horizon as certain Mesozoic strata of the Rhetian Alps. These strata are regarded as closing the Triassic period. See the Chart of Geology."
rhamnus: "A genus of shrubs and small trees; buckthorn. The California Rhamnus Purshianus and the European R. catharticus are used in medicine. The latter is used for hedges."
rhaphe: "The continuation of the seed stalk along the side of an anatropous ovule or seed  forming a ridge or seam."
rheae: "A suborder of struthious birds including the rheas."
rheic: "Pertaining to  or designating an acid (commonly called chrysophanic acid) found in rhubarb (Rheum)."
rhemish: "Of or pertaining to Rheimis  or Reima in France."
rhetian: "Pertaining to the ancient Rhaeti  or Rhaetians or to Rhaetia their country; as the Rhetian Alps now the country of Tyrol and the Grisons."
rheum: "A serous or mucous discharge  especially one from the eves or nose."
rheumy: "Of or pertaining to rheum; abounding in  or causing rheum; affected with rheum."
rhinal: "Og or pertaining to the nose or olfactory organs."
rhino-: "A combining form from Greek //  /// the nose as in rhinolith rhinology."
rhizine: "A rootlike filament or hair growing from the stems of mosses or on lichens; a rhizoid."
rhodic: "Of or pertaining to rhodium; containing rhodium."
rhodium: "A rare element of the light platinum group. It is found in platinum ores  and obtained free as a white inert metal which it is very difficult to fuse. Symbol Rh. Atomic weight 104.1. Specific gravity 12."
rhubarb: "The root of several species of Rheum  used much as a cathartic medicine."
rhumb: "A line which crosses successive meridians at a constant angle; -- called also rhumb line  and loxodromic curve. See Loxodromic."
rhusma: "A mixtire of caustic lime and orpiment  or tersulphide of arsenic -- used in the depilation of hides."
rhymer: "One who makes rhymes; a versifier; -- generally in contempt; a poor poet; a poetaster."
rhymery: "The art or habit of making rhymes; rhyming; -- in contempt."
riant: "Laughing; laughable; exciting gayety; gay; merry; delightful to the view  as a landscape."
ribbed: "Intercalated with slate; -- said of a seam of coal."
ribbing: "An assemblage or arrangement of ribs  as the timberwork for the support of an arch or coved ceiling the veins in the leaves of some plants ridges in the fabric of cloth or the like."
ribband: "A long  narrow strip of timber bent and bolted longitudinally to the ribs of a vessel to hold them in position and give rigidity to the framework."
ribbon: "To adorn with  or as with ribbons; to mark with stripes resembling ribbons."
ribes: "A genus of shrubs including gooseberries and currants of many kinds."
ribwort: "A species of plantain (Plantago lanceolata) with long  narrow ribbed leaves; -- called also rib grass ripple grass ribwort plantain."
riches: "That which appears rich  sumptuous precious or the like."
ricinic: "Pertaining to  or derived from castor oil; formerly designating an acid now called ricinoleic acid."
ricinus: "A genus of plants of the Spurge family  containing but one species (R. communis) the castor-oil plant. The fruit is three-celled and contains three large seeds from which castor oil iss expressed. See Palma Christi."
ricker: "A stout pole for use in making a rick  or for a spar to a boat."
rickets: "A disease which affects children  and which is characterized by a bulky head crooked spine and limbs depressed ribs enlarged and spongy articular epiphyses tumid abdomen and short stature together with clear and often premature mental faculties. The essential cause of the disease appears to be the nondeposition of earthy salts in the osteoid tissues. Children afflicted with this malady stand and walk unsteadily. Called also rachitis."
rickety: "Feeble in the joints; imperfect; weak; shaky."
rictal: "Of or pertaining to the rictus; as  rictal bristles."
rictus: "The gape of the mouth  as of birds; -- often resricted to the corners of the mouth."
ridable: "Suitable for riding; as  a ridable horse; a ridable road."
riddler: "One who speaks in  or propounds riddles."
riding: "A district in charge of an excise officer."
rideau: "A small mound of earth; ground slightly elevated; a small ridge."
ridgy: "Having a ridge or ridges; rising in a ridge."
rietboc: "The reedbuck  a South African antelope (Cervicapra arundinacea); -- so called from its frequenting dry places covered with high grass or reeds. Its color is yellowish brown. Called also inghalla and rietbok."
riffle: "A trough or sluice having cleats  grooves or steps across the bottom for holding quicksilver and catching particles of gold when auriferous earth is washed; also one of the cleats grooves or steps in such a trough. Also called ripple."
riffler: "A curved file used in carving wool and marble."
rifling: "The system of grooves in a rifled gun barrel or cannon."
rifle: "To whet with a rifle. See Rifle  n. 3."
rigging: "DRess; tackle; especially (Naut.)  the ropes chains etc. that support the masts and spars of a vessel and serve as purchases for adjusting the sails etc. See Illustr. of Ship and Sails."
rigel: "A fixed star of the first magnitude in the left foot of the constellation Orion."
rigger: "A cylindrical pulley or drum in machinery."
right: "Hence  to regain an upright position as a ship or boat after careening."
righter: "One who sets right; one who does justice or redresses wrong."
rightly: "According to truth or fact; correctly; not erroneously; exactly."
rigid: "Hence  not lax or indulgent; severe; inflexible; strict; as a rigid father or master; rigid discipline; rigid criticism; a rigid sentence."
rigoll: "A musical instrument formerly in use  consisting of several sticks bound together but separated by beads and played with a stick with a ball at its end."
rille: "One of certain narrow  crooked valleys seen by aid of the telescope on the surface of the moon."
rimbase: "A short cylinder connecting a trunnion with the body of a cannon. See Illust. of Cannon."
rimer: "A tool for shaping the rimes of a ladder."
rimmer: "An implement for cutting  trimming or ornamenting the rim of anything as the edges of pies etc.; also a reamer."
rimose: "Having long and nearly parallel clefts or chinks  like those in the bark of trees."
ringed: "Wearning a wedding ring; hence  lawfully wedded."
ringent: "Having the lips widely separated and gaping like an open mouth; as a ringent bilabiate corolla."
ringer: "A horse that is not entitled to take part in a race  but is fraudulently got into it."
ringlet: "A curl; especially  a curl of hair."
rioter: "One who engages in a riot. See Riot  n. 3."
riotous: "Partaking of the nature of an unlawful assembly or its acts; seditious."
riotry: "The act or practice of rioting; riot."
ripen: "To mature; to fit or prepare; to bring to perfection; as  to ripen the judgment."
ripieno: "Filling up; supplementary; supernumerary; -- a term applied to those instruments which only swell the mass or tutti of an orchestra  but are not obbligato."
ripost: "A quick and sharp refort; a repartee."
ripple: "the residual AC component in the DC current output from a rectifier  expressed as a percentage of the steady component of the current."
ripply: "Having ripples; as  ripply water; hence resembling the sound of rippling water; as ripply laughter; a ripply cove."
riprap: "To form a riprap in or upon."
ripsaw: "A handsaw with coarse teeth which have but a slight set  used for cutting wood in the direction of the fiber; -- called also ripping saw."
rising: "That which rises; a tumor; a boil."
riser: "A feed head. See under Feed  n."
risible: "Used in  or expressing laughter; as risible muscles."
rissoid: "Any one of very numerous species of small spiral gastropods of the genus Rissoa  or family Rissoidae found both in fresh and salt water."
rissole: "A small ball of rich minced meat or fish  covered with pastry and fried."
ritual: "A book containing the rites to be observed."
rivage: "A duty paid to the crown for the passage of vessels on certain rivers."
rivalry: "The act of rivaling  or the state of being a rival; a competition."
river: "To hawk by the side of a river; to fly hawks at river fowl."
rivered: "Supplied with rivers; as  a well rivered country."
rivet: "Hence  to fasten firmly; to make firm strong or immovable; as to rivet friendship or affection."
rivulet: "A small stream or brook; a streamlet."
rizzar: "To dry in the sun; as  rizzared haddock."
roach: "To cut off  as a horse's mane so that the part left shall stand upright."
roadbed: "In railroads  the bed or foundation on which the superstructure (ties rails etc.) rests; in common roads the whole material laid in place and ready for travel."
roadway: "A road; especially  the part traveled by carriages."
roaring: "An affection of the windpipe of a horse  causing a loud peculiar noise in breathing under exertion; the making of the noise so caused. See Roar v. i. 5."
roaster: "A pig  or other article of food fit for roasting."
robber: "One who robs; in law  one who feloniously takes goods or money from the person of another by violence or by putting him in fear."
robbery: "The crime of robbing. See Rob  v. t. 2."
robing: "The act of putting on a robe."
robin: "Any one of several Asiatic birds; as  the Indian robins. See Indian robin below."
robinet: "A military engine formerly used for throwing darts and stones."
robinia: "A genus of leguminous trees including the common locust of North America (Robinia Pseudocacia)."
robust: "Requiring strength or vigor; as  robust employment."
rochet: "The red gurnard  or gurnet. See Gurnard."
rocking: "Having a swaying  rolling or back-and-forth movement; used for rocking."
rockery: "A mound formed of fragments of rock  earth etc. and set with plants."
rocket: "To rise straight up; said of birds; usually in the present participle or as an adjective."
rocky: "Fig.: Not easily impressed or affected; hard; unfeeling; obdurate; as  a rocky bosom."
rocoa: "The orange-colored pulp covering the seeds of the tropical plant Bixa Orellana  from which annotto is prepared. See Annoto."
rococo: "Of or pertaining to the style called rococo; like rococo; florid; fantastic."
rodsman: "One who carries and holds a leveling staff  or rod in a surveying party."
roebuck: "A small European and Asiatic deer (Capreolus capraea) having erect  cylindrical branched antlers forked at the summit. This the smallest European deer is very nimble and graceful. It always prefers a mountainous country or high grounds."
rogue: "To destroy (plants that do not come up to a required standard)."
rokee: "Parched Indian corn  pounded up and mixed with sugar; -- called also yokeage."
rolling: "Having gradual  rounded undulations of surface; as a rolling country; rolling land."
roller: "Any species of small ground snakes of the family Tortricidae."
rolley: "A small wagon used for the underground work of a mine."
rollic: "To move or play in a careless  swaggering manner with a frolicsome air; to frolic; to sport; commonly in the form rollicking."
rollway: "A place prepared for rolling logs into a stream."
romaic: "The modern Greek language  now usually called by the Greeks Hellenic or Neo-Hellenic."
roman: "Roman type  letters or print collectively; -- in distinction from Italics."
romance: "To write or tell romances; to indulge in extravagant stories."
romanic: "Related to the Roman people by descent; -- said especially of races and nations speaking any of the Romanic tongues."
romany: "The language spoken among themselves by the gypsies."
romaunt: "A romantic story in verse; as  the """"Romaunt of the Rose."
romeite: "A mineral of a hyacinth or honey-yellow color  occuring in square octahedrons. It is an antimonate of calcium."
romic: "A method of notation for all spoken sounds  proposed by Mr. Sweet; -- so called because it is based on the common Roman-letter alphabet. It is like the palaeotype of Mr. Ellis in the general plan but simpler."
romish: "Belonging or relating to Rome  or to the Roman Catholic Church; -- frequently used in a disparaging sense; as the Romish church; the Romish religion ritual or ceremonies."
rompish: "Given to rude play; inclined to romp."
rompu: "Broken  as an ordinary; cut off or broken at the top as a chevron a bend or the like."
ronchil: "An American marine food fish (Bathymaster signatus) of the North Pacific coast  allied to the tilefish."
ronde: "A kind of script in which the heavy strokes are nearly upright  giving the characters when taken together a round look."
rondel: "Specifically  a particular form of rondeau containing fourteen lines in two rhymes the refrain being a repetition of the first and second lines as the seventh and eighth and again as the thirteenth and fourteenth."
rondle: "A round mass  plate or disk; especially (Metal.) the crust or scale which forms upon the surface of molten metal in the crucible."
rongeur: "An instrument for removing small rough portions of bone."
ronnen: "obs. p. p. of Renne  to run."
roofing: "The wedging  as of a horse or car against the top of an underground passage."
roomful: "As much or many as a room will hold; as  a roomful of men."
roomy: "Having ample room; spacious; large; as  a roomy mansion; a roomy deck."
roost: "Fig.; To lodge; to rest; to sleep."
rooster: "The male of the domestic fowl; a cock."
rooted: "Having taken root; firmly implanted; fixed in the heart."
rootcap: "A mass of parenchymatous cells which covers and protects the growing cells at the end of a root; a pileorhiza."
rooter: "One who  or that which roots; one that tears up by the roots."
rootery: "A pile of roots  set with plants mosses etc. and used as an ornamental object in gardening."
ropily: "In a ropy manner; in a viscous or glutinous manner."
roquet: "To hit another's ball with one's own."
roral: "Of or pertaining to dew; consisting of dew; dewy."
roric: "Of or pertaining to dew; resembling dew; dewy."
rorqual: "A very large North Atlantic whalebone whale (Physalus antiquorum  or Balaenoptera physalus). It has a dorsal fin and strong longitudinal folds on the throat and belly. Called also razorback."
rosacic: "Pertaining to  or designating an acid (called also lithic acid) found in certain red precipitates of urine. See Uric."
rosalia: "A form of melody in which a phrase or passage is successively repeated  each time a step or half step higher; a melodic sequence."
rosary: "A coin bearing the figure of a rose  fraudulently circulated in Ireland in the 13th century for a penny."
roseal: "resembling a rose in smell or color."
roseate: "resembling a rose in color or fragrance; esp.  tinged with rose color; blooming; as roseate beauty; her roseate lips."
rosebay: "An herb (Epilobium spicatum) with showy purple flowers  common in Europe and North America; -- called also great willow herb."
rosebud: "The flower of a rose before it opens  or when but partially open."
rosella: "A beautiful Australian parrakeet (Platycercus eximius) often kept as a cage bird. The head and back of the neck are scarlet  the throat is white the back dark green varied with lighter green and the breast yellow."
roselle: "a malvaceous plant (Hibiscus Sabdariffa) cultivated in the east and West Indies for its fleshy calyxes  which are used for making tarts and jelly and an acid drink."
roseo-: "A prefix (also used adjectively) signifying rose-red; specifically used to designate certain rose-red compounds (called roseo-cobaltic compounds) of cobalt with ammonia. Cf. Luteo-."
roseola: "A rose-colored efflorescence upon the skin  occurring in circumscribed patches of little or no elevation and often alternately fading and reviving; also an acute specific disease which is characterized by an eruption of this character; -- called also rose rash."
rosery: "A place where roses are cultivated; a nursery of roses. See Rosary  1."
rosette: "A flowerlike color marking; as  the rosettes on the leopard."
rosied: "Decorated with roses  or with the color of roses."
rosin: "To rub with rosin  as musicians rub the bow of a violin."
rosland: "heathy land; land full of heather; moorish or watery land."
rosolic: "Pertaining to  or designating a complex red dyestuff (called rosolic acid) which is analogous to rosaniline and aurin. It is produced by oxidizing a mixture of phenol and cresol as a dark red amorphous mass C20H16O3 which forms weak salts with bases and stable ones with acids. Called also methyl aurin and formerly corallin."
roster: "A register or roll showing the order in which officers  enlisted men companies or regiments are called on to serve."
rostral: "Of or pertaining to the beak or snout of an animal  or the beak of a ship; resembling a rostrum esp. the rostra at Rome or their decorations."
rostrum: "A pair of forceps of various kinds  having a beaklike form."
rotal: "Relating to wheels or to rotary motion; rotary."
rotary: "Turning  as a wheel on its axis; pertaining to or resembling the motion of a wheel on its axis; rotatory; as rotary motion."
rotate: "To cause to succeed in turn; esp.  to cause to succeed some one or to be succeeded by some one in office."
rotated: "Turned round  as a wheel; also wheel-shaped; rotate."
rotche: "A very small arctic sea bird (Mergulus alle  or Alle alle) common on both coasts of the Atlantic in winter; -- called also little auk dovekie rotch rotchie and sea dove."
rotella: "Any one of numerous species of small  polished brightcolored gastropods of the genus Rotella native of tropical seas."
rotgut: "Any bad spirituous liquor  especially when adulterated so as to be very deleterious."
rotifer: "One of the Rotifera. See Illust. in Appendix."
rotten: "Not firm or trusty; unsound; defective; treacherous; unsafe; as  a rotten plank bone stone."
rotular: "Of or pertaining to the rotula  or kneepan."
rotunda: "A round building; especially  one that is round both on the outside and inside like the Pantheon at Rome. Less properly but very commonly used for a large round room; as the rotunda of the Capitol at Washington."
rouet: "A small wheel formerly fixed to the pan of firelocks for discharging them."
rouge: "To tint with rouge; as  to rouge the face or the cheeks."
rough: "To cut or make in a hasty  rough manner; -- with out; as to rough out a carving a sketch."
roughly: "In a rough manner; unevenly; harshly; rudely; severely; austerely."
roulade: "A smoothly running passage of short notes (as semiquavers  or sixteenths) uniformly grouped sung upon one long syllable as in Handel's oratorios."
rouleau: "A little roll; a roll of coins put up in paper  or something resembling such a roll."
rounce: "The handle by which the bed of a hand press  holding the form of type etc. is run in under the platen and out again; -- sometimes applied to the whole apparatus by which the form is moved under the platen."
round: "To go or turn round; to wheel about."
rounded: "Modified by contraction of the lip opening; labialized; labial. See Guide to Pronunciation  / 11."
rounder: "An English game somewhat resembling baseball; also  another English game resembling the game of fives but played with a football."
roundly: "Without regard to detail; in gross; comprehensively; generally; as  to give numbers roundly."
rousant: "Rising; -- applied to a bird in the attitude of rising; also  sometmes to a bird in profile with wings addorsed."
rouse: "To be exited to thought or action from a state of indolence or inattention."
rousing: "Very great; violent; astounding; as  a rousing fire; a rousing lie."
rouser: "A stirrer in a copper for boiling wort."
roust: "A strong tide or current  especially in a narrow channel."
route: "The course or way which is traveled or passed  or is to be passed; a passing; a course; a road or path; a march."
router: "A plane with a hooked tool protruding far below the sole  for smoothing the bottom of a cavity."
routine: "Any regular course of action or procedure rigidly adhered to by the mere force of habit."
roving: "The act of one who roves or wanders."
rowed: "Formed into a row  or rows; having a row or rows; as a twelve-rowed ear of corn."
rowable: "That may be rowed  or rowed upon."
rowboat: "A boat designed to be propelled by oars instead of sails."
rowdy: "One who engages in rows  or noisy quarrels; a ruffianly fellow."
rowel: "To insert a rowel  or roll of hair or silk into (as the flesh of a horse)."
rowen: "The second growth of grass in a season; aftermath."
rowlock: "A contrivance or arrangement serving as a fulcrum for an oar in rowing. It consists sometimes of a notch in the gunwale of a boat  sometimes of a pair of pins between which the oar rests on the edge of the gunwale sometimes of a single pin passing through the oar or of a metal fork or stirrup pivoted in the gunwale and suporting the oar."
rowport: "An opening in the side of small vessels of war  near the surface of the water to facilitate rowing in calm weather."
royally: "In a royal or kingly manner; like a king; as becomes a king."
royalty: "Hence (Com.)  a duty paid by a manufacturer to the owner of a patent or a copyright at a certain rate for each article manufactured; or a percentage paid to the owner of an article by one who hires the use of it."
rubbish: "Of or pertaining to rubbish; of the quality of rubbish; trashy."
rubble: "The whole of the bran of wheat before it is sorted into pollard  bran etc."
rubella: "An acute specific disease with a dusky red cutaneous eruption resembling that of measles  but unattended by catarrhal symptoms; -- called also German measles."
rubian: "One of several color-producing glycosides found in madder root."
rubican: "Colored a prevailing red  bay or black with flecks of white or gray especially on the flanks; -- said of horses."
rubicon: "A small river which separated Italy from Cisalpine Gaul  the province alloted to Julius Caesar."
rubidic: "Of or pertaining to rubidium; containing rubidium."
ruble: "The unit of monetary value in Russia. It is divided into 100 copecks  and in the gold coin of the realm (as in the five and ten ruble pieces) is worth about 77 cents. The silver ruble is a coin worth about 60 cents."
rubus: "A genus of rosaceous plants  including the raspberry and blackberry."
ruche: "A pile of arched tiles  used to catch and retain oyster spawn."
ruction: "An uproar; a quarrel; a noisy outbreak."
rudder: "Fig.: That which resembles a rudder as a guide or governor; that which guides or governs the course."
ruddle: "To mark with ruddle; to raddle; to rouge."
ruddock: "A piece of gold money; -- probably because the gold of coins was often reddened by copper alloy. Called also red ruddock  and golden ruddock."
ruelle: "A private circle or assembly at a private house; a circle."
ruffe: "A small freshwater European perch (Acerina vulgaris); -- called also pope  blacktail and stone / striped perch."
ruffian: "To play the ruffian; to rage; to raise tumult."
ruffle: "The connected series of large egg capsules  or oothecae of any one of several species of American marine gastropods of the genus Fulgur. See Ootheca."
ruffler: "That which ruffles; specifically  a sewing machine attachment for making ruffles."
rufol: "A phenol derivative of anthracene obtained as a white crystalline substance  which on oxidation produces a red dyestuff related to anthraquinone."
rufous: "Reddish; of a yellowish red or brownish red color; tawny."
rugged: "Vigorous; robust; hardy; -- said of health  physique etc."
rugging: "A coarse kind of woolen cloth  used for wrapping blanketing etc."
rugine: "To scrape or rasp  as a bone; to scale."
rugosa: "An extinct tribe of fossil corals  including numerous species many of them of large size. They are characteristic of the Paleozoic formations. The radiating septs when present are usually in multiples of four. See Cyathophylloid."
rugose: "Wrinkled; full of wrinkles; specifically (Bot.)  having the veinlets sunken and the spaces between them elevated as the leaves of the sage and horehound."
rulable: "That may be ruled; subject to rule; accordant or conformable to rule."
ruling: "A decision or rule of a judge or a court  especially an oral decision as in excluding evidence."
ruler: "A straight or curved strip of wood  metal etc. with a smooth edge used for guiding a pen or pencil in drawing lines. Cf. Rule n. 7 (a)."
rumble: "To cause to pass through a rumble  or shaking machine. See Rumble n. 4."
rumicin: "A yellow crystalline substance found in the root of yellow dock (Rumex crispus) and identical with chrysophanic acid."
rumkin: "A popular or jocular name for a drinking vessel."
rummer: "A large and tall glass  or drinking cup."
rumorer: "A teller of news; especially  one who spreads false reports."
rumper: "A member or a supporter of the Rump Parliament."
rumpus: "A disturbance; noise and confusion; a quarrel."
running: "The discharge from an ulcer or other sore."
runaway: "Very successful; accomplishing success quickly; as  a runaway bestseller."
rundle: "One of the pins or trundles of a lantern wheel."
rundlet: "A small barrel of no certain dimensions. It may contain from 3 to 20 gallons  but it usually holds about 14/ gallons."
runer: "A bard  or learned man among the ancient Goths."
runic: "Of or pertaining to a rune  to runes or to the Norsemen; as runic verses; runic letters; runic names; runic rhyme."
runner: "A tool on which lenses are fastened in a group  for polishing or grinding."
runway: "The beaten path made by deer or other animals in passing to and from their feeding grounds."
rupee: "A silver coin  and money of account in the East Indies."
rupia: "An eruption upon the skin  consisting of vesicles with inflamed base and filled with serous purulent or bloody fluid which dries up forming a blackish crust."
ruption: "A breaking or bursting open; breach; rupture."
rural: "Of or pertaining to agriculture; as  rural economy."
rurales: "The gossamer-winged butterflies; a family of small butterflies  including the hairstreaks violets and theclas."
rurally: "In a rural manner; as in the country."
rusher: "One who strewed rushes on the floor at dances."
rusine: "Of  like or pertaining to a deer of the genus Rusa which includes the sambur deer (Rusa Aristotelis) of India."
rusma: "A depilatory made of orpiment and quicklime  and used by the Turks. See Rhusma."
russet: "An apple  or a pear of a russet color; as the English russet and the Roxbury russet."
russian: "A native or inhabitant of Russia; the language of Russia."
russify: "To Russianize; as  to Russify conquered tribes."
rustful: "Full of rust; resembling rust; causing rust; rusty."
rustic: "A rural person having a natural simplicity of character or manners; an artless  unaffected person."
rustle: "A quick succession or confusion of small sounds  like those made by shaking leaves or straw by rubbing silk or the like; a rustling."
rustler: "A bovine animal that can care for itself in any circumstances; also  an alert energetic driving person."
rusty: "Resembling  or covered with a substance resembling rust; affected with rust; rubiginous."
rutic: "Pertaining to  or obtained from rue (Ruta); as rutic acid now commonly called capric acid."
rutile: "A mineral usually of a reddish brown color  and brilliant metallic adamantine luster occurring in tetragonal crystals. In composition it is titanium dioxide like octahedrite and brookite."
rutin: "A glucoside resembling  but distinct from quercitrin. Rutin is found in the leaves of the rue (Ruta graveolens) and other plants and obtained as a bitter yellow crystalline substance which yields quercitin on decomposition."
ruttier: "A chart of a course  esp. at sea."
ruttle: "A rattling sound in the throat arising from difficulty of breathing; a rattle."
ryder: "A gold coin of Zealand [Netherlands] equal to 14 florins  about $ 5.60."
rytina: "A genus of large edentulous sirenians  allied to the dugong and manatee including but one species (R. Stelleri); -- called also Steller's sea cow."
sabal: "A genus of palm trees including the palmetto of the Southern United States."
sabbat: "In mediaeval demonology  the nocturnal assembly in which demons and sorcerers were thought to celebrate their orgies."
sabbath: "Fig.: A time of rest or repose; intermission of pain  effort sorrow or the like."
sabella: "A genus of tubicolous annelids having a circle of plumose gills around the head."
sabian: "An adherent of the Sabian religion; a worshiper of the heavenly bodies."
sabicu: "The very hard wood of a leguminous West Indian tree (Lysiloma Sabicu)  valued for shipbuilding."
sable: "To render sable or dark; to drape darkly or in black."
sabot: "A thick  circular disk of wood to which the cartridge bag and projectile are attached in fixed ammunition for cannon; also a piece of soft metal attached to a projectile to take the groove of the rifling."
saccade: "A sudden  violent check of a horse by drawing or twitching the reins on a sudden and with one pull."
saccate: "Of or pertaining to the Saccata  a suborder of ctenophores having two pouches into which the long tentacles can be retracted."
saccule: "A little sac; specifically  the sacculus of the ear."
sachem: "A chief of a tribe of the American Indians; a sagamore."
sachet: "A scent bag  or perfume cushion to be laid among handkerchiefs garments etc. to perfume them."
sacking: "Stout  coarse cloth of which sacks bags etc. are made."
sackage: "The act of taking by storm and pillaging; sack."
sackbut: "A brass wind instrument  like a bass trumpet so contrived that it can be lengthened or shortened according to the tone required; -- said to be the same as the trombone."
sacker: "One who sacks; one who takes part in the storm and pillage of a town."
sacral: "Of or pertaining to the sacrum; in the region of the sacrum."
sacred: "Solemnly devoted  in a bad sense as to evil vengeance curse or the like; accursed; baleful."
sacrist: "A sacristan; also  a person retained in a cathedral to copy out music for the choir and take care of the books."
sacro-: "A combining form denoting connection with  or relation to the sacrum as in sacro-coccygeal sacro-iliac sacrosciatic."
sacrum: "That part of the vertebral column which is directly connected with  or forms a part of the pelvis."
sadda: "A work in the Persian tongue  being a summary of the Zend-Avesta or sacred books."
saddle: "Hence: To fix as a charge or burden upon; to load; to encumber; as  to saddle a town with the expense of bridges and highways."
saddled: "Having a broad patch of color across the back  like a saddle; saddle-backed."
sadiron: "An iron for smoothing clothes; a flatiron."
sadness: "Quality of being sad  or unhappy; gloominess; sorrowfulness; dejection."
safely: "In a safe manner; danger  injury loss or evil consequences."
saffron: "To give color and flavor to  as by means of saffron; to spice."
sagging: "A bending or sinking between the ends of a thing  in consequence of its own or an imposed weight; an arching downward in the middle as of a ship after straining. Cf. Hogging."
sagathy: "A mixed woven fabric of silk and cotton  or silk and wool; sayette; also a light woolen fabric."
sagene: "A Russian measure of length equal to about seven English feet."
sagger: "The clay of which such pots or cases are made."
sagitta: "A genus of transparent  free-swimming marine worms having lateral and caudal fins and capable of swimming rapidly. It is the type of the class Chaetognatha."
sagum: "The military cloak of the Roman soldiers."
sagus: "A genus of palms from which sago is obtained."
saheb: "A respectful title or appellation given to Europeans of rank."
saiga: "An antelope (Saiga Tartarica) native of the plains of Siberia and Eastern Russia. The male has erect annulated horns  and tufts of long hair beneath the eyes and ears."
sailing: "The art of managing a vessel; seamanship; navigation; as  globular sailing; oblique sailing."
sailer: "A ship or other vessel; -- with qualifying words descriptive of speed or manner of sailing; as  a heavy sailer; a fast sailer."
sailor: "One who follows the business of navigating ships or other vessels; one who understands the practical management of ships; one of the crew of a vessel; a mariner; a common seaman."
saint: "To act or live as a saint."
sainted: "Entered into heaven; -- a euphemism for dead."
saintly: "Like a saint; becoming a holy person."
saithe: "The pollock  or coalfish; -- called also sillock."
saiva: "One of an important religious sect in India which regards Siva with peculiar veneration."
sakti: "The divine energy  personified as the wife of a deity (Brahma Vishnu Siva etc.); the female principle."
salable: "Capable of being sold; fit to be sold; finding a ready market."
salad: "A dish composed of chopped meat or fish  esp. chicken or lobster mixed with lettuce or other vegetables and seasoned with oil vinegar mustard and other condiments; as chicken salad; lobster salad."
salam: "A salutation or compliment of ceremony in the east by word or act; an obeisance  performed by bowing very low and placing the right palm on the forehead."
salary: "To pay  or agree to pay a salary to; to attach salary to; as to salary a clerk; to salary a position."
salep: "The dried tubers of various species of Orchis  and Eulophia. It is used to make a nutritious beverage by treating the powdered preparation with hot water."
salic: "Of or pertaining to the Salian Franks  or to the Salic law so called."
salicin: "A glucoside found in the bark and leaves of several species of willow (Salix) and poplar  and extracted as a bitter white crystalline substance."
salicyl: "The hypothetical radical of salicylic acid and of certain related compounds."
salient: "A salient angle or part; a projection."
salify: "To form a salt with; to convert into a salt; as  to salify a base or an acid."
saline: "A metallic salt; esp.  a salt of potassium sodium lithium or magnesium used in medicine."
salite: "A massive lamellar variety of pyroxene  of a dingy green color."
salix: "A tree or shrub of any kind of willow."
sally: "Transgression of the limits of soberness or steadiness; act of levity; wild gayety; frolic; escapade."
salmis: "A ragout of partly roasted game stewed with sauce  wine bread and condiments suited to provoke appetite."
salmon: "Of a reddish yellow or orange color  like that of the flesh of the salmon."
salol: "A white crystalline substance consisting of phenol salicylate."
salon: "An apartment for the reception of company; hence  in the plural fashionable parties; circles of fashionable society."
saloon: "Popularly  a public room for specific uses; esp. a barroom or grogshop; as a drinking saloon; an eating saloon; a dancing saloon."
saloop: "An aromatic drink prepared from sassafras bark and other ingredients  at one time much used in London."
salpa: "A genus of transparent  tubular free-swimming oceanic tunicates found abundantly in all the warmer latitudes. See Illustration in Appendix."
salpinx: "The Eustachian tube  or the Fallopian tube."
salse: "A mud volcano  the water of which is often impregnated with salts whence the name."
salsola: "A genus of plants including the glasswort. See Glasswort."
saltant: "In a leaping position; springing forward; -- applied especially to the squirrel  weasel and rat also to the cat greyhound monkey etc."
saltcat: "A mixture of salt  coarse meal lime etc. attractive to pigeons."
salter: "One who makes  sells or applies salt; one who salts meat or fish."
saltern: "A building or place where salt is made by boiling or by evaporation; salt works."
saltire: "A St. Andrew's cross  or cross in the form of an X -- one of the honorable ordinaries."
saltly: "With taste of salt; in a salt manner."
salute: "A token of respect or honor for some distinguished or official personage  for a foreign vessel or flag or for some festival or event as by presenting arms by a discharge of cannon volleys of small arms dipping the colors or the topsails etc."
salve: "To save  as a ship or goods from the perils of the sea."
salver: "A tray or waiter on which anything is presented."
salvia: "A genus of plants including the sage. See Sage."
salvo: "A salute paid by a simultaneous  or nearly simultaneous firing of a number of cannon."
salvor: "One who assists in saving a ship or goods at sea  without being under special obligation to do so."
samara: "A dry  indehiscent usually one-seeded winged fruit as that of the ash maple and elm; a key or key fruit."
sambo: "A colloquial or humorous appellation for a negro; sometimes  the offspring of a black person and a mulatto; a zambo."
sambuke: "An ancient stringed instrument used by the Greeks  the particular construction of which is unknown."
sambur: "An East Indian deer (Rusa Aristotelis) having a mane on its neck. Its antlers have but three prongs. Called also gerow. The name is applied to other species of the genus Rusa  as the Bornean sambur (R. equina)."
samiel: "A hot and destructive wind that sometimes blows  in Turkey from the desert. It is identical with the simoom of Arabia and the kamsin of Syria."
samite: "A species of silk stuff  or taffeta generally interwoven with gold."
sammier: "A machine for pressing the water from skins in tanning."
samovar: "A metal urn used in Russia for making tea. It is filled with water  which is heated by charcoal placed in a pipe with chimney attached which passes through the urn."
sampan: "A Chinese boat from twelve to fifteen feet long  covered with a house and sometimes used as a permanent habitation on the inland waters."
sample: "To take or to test a sample or samples of; as  to sample sugar teas wools cloths."
sampler: "A pattern; a specimen; especially  a collection of needlework patterns as letters borders etc. to be used as samples or to display the skill of the worker."
samshu: "A spirituous liquor distilled by the Chinese from the yeasty liquor in which boiled rice has fermented under pressure."
samson: "An Israelite of Bible record (see Judges xiii.)  distinguished for his great strength; hence a man of extraordinary physical strength."
sanable: "Capable of being healed or cured; susceptible of remedy."
sanctum: "A sacred place; hence  a place of retreat; a room reserved for personal use; as an editor's sanctum."
sandal: "An overshoe with parallel openings across the instep."
sanders: "An old name of sandalwood  now applied only to the red sandalwood. See under Sandalwood."
sandish: "Approaching the nature of sand; loose; not compact."
sandix: "A kind of minium  or red lead made by calcining carbonate of lead but inferior to true minium."
sandman: "A mythical person who makes children sleepy  so that they rub their eyes as if there were sand in them."
sandpit: "A pit or excavation from which sand is or has been taken."
sandre: "A Russian fish (Lucioperca sandre) which yields a valuable oil  called sandre oil used in the preparation of caviare."
sandy: "Of the color of sand; of a light yellowish red color; as  sandy hair."
sangu: "The Abyssinian ox (Bos / Bibos  Africanus) noted for the great length of its horns. It has a hump on its back."
sanhita: "A collection of vedic hymns  songs or verses forming the first part of each Veda."
sanicle: "Any plant of the umbelliferous genus Sanicula  reputed to have healing powers."
sanies: "A thin  serous fluid commonly discharged from ulcers or foul wounds."
sanity: "The condition or quality of being sane; soundness of health of body or mind  especially of the mind; saneness."
sanjak: "A district or a subvision of a vilayet."
sankha: "A chank shell (Turbinella pyrum); also  a shell bracelet or necklace made in India from the chank shell."
sankhya: "A Hindoo system of philosophy which refers all things to soul and a rootless germ called prakriti  consisting of three elements goodness passion and darkness."
sannup: "A male Indian; a brave; -- correlative of squaw."
santal: "A colorless crystalline substance  isomeric with piperonal but having weak acid properties. It is extracted from sandalwood."
santees: "One of the seven confederated tribes of Indians belonging to the Sioux  or Dakotas."
santon: "A Turkish saint; a kind of dervish  regarded by the people as a saint: also a hermit."
sapajou: "Any one of several species of South American monkeys of the genus Cebus  having long and prehensile tails. Some of the species are called also capuchins. The bonnet sapajou (C. subcristatus) the golden-handed sapajou (C. chrysopus) and the white-throated sapajou (C. hypoleucus) are well known species. See Capuchin."
sapid: "Having the power of affecting the organs of taste; possessing savor  or flavor."
sapient: "Wise; sage; discerning; -- often in irony or contempt."
saponin: "A poisonous glucoside found in many plants  as in the root of soapwort (Saponaria) in the bark of soap bark (Quillaia) etc. It is extracted as a white amorphous powder which occasions a soapy lather in solution and produces a local anaesthesia. Formerly called also struthiin quillaiin senegin polygalic acid etc. By extension any one of a group of related bodies of which saponin proper is the type."
saponul: "A soapy mixture obtained by treating an essential oil with an alkali; hence  any similar compound of an essential oil."
sapor: "Power of affecting the organs of taste; savor; flavor; taste."
sapper: "One who saps; specifically (Mil.)  one who is employed in working at saps building and repairing fortifications and the like."
sappho: "Any one of several species of brilliant South American humming birds of the genus Sappho  having very bright-colored and deeply forked tails; -- called also firetail."
sapsago: "A kind of Swiss cheese  of a greenish color flavored with melilot."
sapwood: "The alburnum  or part of the wood of any exogenous tree next to the bark being that portion of the tree through which the sap flows most freely; -- distinguished from heartwood."
saracen: "Anciently  an Arab; later a Mussulman; in the Middle Ages the common term among Christians in Europe for a Mohammedan hostile to the crusaders."
sarcasm: "A keen  reproachful expression; a satirical remark uttered with some degree of scorn or contempt; a taunt; a gibe; a cutting jest."
sarcel: "One of the outer pinions or feathers of the wing of a bird  esp. of a hawk."
sarcina: "A genus of bacteria found in various organic fluids  especially in those those of the stomach associated with certain diseases. The individual organisms undergo division along two perpendicular partitions so that multiplication takes place in two directions giving groups of four cubical cells. Also used adjectively; as a sarcina micrococcus; a sarcina group."
sarcle: "To weed  or clear of weeds with a hoe."
sarco-: "A combining form from Gr. sa`rx  sa`rkos flesh; as sarcophagous flesh-eating; sarcology."
sarcode: "A name applied by Dujardin in 1835 to the gelatinous material forming the bodies of the lowest animals; protoplasm."
sarcoid: "Resembling flesh  or muscle; composed of sarcode."
sarcoma: "A tumor of fleshy consistence; -- formerly applied to many varieties of tumor  now restricted to a variety of malignant growth made up of cells resembling those of fetal development without any proper intercellular substance."
sarcous: "Fleshy; -- applied to the minute structural elements  called sarcous elements or sarcous disks of which striated muscular fiber is composed."
sardius: "A precious stone  probably a carnelian one of which was set in Aaron's breastplate."
saree: "The principal garment of a Hindoo woman. It consists of a long piece of cloth  which is wrapped round the middle of the body a portion being arranged to hang down in front and the remainder passed across the bosom over the left shoulder."
sargo: "Any one of several species of sparoid fishes belonging to Sargus  Pomadasys and related genera; -- called also sar and saragu."
sarigue: "A small South American opossum (Didelphys opossum)  having four white spots on the face."
sarking: "Thin boards for sheathing  as above the rafters and under the shingles or slates and for similar purposes."
sarment: "A prostrate filiform stem or runner  as of the strawberry. See Runner."
sarong: "A sort of petticoat worn by both sexes in Java and the Malay Archipelago."
saros: "A Chaldean astronomical period or cycle  the length of which has been variously estimated from 3 600 years to 3 600 days or a little short of 10 years."
sarplar: "A large bale or package of wool  containing eighty tods or 2 240 pounds in weight."
sarpo: "A large toadfish of the Southern United States and the Gulf of Mexico (Batrachus tau  var. pardus)."
sarsen: "One of the large sandstone blocks scattered over the English chalk downs; -- called also sarsen stone  and Druid stone."
sashery: "A collection of sashes; ornamentation by means of sashes."
sashoon: "A kind of pad worn on the leg under the boot."
sasin: "The Indian antelope (Antilope bezoartica  / cervicapra) noted for its beauty and swiftness. It has long spiral divergent horns."
sasse: "A sluice or lock  as in a river to make it more navigable."
satan: "The grand adversary of man; the Devil  or Prince of darkness; the chief of the fallen angels; the archfiend."
satchel: "A little sack or bag for carrying papers  books or small articles of wearing apparel; a hand bag."
sateen: "A kind of dress goods made of cotton or woolen  with a glossy surface resembling satin."
satiety: "The state of being satiated or glutted; fullness of gratification  either of the appetite or of any sensual desire; fullness beyond desire; an excess of gratification which excites wearisomeness or loathing; repletion; satiation."
satin: "A silk cloth  of a thick close texture and overshot woof which has a glossy surface."
satinet: "A kind of cloth made of cotton warp and woolen filling  used chiefly for trousers."
satiny: "Like or composed of satin; glossy; as  to have a satiny appearance; a satiny texture."
satire: "Keeness and severity of remark; caustic exposure to reprobation; trenchant wit; sarcasm."
satisfy: "To make payment or atonement; to atone."
satrap: "The governor of a province in ancient Persia; hence  a petty autocrat despot."
satrapy: "The government or jurisdiction of a satrap; a principality."
sauce: "A soft crayon for use in stump drawing or in shading with the stump."
saucer: "A shallow socket for the pivot of a capstan."
saucily: "In a saucy manner; impudently; with impertinent boldness."
saucy: "Expressive of  or characterized by impudence; impertinent; as a saucy eye; saucy looks."
sauger: "An American fresh-water food fish (Stizostedion Canadense); -- called also gray pike  blue pike hornfish land pike sand pike pickering and pickerel."
sault: "A rapid in some rivers; as  the Sault Ste. Marie."
saurel: "Any carangoid fish of the genus Trachurus  especially T. trachurus or T. saurus of Europe and America and T. picturatus of California. Called also skipjack and horse mackerel."
sauria: "A division of Reptilia formerly established to include the Lacertilia  Crocodilia Dinosauria and other groups. By some writers the name is restricted to the Lacertilia."
sauroid: "Resembling a saurian superficially; as  a sauroid fish."
saury: "A slender marine fish (Scomberesox saurus) of Europe and America. It has long  thin beaklike jaws. Called also billfish gowdnook gawnook skipper skipjack skopster lizard fish and Egypt herring."
savable: "Capable of  or admitting of being saved."
savanna: "A tract of level land covered with the vegetable growth usually found in a damp soil and warm climate  -- as grass or reeds -- but destitute of trees."
savant: "A man of learning; one versed in literature or science; a person eminent for acquirements."
savior: "Specifically: The (or our  your etc.) Savior he who brings salvation to men; Jesus Christ the Redeemer."
savor: "To taste or smell with pleasure; to delight in; to relish; to like; to favor."
savory: "An aromatic labiate plant (Satureia hortensis)  much used in cooking; -- also called summer savory."
savoy: "A variety of the common cabbage (Brassica oleracea major)  having curled leaves -- much cultivated for winter use."
sawder: "A corrupt spelling and pronunciation of solder."
sawdust: "Dust or small fragments of wood (or of stone  etc.) made by the cutting of a saw."
sawfish: "Any one of several species of elasmobranch fishes of the genus Pristis. They have a sharklike form  but are more nearly allied to the rays. The flattened and much elongated snout has a row of stout toothlike structures inserted along each edge forming a sawlike organ with which it mutilates or kills its prey."
sawfly: "Any one of numerous species of hymenopterous insects belonging to the family Tenthredinidae. The female usually has an ovipositor containing a pair of sawlike organs with which she makes incisions in the leaves or stems of plants in which to lay the eggs. The larvae resemble those of Lepidoptera."
sawmill: "A mill for sawing  especially one for sawing timber or lumber."
saw-set: "An instrument used to set or turn the teeth of a saw a little sidewise  that they may make a kerf somewhat wider than the thickness of the blade to prevent friction; -- called also saw-wrest."
saxhorn: "A name given to a numerous family of brass wind instruments with valves  invented by Antoine Joseph Adolphe Sax (known as Adolphe Sax) of Belgium and Paris and much used in military bands and in orchestras."
saxon: "Of or pertaining to Saxony or its inhabitants."
saxonic: "Relating to the Saxons or Anglo- Saxons."
saying: "That which is said; a declaration; a statement  especially a proverbial one; an aphorism; a proverb."
sayette: "A mixed stuff  called also sagathy. See Sagathy."
'sblood: "An abbreviation of God's blood; -- used as an oath."
scabby: "Diseased with the scab  or mange; mangy."
scala: "A term applied to any one of the three canals of the cochlea."
scalar: "In the quaternion analysis  a quantity that has magnitude but not direction; -- distinguished from a vector which has both magnitude and direction."
scald: "One of the ancient Scandinavian poets and historiographers; a reciter and singer of heroic poems  eulogies etc. among the Norsemen; more rarely a bard of any of the ancient Teutonic tribes."
scaldic: "Of or pertaining to the scalds of the Norsemen; as  scaldic poetry."
scale: "To lead up by steps; to ascend."
scaled: "Having feathers which in form  color or arrangement somewhat resemble scales; as the scaled dove."
scaling: "Serving as an aid in clambering; as  a scaling ladder used in assaulting a fortified place."
scalene: "A triangle having its sides and angles unequal."
scaler: "One who  or that which scales; specifically a dentist's instrument for removing tartar from the teeth."
scallop: "To bake in scallop shells or dishes; to prepare with crumbs of bread or cracker  and bake. See Scalloped oysters below."
scalp: "To make a small  quick profit by slight fluctuations of the market; -- said of brokers who operate in this way on their own account."
scalpel: "A small knife with a thin  keen blade -- used by surgeons and in dissecting."
scalper: "A person who buys tickets for entertainment or sports events and sells them at a profit  often at a much higher price. Also ticket scalper."
scaly: "Composed of scales lying over each other; as  a scaly bulb; covered with scales; as a scaly stem."
scamp: "To perform in a hasty  neglectful or imperfect manner; to do superficially."
scandia: "A chemical earth  the oxide of scandium."
scandic: "Of or pertaining to scandium; derived from  or containing scandium."
scantle: "To scant; to be niggard of; to divide into small pieces; to cut short or down."
scapple: "To dress in any way short of fine tooling or rubbing  as stone."
scapula: "One of the plates from which the arms of a crinoid arise."
scare: "Fright; esp.  sudden fright produced by a trifling cause or originating in mistake."
scarify: "To stir the surface soil of  as a field."
scaroid: "Of or pertaining to the Scaridae  a family of marine fishes including the parrot fishes."
scarp: "To cut down perpendicularly  or nearly so; as to scarp the face of a ditch or a rock."
scarry: "Like a scar  or rocky eminence; containing scars."
scarus: "A Mediterranean food fish (Sparisoma scarus) of excellent quality and highly valued by the Romans; -- called also parrot fish."
scatch: "A kind of bit for the bridle of a horse; -- called also scatchmouth."
scath: "To do harm to; to injure; to damage; to waste; to destroy."
scatter: "To be dispersed or dissipated; to disperse or separate; as  clouds scatter after a storm."
