scauper: "A tool with a semicircular edge  -- used by engravers to clear away the spaces between the lines of an engraving."
scaur: "A precipitous bank or rock; a scar."
scavage: "A toll or duty formerly exacted of merchant strangers by mayors  sheriffs etc. for goods shown or offered for sale within their precincts."
scena: "An accompanied dramatic recitative  interspersed with passages of melody or followed by a full aria."
scene: "To exhibit as a scene; to make a scene of; to display."
scenery: "Sum of scenes or views; general aspect  as regards variety and beauty or the reverse in a landscape; combination of natural views as woods hills etc."
scent: "The power of smelling; the sense of smell; as  a hound of nice scent; to divert the scent."
sceptre: "To endow with the scepter  or emblem of authority; to invest with royal authority."
schema: "An outline or image universally applicable to a general conception  under which it is likely to be presented to the mind; as five dots in a line are a schema of the number five; a preceding and succeeding event are a schema of cause and effect."
schemer: "One who forms schemes; a projector; esp.  a plotter; an intriguer."
schene: "An Egyptian or Persian measure of length  varying from thirty-two to sixty stadia."
scherzo: "A playful  humorous movement commonly in 3-4 measure which often takes the place of the old minuet and trio in a sonata or a symphony."
schesis: "A figure of speech whereby the mental habitude of an adversary or opponent is feigned for the purpose of arguing against him."
schism: "Division or separation; specifically (Eccl.)  permanent division or separation in the Christian church; breach of unity among people of the same religious faith; the offense of seeking to produce division in a church without justifiable cause."
schisma: "An interval equal to half a comma."
schist: "Any crystalline rock having a foliated structure (see Foliation) and hence admitting of ready division into slabs or slates. The common kinds are mica schist  and hornblendic schist consisting chiefly of quartz with mica or hornblende and often feldspar."
schizo-: "A combining form denoting division or cleavage; as  schizogenesis reproduction by fission or cell division."
schlich: "The finer portion of a crushed ore  as of gold lead or tin separated by the water in certain wet processes."
scholar: "In English universities  an undergraduate who belongs to the foundation of a college and receives support in part from its revenues."
school: "To tutor; to chide and admonish; to reprove; to subject to systematic discipline; to train."
schorly: "Pertaining to  or containing schorl; as schorly granite."
science: "To cause to become versed in science; to make skilled; to instruct."
sciniph: "Some kind of stinging or biting insect  as a flea a gnat a sandfly or the like."
scion: "Hence  a descendant; an heir; as a scion of a royal stock."
scissel: "The slips or plates of metal out of which circular blanks have been cut for the purpose of coinage."
scissor: "To cut with scissors or shears; to prepare with the aid of scissors."
sciurus: "A genus of rodents comprising the common squirrels."
scoff: "To treat or address with derision; to assail scornfully; to mock at."
scomber: "A genus of acanthopterygious fishes which includes the common mackerel."
scomm: "A flout; a jeer; a gibe; a taunt."
scone: "A cake  thinner than a bannock made of wheat or barley or oat meal."
scoop: "To make hollow  as a scoop or dish; to excavate; to dig out; to form by digging or excavation."
scooper: "The avocet; -- so called because it scoops up the mud to obtain food."
scoot: "To walk fast; to go quickly; to run hastily away."
scopate: "Having the surface closely covered with hairs  like a brush."
scope: "To look at for the purpose of evaluation; usually with out; as  to scope out the area as a camping site."
scopula: "A special tuft of hairs on the leg of a bee."
score: "To mark with parallel lines or scratches; as  the rocks of New England and the Western States were scored in the drift epoch."
scorify: "To reduce to scoria or slag; specifically  in assaying to fuse so as to separate the gangue and earthy material with borax lead soda etc. thus leaving the gold and silver in a lead button; hence to separate from or by means of a slag."
scorn: "To scoff; to mock; to show contumely  derision or reproach; to act disdainfully."
scorner: "One who scorns; a despiser; a contemner; specifically  a scoffer at religion."
scorpio: "A constellation of the zodiac containing the bright star Antares. It is drawn on the celestial globe in the figure of a scorpion."
scorse: "To deal for the purchase of anything; to practice barter."
scotale: "The keeping of an alehouse by an officer of a forest  and drawing people to spend their money for liquor for fear of his displeasure."
scotch: "A slight cut or incision; a score."
scoter: "Any one of several species of northern sea ducks of the genus Oidemia."
scotist: "A follower of (Joannes) Duns Scotus  the Franciscan scholastic (d. 1308) who maintained certain doctrines in philosophy and theology in opposition to the Thomists or followers of Thomas Aquinas the Dominican scholastic."
scotomy: "Obscuration of the field of vision due to the appearance of a dark spot before the eye."
scots: "Of or pertaining to the Scotch; Scotch; Scottish; as  Scots law; a pound Scots (1s. 8d.)."
scourer: "A rover or footpad; a prowling robber."
scouse: "A sailor's dish. Bread scouse contains no meat; lobscouse contains meat  etc. See Lobscouse."
scout: "To go on the business of scouting  or watching the motions of an enemy; to act as a scout."
scovel: "A mop for sweeping ovens; a malkin."
scranch: "To grind with the teeth  and with a crackling sound; to craunch."
scrape: "A disagreeable and embarrassing predicament out of which one can not get without undergoing  as it were a painful rubbing or scraping; a perplexity; a difficulty."
scraper: "One who acquires avariciously and saves penuriously."
scrappy: "Consisting of scraps; fragmentary; lacking unity or consistency; as  a scrappy lecture."
scratch: "Made  done or happening by chance; arranged with little or no preparation; determined by circumstances; haphazard; as a scratch team; a scratch crew for a boat race; a scratch shot in billiards."
scrawl: "Unskillful or inelegant writing; that which is unskillfully or inelegantly written."
scream: "A sharp  shrill cry uttered suddenly as in terror or in pain; a shriek; a screech."
scree: "A pebble; a stone; also  a heap of stones or rocky debris."
screech: "A harsh  shrill cry as of one in acute pain or in fright; a shriek; a scream."
screed: "An harangue; a long tirade on any subject."
screen: "To pass  as coal gravel ashes etc. through a screen in order to separate the coarse from the fine or the worthless from the valuable; to sift."
screw: "To turn one's self uneasily with a twisting motion; as  he screws about in his chair."
scriber: "A sharp-pointed tool  used by joiners for drawing lines on stuff; a marking awl."
scrim: "Thin canvas glued on the inside of panels to prevent shrinking  checking etc."
scrode: "A young codfish  especially when cut open on the back and dressed."
scroll: "Same as Skew surface. See under Skew."
scrotal: "Of or pertaining to the scrotum; as  scrotal hernia."
scrotum: "The bag or pouch which contains the testicles; the cod."
scrow: "A clipping from skins; a currier's cuttings."
scrubby: "Of the nature of scrub; small and mean; stunted in growth; as  a scrubby cur."
scruff: "The nape of the neck; the loose outside skin  as of the back of the neck."
scruple: "To excite scruples in; to cause to scruple."
scuddle: "To run hastily; to hurry; to scuttle."
scudo: "A gold coin of Rome  worth 64 shillings 11 pence sterling or about $ 15.70."
scuff: "To walk without lifting the feet; to proceed with a scraping or dragging movement; to shuffle."
scull: "To impel a boat with a scull or sculls."
sculpin: "The dragonet  or yellow sculpin of Europe (Callionymus lura)."
scumble: "To cover lighty  as a painting or a drawing with a thin wash of opaque color or with color-crayon dust rubbed on with the stump or to make any similar additions to the work so as to produce a softened effect."
scummer: "An instrument for taking off scum; a skimmer."
scummy: "Covered with scum; of the nature of scum."
scunner: "A feeling of disgust or loathing; a strong prejudice; abhorrence; as  to take a scunner against some one."
scupper: "An opening cut through the waterway and bulwarks of a ship  so that water falling on deck may flow overboard; -- called also scupper hole."
scurf: "Minute membranous scales on the surface of some leaves  as in the goosefoot."
scurfy: "Having or producing scurf; covered with scurf; resembling scurf."
scurvy: "A disease characterized by livid spots  especially about the thighs and legs due to extravasation of blood and by spongy gums and bleeding from almost all the mucous membranes. It is accompanied by paleness languor depression and general debility. It is occasioned by confinement innutritious food and hard labor but especially by lack of fresh vegetable food or confinement for a long time to a limited range of food
scutage: "Shield money; commutation of service for a sum of money. See Escuage."
scutate: "Protected or covered by bony or horny plates  or large scales."
scutch: "The woody fiber of flax; the refuse of scutched flax."
scute: "A bony scale of a reptile or fish; a large horny scale on the leg of a bird  or on the belly of a snake."
scuttle: "To sink by making holes through the bottom of; as  to scuttle a ship."
scutum: "One of the two lower valves of the operculum of a barnacle."
scylla: "A dangerous rock on the Italian coast opposite the whirpool Charybdis on the coast of Sicily  -- both personified in classical literature as ravenous monsters. The passage between them was formerly considered perilous; hence the saying """"Between Scylla and Charybdis " signifying a great peril on either hand."
scyphus: "A cup-shaped stem or podetium in lichens. Also called scypha. See Illust. of Cladonia pyxidata  under Lichen."
scythe: "To cut with a scythe; to cut off as with a scythe; to mow."
'sdeath: "An exclamation expressive of impatience or anger."
sea cat: "Any marine siluroid fish  as Aelurichthys marinus and Arinus felis of the eastern coast of the United States. Many species are found on the coasts of Central and South America."
sea-ear: "Any species of ear-shaped shells of the genus Haliotis. See Abalone."
sea fan: "Any gorgonian which branches in a fanlike form  especially Gorgonia flabellum of Florida and the West Indies."
sea fir: "A sertularian hydroid  especially Sertularia abietina which branches like a miniature fir tree."
seagirt: "Surrounded by the water of the sea or ocean; as  a seagirt isle."
sea god: "A marine deity; a fabulous being supposed to live in  or have dominion over the sea or some particular sea or part of the sea as Neptune."
sea hen: "the common guillemot; -- applied also to various other sea birds."
sealer: "A mariner or a vessel engaged in the business of capturing seals."
seamed: "Out of condition; not in good condition; -- said of a hawk."
seaming: "The cord or rope at the margin of a seine  to which the meshes of the net are attached."
seaman: "One whose occupation is to assist in the management of ships at sea; a mariner; a sailor; -- applied both to officers and common mariners  but especially to the latter. Opposed to landman or landsman."
seamark: "Any elevated object on land which serves as a guide to mariners; a beacon; a landmark visible from the sea  as a hill a tree a steeple or the like."
sea mat: "Any bryozoan of the genus Flustra or allied genera which form frondlike corals."
sea mud: "A rich slimy deposit in salt marshes and along the seashore  sometimes used as a manure; -- called also sea ooze."
seamy: "Having a seam; containing seams  or showing them."
seance: "A session  as of some public body; especially a meeting of spiritualists to receive spirit communication so called."
sea pie: "A dish of crust or pastry and meat or fish  etc. cooked together in alternate layers -- a common food of sailors; as a three-decker sea pie."
seaport: "A port on the seashore  or one accessible for seagoing vessels. Also used adjectively; as a seaport town."
seared: "Scorched; cauterized; hence  figuratively insensible; not susceptible to moral influences."
search: "The act of seeking or looking for something; quest; inquiry; pursuit for finding something; examination."
seaside: "The land bordering on  or adjacent to the sea; the seashore. Also used adjectively."
seating: "The act of making seats; also  the material for making seats; as cane seating."
seawant: "The name used by the Algonquin Indians for the shell beads which passed among the Indians as money."
seaware: "Seaweed; esp.  coarse seaweed. See Ware and Sea girdles."
seaweed: "Any marine plant of the class Algae  as kelp dulse Fucus Ulva etc."
sebacic: "Of or pertaining to fat; derived from  or resembling fat; specifically designating an acid (formerly called also sebic and pyroleic acid) obtained by the distillation or saponification of certain oils (as castor oil) as a white crystalline substance."
sebat: "The eleventh month of the ancient Hebrew year  approximately corresponding with February."
secale: "A genus of cereal grasses including rye."
secancy: "A cutting; an intersection; as  the point of secancy of one line by another."
secant: "A right line drawn from the center of a circle through one end of a circular arc  and terminated by a tangent drawn from the other end; the number expressing the ratio line of this line to the radius of the circle. See Trigonometrical function under Function."
secede: "To withdraw from fellowship  communion or association; to separate one's self by a solemn act; to draw off; to retire; especially to withdraw from a political or religious body."
seceder: "One of a numerous body of Presbyterians in Scotland who seceded from the communion of the Established Church  about the year 1733 and formed the Secession Church so called."
secern: "To secrete; as  mucus secerned in the nose."
sechium: "The edible fruit of a West Indian plant (Sechium edule) of the Gourd family. It is soft  pear-shaped and about four inches long and contains a single large seed. The root of the plant resembles a yam and is used for food."
seckel: "A small reddish brown sweet and juicy pear. It originated on a farm near Philadelphia  afterwards owned by a Mr. Seckel."
seclude: "To shut or keep out; to exclude."
second: "Specifically  to support as a motion or proposal by adding one's voice to that of the mover or proposer."
secondo: "The second part in a concerted piece."
secrecy: "The quality of being secretive; fidelity to a secret; forbearance of disclosure or discovery."
secrete: "To separate from the blood and elaborate by the process of secretion; to elaborate and emit as a secretion. See Secretion."
sectant: "One of the portions of space bounded by the three coordinate planes. Specif. (Crystallog.)  one of the parts of a crystal into which it is divided by the axial planes."
sectary: "A sectarian; a member or adherent of a sect; a follower or disciple of some particular teacher in philosophy or religion; one who separates from an established church; a dissenter."
sectile: "Capable of being cut; specifically (Min.)  capable of being severed by the knife with a smooth cut; -- said of minerals."
section: "The description or representation of anything as it would appear if cut through by any intersecting plane; depiction of what is beyond a plane passing through  or supposed to pass through an object as a building a machine a succession of strata; profile."
sectist: "One devoted to a sect; a soetary."
sector: "An astronomical instrument  the limb of which embraces a small portion only of a circle used for measuring differences of declination too great for the compass of a micrometer. When it is used for measuring zenith distances of stars it is called a zenith sector."
secular: "A layman  as distinguished from a clergyman."
secund: "Arranged on one side only  as flowers or leaves on a stalk."
secure: "To get possession of; to make one's self secure of; to acquire certainly; as  to secure an estate."
sedan: "A portable chair or covered vehicle for carrying a single person  -- usually borne on poles by two men. Called also sedan chair."
sedate: "Undisturbed by passion or caprice; calm; tranquil; serene; not passionate or giddy; composed; staid; as  a sedate soul mind or temper."
sedilia: "Seats in the chancel of a church near the altar for the officiating clergy during intervals of service."
seduce: "Specifically  to induce to surrender chastity; to debauch by means of solicitation."
seducer: "One who  or that which seduces; specifically one who prevails over the chastity of a woman by enticements and persuasions."
sedum: "A genus of plants  mostly perennial having succulent leaves and cymose flowers; orpine; stonecrop."
seeing: ") In view of the fact (that); considering; taking into account (that); insmuch as; since; because; -- followed by a dependent clause; as  he did well seeing that he was so young."
seedbox: "A plant (Ludwigia alternifolia) which has somewhat cubical or box-shaped capsules."
seeder: "One who  or that which sows or plants seed."
seedlop: "A vessel in which a sower carries the seed to be scattered."
seedy: "Old and worn out; exhausted; spiritless; also  poor and miserable looking; shabbily clothed; shabby looking; as he looked seedy coat."
seeker: "One of a small heterogeneous sect of the 17th century  in Great Britain who professed to be seeking the true church ministry and sacraments."
seeling: "The rolling or agitation of a ship in a storm."
seemer: "One who seems; one who carries or assumes an appearance or semblance."
seemly: "In a decent or suitable manner; becomingly."
seesaw: "Moving up and down  or to and fro; having a reciprocating motion."
sodden: "To soak; to make heavy with water."
seethe: "To be a state of ebullition or violent commotion; to be hot; to boil."
seether: "A pot for boiling things; a boiler."
seggar: "A case or holder made of fire clay  in which fine pottery is inclosed while baking in the kin."
segment: "To divide or separate into parts in growth; to undergo segmentation  or cleavage as in the segmentation of the ovum."
segno: "A sign. See Al segno  and Dal segno."
seiches: "Local oscillations in level observed in the case of some lakes  as Lake Geneva."
seine: "A large net  one edge of which is provided with sinkers and the other with floats. It hangs vertically in the water and when its ends are brought together or drawn ashore incloses the fish."
seismal: "Of or pertaining to an earthquake; caused by an earthquake."
seizing: "The cord or lashing used for such fastening."
seize: "To bind or fasten together with a lashing of small stuff  as yarn or marline; as to seize ropes."
seizure: "That which is seized  or taken possession of; a thing laid hold of or possessed."
sejeant: "Sitting  as a lion or other beast."
sekes: "A place in a pagan temple in which the images of the deities were inclosed."
selah: "A word of doubtful meaning  occuring frequently in the Psalms; by some supposed to signify silence or a pause in the musical performance of the song."
select: "To choose and take from a number; to take by preference from among others; to pick out; to cull; as  to select the best authors for perusal."
selenic: "Of or pertaining to selenium; derived from  or containing selenium; specifically designating those compounds in which the element has a higher valence as contrasted with selenious compounds."
selfish: "Believing or teaching that the chief motives of human action are derived from love of self."
selfism: "Concentration of one's interests on one's self; self-love; selfishness."
selion: "A short piece of land in arable ridges and furrows  of uncertain quantity; also a ridge of land lying between two furrows."
semele: "A daughter of Cadmus  and by Zeus mother of Bacchus."
semen: "The seed or fecundating fluid of male animals; sperm. It is a white or whitish viscid fluid secreted by the testes  characterized by the presence of spermatozoids to which it owes its generative power."
semi-: "A prefix signifying half  and sometimes partly or imperfectly; as semiannual half yearly; semitransparent imperfectly transparent."
semilor: "A yellowish alloy of copper and zinc. See Simplor."
semined: "Thickly covered or sown  as with seeds."
semita: "A fasciole of a spatangoid sea urchin."
semite: "One belonging to the Semitic race. Also used adjectively."
semitic: "Of or pertaining to Shem or his descendants; belonging to that division of the Caucasian race which includes the Arabs  Jews and related races."
sempre: "Always; throughout; as  sempre piano always soft."
senary: "Of six; belonging to six; containing six."
senate: "In some American colleges  a council of elected students presided over by the president of the college to which are referred cases of discipline and matters of general concern affecting the students."
senator: "A member of the king's council; a king's councilor."
senecas: "A tribe of Indians who formerly inhabited a part of Western New York. This tribe was the most numerous and most warlike of the Five Nations."
senecio: "A very large genus of composite plants including the groundsel and the golden ragwort."
senegin: "A substance extracted from the rootstock of the Polygala Senega (Seneca root)  and probably identical with polygalic acid."
senile: "Of or pertaining to old age; proceeding from  or characteristic of old age; affected with the infirmities of old age; as senile weakness."
senior: "One in the fourth or final year of his collegiate course at an American college; -- originally called senior sophister; also  one in the last year of the course at a professional schools or at a seminary."
senna: "The plants themselves  native to the East but now cultivated largely in the south of Europe and in the West Indies."
sennit: "Plaited straw or palm leaves for making hats."
seï¿½or: "A Spanish title of courtesy corresponding to the English Mr. or Sir; also  a gentleman."
sense: "To perceive by the senses; to recognize."
sensist: "One who  in philosophy holds to sensism."
sensory: "Of or pertaining to the sensorium or sensation; as  sensory impulses; -- especially applied to those nerves and nerve fibers which convey to a nerve center impulses resulting in sensation; also sometimes loosely employed in the sense of afferent to indicate nerve fibers which convey impressions of any kind to a nerve center."
sensual: "Pertaining or peculiar to the philosophical doctrine of sensualism."
sentine: "A place for dregs and dirt; a sink; a sewer."
sepal: "A leaf or division of the calyx."
sephen: "A large sting ray of the genus Trygon  especially T. sephen of the Indian Ocean and the Red Sea. The skin is an article of commerce."
sepia: "Of a dark brown color  with a little red in its composition; also made of or done in sepia."
sepic: "Of or pertaining to sepia; done in sepia; as  a sepic drawing."
sepoy: "A native of India employed as a soldier in the service of a European power  esp. of Great Britain; an Oriental soldier disciplined in the European manner."
sepsin: "A soluble poison (ptomaine) present in putrid blood. It is also formed in the putrefaction of proteid matter in general."
sepsis: "The poisoning of the system by the introduction of putrescent material into the blood."
septal: "Of or pertaining to a septum or septa  as of a coral or a shell."
septate: "Divided by partition or partitions; having septa; as  a septate pod or shell."
septi-: "A combining form meaning seven; as  septifolious seven-leaved; septi-lateral seven-sided."
septum: "One of the transverse partitions dividing the body cavity of an annelid."
sequela: "A morbid phenomenon left as the result of a disease; a disease resulting from another."
sequent: "That which follows as a result; a sequence."
sequin: "An old gold coin of Italy and Turkey. It was first struck at Venice about the end of the 13th century  and afterward in the other Italian cities and by the Levant trade was introduced into Turkey. It is worth about 9s. 3d. sterling or about $2.25. The different kinds vary somewhat in value."
sequoia: "A genus of coniferous trees  consisting of two species Sequoia Washingtoniana syn. S. gigantea the """"big tree"""" of California and S. sempervirens the redwood both of which attain an immense height."
serai: "A palace; a seraglio; also  in the East a place for the accommodation of travelers; a caravansary or rest house."
serang: "The boatswain of a Lascar or East Ondian crew."
serape: "A blanket or shawl worn as an outer garment by the Spanish Americans  as in Mexico."

serein: "A mist  or very fine rain which sometimes falls from a clear sky a few moments after sunset."
serfdom: "The state or condition of a serf."
serge: "A large wax candle used in the ceremonies of various churches."
serial: "A publication appearing in a series or succession of part; a tale  or other writing published in successive numbers of a periodical."

sericin: "A gelatinous nitrogenous material extracted from crude silk and other similar fiber by boiling water; -- called also silk gelatin."
seriema: "A large South American bird (Dicholophus  / Cariama cristata) related to the cranes. It is often domesticated. Called also cariama."
series: "An indefinite number of terms succeeding one another  each of which is derived from one or more of the preceding by a fixed law called the law of the series; as an arithmetical series; a geometrical series."
serin: "A European finch (Serinus hortulanus) closely related to the canary."
serine: "A white crystalline nitrogenous substance obtained by the action of dilute sulphuric acid on silk gelatin."
serious: "Hence  giving rise to apprehension; attended with danger; as a serious injury."

serous: "Of or pertaining to serum; as  the serous glands membranes layers. See Serum."
serpens: "A constellation represented as a serpent held by Serpentarius."
serpigo: "A dry  scaly eruption on the skin; especially a ringworm."

serrous: "Like the teeth off a saw; jagged."
serum: "A thin watery fluid  containing more or less albumin secreted by the serous membranes of the body such as the pericardium and peritoneum."
serval: "An African wild cat (Felis serval) of moderate size. It has rather long legs and a tail of moderate length. Its color is tawny  with black spots on the body and rings of black on the tail."

service: "Act of serving or covering. See Serve  v. t. 13."

sessile: "Permanently attached; -- said of the gonophores of certain hydroids which never became detached."
session: "Hence  also the time period or term during which a court council legislature etc. meets daily for business; or the space of time between the first meeting and the prorogation or adjournment; thus a session of Parliaments is opened with a speech from the throne and closed by prorogation. sestet: "The last six lines of a sonnet."
setting: "That in which something  as a gem is set; as the gold setting of a jeweled pin."

setout: "A display  as of plate equipage etc.; that which is displayed."

sfumato: "Having vague outlines  and colors and shades so mingled as to give a misty appearance; -- said of a painting."
shabble: "A kind of crooked sword or hanger."

shadd: "Rounded stones containing tin ore  lying at the surface of the ground and indicating a vein."

shall: "As an auxiliary  shall indicates a duty or necessity whose obligation is derived from the person speaking; as you shall go; he shall go; that is I order or promise your going. """" since a promise or threat and an authoritative prophecy nearly coincide in significance. In shall with the first person
shallon: "An evergreen shrub (Gaultheria Shallon) of Northwest America; also  its fruit. See Salal-berry."
shallot: "A small kind of onion (Allium Ascalonicum) growing in clusters  and ready for gathering in spring; a scallion or eschalot."
shama: "A saxicoline singing bird (Kittacincla macroura) of India  noted for the sweetness and power of its song. In confinement it imitates the notes of other birds and various animals with accuracy. Its head neck back breast and tail are glossy black the rump white the under parts chestnut."
shaman: "A priest of Shamanism; a wizard among the Shamanists."
shamble: "To walk awkwardly and unsteadily  as if the knees were weak; to shuffle along."

shanny: "The European smooth blenny (Blennius pholis). It is olive-green with irregular black spots  and without appendages on the head."
shape: "A piece which has been roughly forged nearly to the form it will receive when completely forged or fitted."

share: "To have part; to receive a portion; to partake  enjoy or suffer with others."

shatter: "A fragment of anything shattered; -- used chiefly or soley in the phrase into shatters; as  to break a glass into shatters."

shelf: "A piece of timber running the whole length of a vessel inside the timberheads."

sherbet: "A preparation of bicarbonate of soda  tartaric acid sugar etc. variously flavored for making an effervescing drink; -- called also sherbet powder."

shimmer: "A faint  tremulous light; a gleaming; a glimmer."
shingle: "To subject to the process of shindling  as a mass of iron from the pudding furnace."

shinty: "A Scotch game resembling hockey; also  the club used in the game."

shooty: "Sprouting or coming up freely and regularly."

shovel: "To gather up as with a shovel."

showily: "In a showy manner; pompously; with parade."

shyness: "The quality or state of being shy."

siamang: "A gibbon (Hylobates syndactylus)  native of Sumatra. It has the second and third toes partially united by a web."

sicca: "A seal; a coining die; -- used adjectively to designate the silver currency of the Mogul emperors  or the Indian rupee of 192 grains."

signior: "Sir; Mr. The English form and pronunciation for the Italian Signor and the Spanish Seï¿½or."
signore: "Sir; Mr.; -- a title of address or respect among the Italians. Before a noun the form is Signor."
signora: "Madam; Mrs; -- a title of address or respect among the Italians."
sikhs: "A religious sect noted for warlike traits  founded in the Punjab at the end of the 15th century."
silence: "To cause to cease firing  as by a vigorous cannonade; as to silence the batteries of an enemy."

silesia: "A twilled cotton fabric  used for dress linings."

silica: "Silicon dioxide  SiO/. It constitutes ordinary quartz (also opal and tridymite) and is artifically prepared as a very fine white tasteless inodorous powder."

Silicon is characteristically the element of the mineral kingdom as carbon is of the organic world. Symbol Si. Atomic weight 28. Called also silicium."

semious: "Of or pertaining to the Sim/; monkeylike."
simmer: "To cause to boil gently; to cook in liquid heated almost or just to the boiling point."
simnel: "A kind of rich plum cake  eaten especially on Mid-Lent Sunday."
simony: "The crime of buying or selling ecclesiastical preferment; the corrupt presentation of any one to an ecclesiastical benefice for money or reward."
simoon: "A hot  dry suffocating dust-laden wind that blows occasionally in Arabia Syria and neighboring countries generated by the extreme heat of the parched deserts or sandy plains."
simous: "Having a very flat or snub nose  with the end turned up."
simpai: "A long-tailed monkey (Semnopitchecus melalophus) native of Sumatra. It has a crest of black hair. The forehead and cheeks are fawn color  the upper parts tawny and red the under parts white. Called also black-crested monkey and sinpae."
simper: "A constrained  self-conscious smile; an affected silly smile; a smirk."
simpler: "One who collects simples  or medicinal plants; a herbalist; a simplist."
simulty: "Private grudge or quarrel; as  domestic simulties."
sinapic: "Of or pertaining to sinapine; specifically  designating an acid (C11H12O5) related to gallic acid and obtained by the decomposition of sinapine as a white crystalline substance."
sinapis: "A disused generic name for mustard; -- now called Brassica."
since: "Seeing that; because; considering; -- formerly followed by that."
sincere: "Honest; free from hypocrisy or dissimulation; as  a sincere friend; a sincere person."
sinch: "To gird with a sinch; to tighten the sinch or girth of (a saddle); as  to sinch up a sadle."
sindon: "A small rag or pledget introduced into the hole in the cranium made by a trephine."
sinew: "To knit together  or make strong with or as with sinews."
sinewy: "Well braced with  or as if with sinews; nervous; vigorous; strong; firm; tough; as the sinewy Ajax."
sinful: "Tainted with  or full of sin; wicked; iniquitous; criminal; unholy; as sinful men; sinful thoughts."
singe: "A burning of the surface; a slight burn."
singer: "One who sings; especially  one whose profession is to sing."
single: "A hit by a batter which enables him to reach first base only."
singlet: "An unlined or undyed waistcoat; a single garment; -- opposed to doublet."
singult: "A sigh or sobbing; also  a hiccough."
sinical: "Of or pertaining to a sine; employing  or founded upon sines; as a sinical quadrant."
sunken: "Lying on the bottom of a river or other water; sunk."
sinker: "In knitting machines  one of the thin plates blades or other devices that depress the loops upon or between the needles."
sinter: "Dross  as of iron; the scale which files from iron when hammered; -- applied as a name to various minerals."
sintoc: "A kind of spice used in the East Indies  consisting of the bark of a species of Cinnamomum."
siniate: "Having the margin alternately curved inward and outward; having rounded lobes separated by rounded sinuses; sinuous; wavy."
sinuate: "To bend or curve in and out; to wind; to turn; to be sinusous."
sinuous: "Bending in and out; of a serpentine or undulating form; winding; crooked."
siphoid: "A siphon bottle. See under Siphon  n."
siphon: "To convey  or draw off by means of a siphon as a liquid from one vessel to another at a lower level."
sipid: "Having a taste or flavorl savory; sapid."
sippet: "A small sop; a small  thin piece of toasted bread soaked in milk broth or the like; a small piece of toasted or fried bread cut into some special shape and used for garnishing."
si quis: "A notification by a candidate for orders of his intention to inquire whether any impediment may be alleged against him."
sircar: "The government; the supreme authority of the state."
sirdar: "A native chief in Hindostan; a headman."
siredon: "The larval form of any salamander while it still has external gills; especially  one of those which like the axolotl (Amblystoma Mexicanum) sometimes lay eggs while in this larval state but which under more favorable conditions lose their gills and become normal salamanders. See also Axolotl."
siren: "Of or pertaining to a siren; bewitching  like a siren; fascinating; alluring; as a siren song."
sirenia: "An order of large aquatic herbivorous mammals  including the manatee dugong rytina and several fossil genera."
sirkeer: "Any one of several species of Asiatic cuckoos of the genus Taccocua  as the Bengal sirkeer (T. sirkee)."
sirloin: "A loin of beef  or a part of a loin."
sirocco: "An oppressive  relaxing wind from the Libyan deserts chiefly experienced in Italy Malta and Sicily."
sirrah: "A term of address implying inferiority and used in anger  contempt reproach or disrespectful familiarity addressed to a man or boy but sometimes to a woman. In sililoquies often preceded by ah. Not used in the plural."
syruped: "Moistened  covered or sweetened with sirup or sweet juice."
siskin: "The American pinefinch (S. pinus); -- called also pine siskin. See Pinefinch."
sissoo: "A leguminous tree (Dalbergia Sissoo) of the northern parts of India; also  the dark brown compact and durable timber obtained from it. It is used in shipbuilding and for gun carriages railway ties etc."
sister: "To be sister to; to resemble closely."
sistrum: "An instrument consisting of a thin metal frame  through which passed a number of metal rods and furnished with a handle by which it was shaken and made to rattle. It was peculiarly Egyptian and used especially in the worship of Isis. It is still used in Nubia."
sitting: "A brooding over eggs for hatching  as by fowls."
sitfast: "A callosity with inflamed edges  on the back of a horse under the saddle."
sithe: "To cut with a scythe; to scythe."
sittine: "Of or pertaining to the family Sittidae  or nuthatches."
situs: "The method in which the parts of a plant are arranged; also  the position of the parts."
sivan: "The third month of the Jewish ecclesiastical year; -- supposed to correspond nearly with our month of June."
sixfold: "Six times repeated; six times as much or as many."
sixteen: "A symbol representing sixteen units  as 16 or xvi."
sixth: "The interval embracing six diatonic degrees of the scale."
sixty: "A symbol representing sixty units  as 60 lx. or LX."
sizable: "Being of reasonable or suitable size; as  sizable timber; sizable bulk."
sizar: "One of a body of students in the universities of Cambridge (Eng.) and Dublin  who having passed a certain examination are exempted from paying college fees and charges. A sizar corresponded to a servitor at Oxford."
sized: "Having a particular size or magnitude; -- chiefly used in compounds; as  large-sized; common-sized."
sizing: "Food and drink ordered from the buttery by a student."
sizer: "An instrument or tool for bringing anything to an exact size."
sizzle: "A hissing sound  as of something frying over a fire."
skate: "Any one of numerous species of large  flat elasmobranch fishes of the genus Raia having a long slender tail terminated by a small caudal fin. The pectoral fins which are large and broad and united to the sides of the body and head give a somewhat rhombic form to these fishes. The skin is more or less spinose."
skater: "Any one of numerous species of hemipterous insects belonging to Gerris  Pyrrhocoris Prostemma and allied genera. They have long legs and run rapidly over the surface of the water as if skating."
skatol: "A constituent of human faeces formed in the small intestines as a product of the putrefaction of albuminous matter. It is also found in reduced indigo. Chemically it is methyl indol  C9H9N."
skean: "A knife or short dagger  esp. that in use among the Highlanders of Scotland. [Variously spelt.]"
skeel: "A shallow wooden vessel for holding milk or cream."
skeet: "A scoop with a long handle  used to wash the sides of a vessel and formerly to wet the sails or deck."
skein: "A flight of wild fowl (wild geese or the like)."
skelp: "A wrought-iron plate from which a gun barrel or pipe is made by bending and welding the edges together  and drawing the thick tube thus formed."
skelter: "To run off helter-skelter; to hurry; to scurry; -- with away or off."
sketchy: "Containing only an outline or rough form; being in the manner of a sketch; incomplete."
skill: "To make a difference; to signify; to matter; -- used impersonally."
skilled: "Having familiar knowledge united with readiness and dexterity in its application; familiarly acquainted with; expert; skillful; -- often followed by in; as  a person skilled in drawing or geometry."
skillet: "A small vessel of iron  copper or other metal with a handle used for culinary purpose as for stewing meat."
skilts: "A kind of large  coarse short trousers formerly worn."
skimmer: "Any one of several large bivalve shells  sometimes used for skimming milk as the sea clams and large scallops."
skinch: "To give scant measure; to squeeze or pinch in order to effect a saving."
skinful: "As much as a skin can hold."
skinner: "One who deals in skins  pelts or hides."
skinny: "Consisting  or chiefly consisting of skin; wanting flesh."
skippet: "A small round box for keeping records."
skirret: "An umbelliferous plant (Sium  / Pimpinella Sisarum). It is a native of Asia but has been long cultivated in Europe for its edible clustered tuberous roots which are very sweet."
skirt: "To be on the border; to live near the border  or extremity."
skitty: "A rail; as  the water rail (called also skitty cock and skitty coot); the spotted crake (Porzana maruetta) and the moor hen."
skive: "To pare or shave off the rough or thick parts of (hides or leather)."
skiver: "The cutting tool or machine used in splitting leather or skins  as sheepskins."
skiving: "A piece made in paring or splitting leather; specifically  the part from the inner or flesh side."
skunk: "In games of chance and skill: To defeat (an opponent) (as in cards) so that he fails to gain a point  or (in checkers) to get a king."
skyey: "Like the sky; ethereal; being in the sky."
skyish: "Like the sky  or approaching the sky; lofty; ethereal."
skylark: "A lark that mounts and sings as it files  especially the common species (Alauda arvensis) found in Europe and in some parts of Asia and celebrated for its melodious song; -- called also sky laverock. See under Lark."
skysail: "The sail set next above the royal. See Illust. under Sail."
slacken: "A spongy  semivitrifled substance which miners or smelters mix with the ores of metals to prevent their fusion."
slaggy: "Of or pertaining to slag; resembling slag; as  slaggy cobalt."
slake: "To become mixed with water  so that a true chemical combination takes place; as the lime slakes."
slander: "To bring discredit or shame upon by one's acts."
slangy: "Of or pertaining to slang; of the nature of slang; disposed to use slang."
slant: "Inclined from a direct line  whether horizontal or perpendicular; sloping; oblique."
slashed: "Divided into many narrow parts or segments by sharp incisions; laciniate."
slash: "Swampy or wet lands overgrown with bushes."
slasher: "A machine for applying size to warp yarns."
slatch: "The loose or slack part of a rope; slack."
slate: "To set a dog upon; to bait; to slat. See 2d Slat  3."
slater: "Any terrestrial isopod crustacean of the genus Porcellio and allied genera; a sow bug."
slatt: "A slab of stone used as a veneer for coarse masonry."
slatter: "To be careless  negligent or aswkward esp. with regard to dress and neatness; to be wasteful."
slaty: "Resembling slate; having the nature  appearance or properties of slate; composed of thin parallel plates capable of being separated by splitting; as a slaty color or texture."
slavic: "The group of allied languages spoken by the Slavs."
slavish: "Of or pertaining to slaves; such as becomes or befits a slave; servile; excessively laborious; as  a slavish life; a slavish dependance on the great."
slavism: "The common feeling and interest of the Slavonic race."
slayer: "One who slays; a killer; a murderer; a destrroyer of life."
sleave: "To separate  as threads; to divide as a collection of threads; to sley; -- a weaver's term."
sleaved: "Raw; not spun or wrought; as  sleaved thread or silk."
sleazy: "Wanting firmness of texture or substance; thin; flimsy; as  sleazy silk or muslin."
sledge: "A large  heavy hammer usually wielded with both hands; -- called also sledge hammer."
sleek: "To make even and smooth; to render smooth  soft and glossy; to smooth over."
sleep: "A natural and healthy  but temporary and periodical suspension of the functions of the organs of sense as well as of those of the voluntary and rational soul; that state of the animal in which there is a lessened acuteness of sensory perception a confusion of ideas and a loss of mental control followed by a more or less unconscious state."
sleeper: "The lowest  or bottom tier of casks."
sleepy: "Characterized by an absence of watchfulness; as  sleepy security."
sleet: "To snow or hail with a mixture of rain."
sleetch: "Mud or slime  such as that at the bottom of rivers."
sleety: "Of or pertaining to sleet; characterized by sleet; as  a sleety storm; sleety weather."
sleeve: "To furnish with sleeves; to put sleeves into; as  to sleeve a coat."
sleeved: "Having sleeves; furnished with sleeves; -- often in composition; as  long-sleeved."
sleid: "To sley  or prepare for use in the weaver's sley or slaie."
sleigh: "A vehicle moved on runners  and used for transporting persons or goods on snow or ice; -- in England commonly called a sledge."
slender: "Uttered with a thin tone; -- the opposite of broad; as  the slender vowels long e and i."
slepez: "A burrowing rodent (Spalax typhlus)  native of Russia and Asia Minor. It has the general appearance of a mole and is destitute of eyes. Called also mole rat."
sleuth: "The track of man or beast as followed by the scent."
slice: "To clear by means of a slice bar  as a fire or the grate bars of a furnace."
slicer: "One who  or that which slices; specifically the circular saw of the lapidary."
slimly: "In a state of slimness; in a slim manner; slenderly."
slimy: "Of or pertaining to slime; resembling slime; of the nature of slime; viscous; glutinous; also  covered or daubed with slime; yielding or abounding in slime."
sling: "A drink composed of spirit (usually gin) and water sweetened."
slinger: "One who slings  or uses a sling."
slipes: "Sledge runners on which a skip is dragged in a mine."
slip-on: "A kind of overcoat worn upon the shoulders in the manner of a cloak."
sliver: "Bait made of pieces of small fish. Cf. Kibblings."
sloakan: "A species of seaweed. [Spelled also slowcawn.] See 3d Laver."
sloam: "A layer of earth between coal seams."
sloat: "A narrow piece of timber which holds together large pieces; a slat; as  the sloats of a cart."
slocken: "To quench; to allay; to slake. See Slake."
slogan: "The war cry  or gathering word of a Highland clan in Scotland; hence any rallying cry."
sloop: "A vessel having one mast and fore-and-aft rig  consisting of a boom-and-gaff mainsail jibs staysail and gaff topsail. The typical sloop has a fixed bowsprit topmast and standing rigging while those of a cutter are capable of being readily shifted. The sloop usually carries a centerboard and depends for stability upon breadth of beam rather than depth of keel. The two types have rapidly approximated since 1880. One radical distinction is that a slop may carry a centerboard. See Cutter and Illustration in Appendix."
sloping: "Inclining or inclined from the plane of the horizon  or from a horizontal or other right line; oblique; declivous; slanting."
sloppy: "Wet  so as to spatter easily; wet as with something slopped over; muddy; plashy; as a sloppy place walk road."
slouch: "To cause to hang down; to depress at the side; as  to slouth the hat."
slough: "To cast off; to discard as refuse."
sloughy: "Resembling  or of the nature of a slough or the dead matter which separates from living flesh."
sloven: "A man or boy habitually negligent of neathess and order; -- the correlative term to slattern  or slut."
slowly: "In a slow manner; moderately; not rapidly; not early; not rashly; not readly; tardly."
sludger: "A bucket for removing mud from a bored hole; a sand pump."
slugger: "One who strikes heavy blows; hence  a boxer; a prize fighter."
sluice: "To wash with  or in a stream of water running through a sluice; as to sluice eart or gold dust in mining."
sluicy: "Falling copiously or in streams  as from a sluice."
slumber: "Sleep; especially  light sleep; sleep that is not deep or sound; repose."
slump: "The noise made by anything falling into a hole  or into a soft miry place."
slurred: "Marked with a slur; performed in a smooth  gliding style like notes marked with a slur."
slush: "To paint with a mixture of white lead and lime."
slushy: "Abounding in slush; characterized by soft mud or half-melted snow; as  the streets are slushy; the snow is slushy."
slyness: "The quality or state of being sly."
slype: "A narrow passage between two buildings  as between the transept and chapter house of a monastery."
smack: "To make a sharp noise by striking; to crack; as  to smack a whip."
smally: "In a small quantity or degree; with minuteness."
smalt: "A deep blue pigment or coloring material used in various arts. It is a vitreous substance made of cobalt  potash and calcined quartz fused and reduced to a powder."
smarten: "To make smart or spruce; -- usually with up."
smeared: "Having the color mark ings ill defined  as if rubbed; as the smeared dagger moth (Apatela oblinita)."
smear: "Hence  a spot made by or as by an unctuous or adhesive substance; a blot or blotch; a daub; a stain."
smeary: "Tending to smear or soil; adhesive; viscous."
smegma: "The cheesy  sebaceous matter which collects between the glans penis and the foreskin."
smeir: "A salt glaze on pottery  made by adding common salt to an earthenware glaze."
smelt: "To melt or fuse  as ore for the purpose of separating and refining the metal; hence to reduce; to refine; to flux or scorify; as to smelt tin."
smell: "The quality of any thing or substance  or emanation therefrom which affects the olfactory organs; odor; scent; fragrance; perfume; as the smell of mint."
smift: "A match for firing a charge of powder  as in blasting; a fuse."
smilax: "A delicate trailing plant (Myrsiphyllum asparagoides) much used for decoration. It is a native of the Cape of Good Hope."
smile: "Gay or joyous appearance; as  the smiles of spring."
smithy: "The workshop of a smith  esp. a blacksmith; a smithery; a stithy."
smitt: "Fine clay or ocher made up into balls  used for marking sheep."
smock: "To provide with  or clothe in a smock or a smock frock."
smoke: "To subject to the operation of smoke  for the purpose of annoying or driving out; -- often with out; as to smoke a woodchuck out of his burrow."
smolt: "A young salmon two or three years old  when it has acquired its silvery color."
smouch: "A dark soil or stain; a smutch."
smudge: "To smear; to smutch; to soil; to blacken with smoke."
smuggle: "To import or export in violation of the customs laws."
smutch: "To blacken with smoke  soot or coal."
smutty: "Obscene; not modest or pure; as  a smutty saying."
snacot: "A pipefish of the genus Syngnathus. See Pipefish."
snaffle: "To put a snaffle in the mouth of; to subject to the snaffle; to bridle."
'snails: "God's nails  or His nails that is the nails with which the Savior was fastened to the cross; -- an ancient form of oath corresponding to 'Od's bodikins (dim. of body i.e. God's dear body)."
snakish: "Having the qualities or characteristics of a snake; snaky."
snaky: "Covered with serpents; having serpents; as  a snaky rod or wand."
snape: "To bevel the end of a timber to fit against an inclined surface."
snare: "To catch with a snare; to insnare; to entangle; hence  to bring into unexpected evil perplexity or danger."
snarl: "The act of snarling; a growl; a surly or peevish expression; an angry contention."
snarler: "One who makes use of a snarling iron."
snary: "Resembling  or consisting of snares; entangling; insidious."
snast: "The snuff  or burnt wick of a candle."
snatch: "The handle of a scythe; a snead."
sneak: "A ball bowled so as to roll along the ground; -- called also grub."
sneer: "A smile  grin or contortion of the face indicative of contempt; an indirect expression or insinuation of contempt."
sneeze: "A sudden and violent ejection of air with an audible sound  chiefly through the nose."
snell: "A short line of horsehair  gut etc. by which a fishhook is attached to a longer line."
snide: "Tricky; deceptive; contemptible; as  a snide lawyer; snide goods."
sniff: "The act of sniffing; perception by sniffing; that which is taken by sniffing; as  a sniff of air."
sniffle: "To snuffle  as one does with a catarrh."
sniggle: "To catch  as an eel by sniggling; hence to hook; to insnare."
snite: "To blow  as the nose; to snuff as a candle."
snithy: "Sharp; piercing; cutting; -- applied to the wind."
snively: "Running at the nose; sniveling pitiful; whining."
snoff: "A short candle end used for igniting a fuse."
snood: "To bind or braid up  as the hair with a snood."
snooze: "To doze; to drowse; to take a short nap; to slumber."
snoring: "The act of respiring through the open mouth so that the currents of inspired and expired air cause a vibration of the uvula and soft palate  thus giving rise to a sound more or less harsh. It is usually unvoluntary but may be produced voluntarily."
snore: "A harsh nasal noise made in sleep."
snort: "To expel throught the nostrils with a snort; to utter with a snort."
snorter: "The wheather; -- so called from its cry."
snotter: "A rope going over a yardarm  used to bend a tripping line to in sending down topgallant and royal yards in vessels of war; also the short line supporting the heel of the sprit in a small boat."
snout: "To furnish with a nozzle or point."
snowcap: "A very small humming bird (Microchaera albocoronata) native of New Grenada."
snuff: "Resentment  displeasure or contempt expressed by a snuffing of the nose."
snuffle: "Obstruction of the nose by mucus; nasal catarrh of infants or children."
snuggle: "To move one way and the other so as to get a close place; to lie close for comfort; to cuddle; to nestle."
snying: "A curved plank  placed edgewise to work in the bows of a vessel."
soaking: "Wetting thoroughly; drenching; as  a soaking rain."
soakage: "The act of soaking  or the state of being soaked; also the quantity that enters or issues by soaking."
sobbing: "A series of short  convulsive inspirations the glottis being suddenly closed so that little or no air enters into the lungs."
soboles: "A sucker  as of tree or shrub."
socage: "A tenure of lands and tenements by a certain or determinate service; a tenure distinct from chivalry or knight's service  in which the obligations were uncertain. The service must be certain in order to be denominated socage as to hold by fealty and twenty shillings rent."
social: "Forming compound groups or colonies by budding from basal processes or stolons; as  the social ascidians."
society: "Specifically  the more cultivated portion of any community in its social relations and influences; those who mutually give receive formal entertainments."
socket: "Especially  the hollow tube or place in which a candle is fixed in the candlestick."
socle: "A plain face or plinth at the lower part of a wall."
socman: "One who holds lands or tenements by socage; a socager."
socome: "A custom of tenants to grind corn at the lord's mill."
soddy: "Consisting of sod; covered with sod; turfy."
sodic: "Of or pertaining to sodium; containing sodium."
sodio-: "A combining form (also used adjectively) denoting the presence of sodium or one of its compounds."
sodium: "A common metallic element of the alkali group  in nature always occuring combined as in common salt in albite etc. It is isolated as a soft waxy white unstable metal so readily oxidized that it combines violently with water and to be preserved must be kept under petroleum or some similar liquid. Sodium is used combined in many salts in the free state as a reducer and as a means of obtaining other metals (as magnesium and aluminium) is an important commercial product. Symbol Na (Natrium). Atomic weight 23. Specific gravity 0.97."
sodomy: "Carnal copulation in a manner against nature; buggery."
soever: "A word compounded of so and ever  used in composition with who what where when how etc. and indicating any out of all possible or supposable persons things places times ways
soffit: "The under side of the subordinate parts and members of buildings  such as staircases entablatures archways cornices or the like. See Illust. of Lintel."
softa: "Any one attached to a Mohammedan mosque  esp. a student of the higher branches of theology in a mosque school."
soften: "To become soft or softened  or less rude harsh severe or obdurate."
soggy: "Filled with water; soft with moisture; sodden; soaked; wet; as  soggy land or timber."
soiree: "An evening party; -- distinguished from levee  and matinee."
sojourn: "A temporary residence  as that of a traveler in a foreign land."
solano: "A hot  oppressive wind which sometimes blows in the Mediterranean particularly on the eastern coast of Spain."
solanum: "A genus of plants comprehending the potato (S. tuberosum)  the eggplant (S. melongena and several hundred other species; nightshade."
solar: "Produced by the action of the sun  or peculiarly affected by its influence."
soldier: "To make a pretense of doing something  or of performing any task."
soldo: "A small Italian coin worth a sou or a cent; the twentieth part of a lira."
solely: "Singly; alone; only; without another; as  to rest a cause solely one argument; to rely solelyn one's own strength."
solemn: "Made in form; ceremonious; as  solemn war; conforming with all legal requirements; as probate in solemn form."
solen: "Any marine bivalve mollusk belonging to Solen or allied genera of the family Solenidae; a razor shell."
solere: "A loft or garret. See Solar  n."
sol-fa: "The gamut  or musical scale. See Tonic sol-fa under Tonic n."
solicit: "To disturb; to disquiet; -- a Latinism rarely used."
solid: "A magnitude which has length  breadth and thickness; a part of space bounded on all sides."
solidly: "In a solid manner; densely; compactly; firmly; truly."
soliped: "A mammal having a single hoof on each foot  as the horses and asses; a solidungulate."
sollar: "To cover  or provide with a sollar."
soloist: "One who sings or plays a solo."
solomon: "One of the kings of Israel  noted for his superior wisdom and magnificent reign; hence a very wise man."
solon: "A celebrated Athenian lawmaker  born about 638 b. c.; hence a legislator; a publicist; -- often used ironically."
solvent: "That which resolves; as  a solvent of mystery."
samaj: "A society; a congregation; a worshiping assembly  or church esp. of the Brahmo-somaj."
somal: "A Hamitic people of East Central Africa."
somatic: "Of or pertaining to the wall of the body; somatopleuric; parietal; as  the somatic stalk of the yolk sac of an embryo."
somehow: "In one way or another; in some way not yet known or designated; by some means; as  the thing must be done somehow; he lives somehow."
somite: "One of the actual or ideal serial segments of which an animal  esp. an articulate or vertebrate is is composed; somatome; metamere."
somner: "A summoner; esp.  one who summons to an ecclesiastical court."
somnial: "Of or pertaining to sleep or dreams."
sonance: "The quality or state of being sonant."
sonata: "An extended composition for one or two instruments  consisting usually of three or four movements; as Beethoven's sonatas for the piano for the violin and piano etc."
sonde: "That which is sent; a message or messenger; hence  also a visitation of providence; an affliction or trial."
sonifer: "A kind of ear trumpet for the deaf  or the partially deaf."
sonship: "The state of being a son  or of bearing the relation of a son; filiation."
sontag: "A knitted worsted jacket  worn over the waist of a woman's dress."
sonties: "Probably from """"saintes"""" saints  or from sanctities; -- used as an oath."
soorma: "A preparation of antimony with which Mohammedan men anoint their eyelids."
soosoo: "A kind of dolphin (Platanista Gangeticus) native of the river Ganges; the Gangetic dolphin. It has a long  slender somewhat spatulate beak."
soothe: "To assuage; to mollify; to calm; to comfort; as  to soothe a crying child; to soothe one's sorrows."
sophism: "The doctrine or mode of reasoning practiced by a sophist; hence  any fallacy designed to deceive."
sophist: "Hence  an impostor in argument; a captious or fallacious reasoner."
sophora: "A tree (Sophora Japonica) of Eastern Asia  resembling the common locust; occasionally planted in the United States."
sopite: "To lay asleep; to put to sleep; to quiet."
sopor: "Profound sleep from which a person can be roused only with difficulty."
soppy: "Soaked or saturated with liquid or moisture; very wet or sloppy."
soprano: "A singer  commonly a woman with a treble voice."
sorbic: "Pertaining to  or obtained from the rowan tree or sorb; specifically designating an acid C/H/CO/H of the acetylene series found in the unripe berries of this tree and extracted as a white crystalline substance."
sorbin: "An unfermentable sugar  isomeric with glucose found in the ripe berries of the rowan tree or sorb and extracted as a sweet white crystalline substance; -- called also mountain-ash sugar."
sorbite: "A sugarlike substance  isomeric with mannite and dulcite found with sorbin in the ripe berries of the sorb and extracted as a sirup or a white crystalline substance."
sorcery: "Divination by the assistance  or supposed assistance of evil spirits or the power of commanding evil spirits; magic; necromancy; witchcraft; enchantment."
sordes: "Foul matter; excretion; dregs; filthy  useless or rejected matter of any kind; specifically (Med.) the foul matter that collects on the teeth and tongue in low fevers and other conditions attended with great vital depression."
sorehon: "Formerly  in Ireland a kind of servile tenure which subjected the tenant to maintain his chieftain gratuitously whenever he wished to indulge in a revel."
sorel: "A yellowish or reddish brown color; sorrel."
sorely: "In a sore manner; grievously; painfully; as  to be sorely afflicted."
sorema: "A heap of carpels belonging to one flower."
sorex: "A genus of small Insectivora  including the common shrews."
sorghum: "A variety of Sorghum vulgare  grown for its saccharine juice; the Chinese sugar cane."
sorgo: "Indian millet and its varieties. See Sorghum."
sorites: "An abridged form of stating of syllogisms in a series of propositions so arranged that the predicate of each one that precedes forms the subject of each one that follows  and the conclusion unites the subject of the first proposition with the predicate of the last proposition"
sorner: "One who obtrudes himself on another for bed and board."
sorosis: "A fleshy fruit formed by the consolidation of many flowers with their receptacles  ovaries etc. as the breadfruit mulberry and pineapple."
sorrel: "One of various plants having a sour juice; especially  a plant of the genus Rumex as Rumex Acetosa Rumex Acetosella etc."
sorrow: "To feel pain of mind in consequence of evil experienced  feared or done; to grieve; to be sad; to be sorry."
sorry: "Poor; mean; worthless; as  a sorry excuse."
sortie: "The sudden issuing of a body of troops  usually small from a besieged place to attack or harass the besiegers; a sally."
sorus: "One of the fruit dots  or small clusters of sporangia on the back of the fronds of ferns."
sothic: "Of or pertaining to Sothis  the Egyptian name for the Dog Star; taking its name from the Dog Star; canicular."
sotted: "a. & p. p. of Sot. Befooled; deluded; besotted."
sottish: "Like a sot; doltish; very foolish; drunken."
souffle: "A side dish served hot from the oven at dinner  made of eggs milk and flour or other farinaceous substance beaten till very light and flavored with fruits liquors or essence."
sough: "To whistle or sigh  as the wind."
souled: "Furnished with a soul; possessing soul and feeling; -- used chiefly in composition; as  great-souled Hector."
soulili: "A long-tailed  crested Javan monkey (Semnopithecus mitratus). The head the crest and the upper surface of the tail are black."
souple: "That part of a flail which strikes the grain."
source: "That from which anything comes forth  regarded as its cause or origin; the person from whom anything originates; first cause."
sourde: "To have origin or source; to rise; to spring."
sourish: "Somewhat sour; moderately acid; as  sourish fruit; a sourish taste."
soursop: "The large succulent and slightly acid fruit of a small tree (Anona muricata) of the West Indies; also  the tree itself. It is closely allied to the custard apple."
soutage: "That in which anything is packed; bagging  as for hops."
soutane: "A close garnment with straight sleeves  and skirts reaching to the ankles and buttoned in front from top to bottom; especially the black garment of this shape worn by the clergy in France and Italy as their daily dress; a cassock."
south: "To come to the meridian; to cross the north and south line; -- said chiefly of the moon; as  the moon souths at nine."
souther: "A strong wind  gale or storm from the south."
sowbane: "The red goosefoot (Chenopodium rubrum)  -- said to be fatal to swine."
sowens: "A nutritious article of food  much used in Scotland made from the husk of the oat by a process not unlike that by which common starch is made; -- called flummery in England."
sowle: "To pull by the ears; to drag about."
spaad: "A kind of spar; earth flax  or amianthus."
space: "To arrange or adjust the spaces in or between; as  to space words lines or letters."
spade: "To dig with a spade; to pare off the sward of  as land with a spade."
spader: "One who  or that which spades; specifically a digging machine."
spadix: "A special organ of the nautilus  due to a modification of the posterior tentacles."
spahee: "An Algerian cavalryman in the French army."
spall: "To give off spalls  or wedge-shaped chips; -- said of stone as when badly set with the weight thrown too much on the outer surface."
spalt: "To split off; to cleave off  as chips from a piece of timber with an ax."
spancel: "To tie or hobble with a spancel."
spangle: "To show brilliant spots or points; to glisten; to glitter."
spangly: "Resembling  or consisting of spangles; glittering; as spangly light."
spank: "To move with a quick  lively step between a trot and gallop; to move quickly."
spanner: "A contrivance in some of the ealier steam engines for moving the valves for the alternate admission and shutting off of the steam."
sparada: "A small California surf fish (Micrometrus aggregatus); -- called also shiner."
spare: "The right of bowling again at a full set of pins  after having knocked all the pins down in less than three bowls. If all the pins are knocked down in one bowl it is a double spare; in two bowls a single spare."
sparge: "To sprinkle; to moisten by sprinkling; as  to sparge paper."
sparger: "A vessel with a perforated cover  for sprinkling with a liquid; a sprinkler."
spark: "To play the spark  beau or lover."
sparrow: "Any one of several small singing birds somewhat resembling the true sparrows in form or habits  as the European hedge sparrow. See under Hedge."
sparry: "Resembling spar  or consisting of spar; abounding with spar; having a confused crystalline structure; spathose."
spartan: "A native or inhabitant of Sparta; figuratively  a person of great courage and fortitude."
spasm: "A sudden  violent and temporary effort or emotion; as a spasm of repentance."
spastic: "Of or pertaining to spasm; spasmodic; especially  pertaining to tonic spasm; tetanic."
spate: "A river flood; an overflow or inundation."
spathal: "Furnished with a spathe; as  spathal flowers."
spathe: "A special involucre formed of one leaf and inclosing a spadix  as in aroid plants and palms. See the Note under Bract and Illust. of Spadix."
spathed: "Having a spathe or calyx like a sheath."
spatter: "To throw something out of the mouth in a scattering manner; to sputter."
spattle: "A tool or implement for mottling a molded article with coloring matter"
spatula: "An implement shaped like a knife  flat thin and somewhat flexible used for spreading paints fine plasters drugs in compounding prescriptions etc. Cf. Palette knife under Palette."
spavin: "A disease of horses characterized by a bony swelling developed on the hock as the result of inflammation of the bones; also  the swelling itself. The resulting lameness is due to the inflammation and not the bony tumor as popularly supposed."
spawl: "To scatter spittle from the mouth; to spit  as saliva."
spawn: "The white fibrous matter forming the matrix from which fungi."
spoke: "To furnish with spokes  as a wheel."
spoken: "Characterized by a certain manner or style in speaking; -- often in composition; as  a pleasant-spoken man."
speak: "To address; to accost; to speak to."
speaker: "A book of selections for declamation."
spear: "To shoot into a long stem  as some plants. See Spire."
spearer: "One who uses a spear; as  a spearer of fish."
special: "One appointed for a special service or occasion."
species: "The form or shape given to materials; fashion or shape; form; figure."
specify: "To mention or name  as a particular thing; to designate in words so as to distinguish from other things; as to specify the uses of a plant; to specify articles purchased."
speck: "To cause the presence of specks upon or in  especially specks regarded as defects or blemishes; to spot; to speckle; as paper specked by impurities in the water used in its manufacture."
speckle: "To mark with small spots of a different color from that of the rest of the surface; to variegate with spots of a different color from the ground or surface."
speed: "To wish success or god fortune to  in any undertaking especially in setting out upon a journey."
speeder: "A machine for drawing and twisting slivers to form rovings."
speedy: "Not dilatory or slow; quick; swift; nimble; hasty; rapid in motion or performance; as  a speedy flight; on speedy foot."
speight: "A woodpecker; -- called also specht  spekt spight."
speiss: "A regulus consisting essentially of nickel  obtained as a residue in fusing cobalt and nickel ores with silica and sodium carbonate to make smalt."
spelk: "A small stick or rod used as a spike in thatching; a splinter."
spell: "To study by noting characters; to gain knowledge or learn the meaning of anything  by study."
spelter: "Zinc; -- especially so called in commerce and arts."
spence: "The inner apartment of a country house; also  the place where the family sit and eat."
spencer: "A fore-and-aft sail  abaft the foremast or the mainmast hoisted upon a small supplementary mast and set with a gaff and no boom; a trysail carried at the foremast or mainmast; -- named after its inventor Knight Spencer of England [1802]."
spent: "Exhausted of spawn or sperm; -- said especially of fishes."
spender: "One who spends; esp.  one who spends lavishly; a prodigal; a spendthrift."
sperre: "To shut in; to support; to inclose; to fasten."
sperate: "Hoped for  or to be hoped for."
sperge: "A charge of wash for the still."
spermo-: "Combining forms from Gr. spe`rma  -atos seed sperm semen (of plants or animals); as spermatoblast spermoblast."
spermic: "Of or pertaining to sperm  or semen."
sphene: "A mineral found usually in thin  wedge-shaped crystals of a yellow or green to black color. It is a silicate of titanium and calcium; titanite."
spheno-: "A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with  or relation to the sphenoid bone; as in sphenomaxillary sphenopalatine."
spheral: "Rounded like a sphere; sphere-shaped; hence  symmetrical; complete; perfect."
sphere: "To form into roundness; to make spherical  or spheral; to perfect."
spheric: "Of or pertaining to the heavenly orbs  or to the sphere or spheres in which according to ancient astronomy and astrology they were set."
sphex: "Any one of numerous species of sand wasps of the genus Sphex and allied genera. These wasps have the abdomen attached to the thorax by a slender pedicel. See Illust. of Sand wasp  under Sand."
spica: "A star of the first magnitude situated in the constellation Virgo."
spice: "To render nice or dainty; hence  to render scrupulous."
spicose: "Having spikes  or ears like corn spikes."
spicule: "Any small calcareous or siliceous body found in the tissues of various invertebrate animals  especially in sponges and in most Alcyonaria."
spicy: "Fig.: Piquant; racy; as  a spicy debate."
spider: "A skeleton  or frame having radiating arms or members often connected by crosspieces; as a casting forming the hub and spokes to which the rim of a fly wheel or large gear is bolted; the body of a piston head; a frame for strengthening a core or mold for a casting etc."
spignet: "An aromatic plant of America. See Spikenard."
spigot: "A pin or peg used to stop the vent in a cask; also  the plug of a faucet or cock."
spiked: "Furnished or set with spikes  as corn; fastened with spikes; stopped with spikes."
spiky: "Having a sharp point  or sharp points; furnished or armed with spikes."
spile: "To supply with a spile or a spigot; to make a small vent in  as a cask."
spill: "To be shed; to run over; to fall out  and be lost or wasted."
spiller: "A kind of fishing line with many hooks; a boulter."
spilter: "Any one of the small branches on a stag's head."
spilth: "Anything spilt  or freely poured out; slop; effusion."
spinage: "A common pot herb (Spinacia oleracea) belonging to the Goosefoot family."
spinal: "Of or pertaining to a spine or spines."
spindle: "To shoot or grow into a long  slender stalk or body; to become disproportionately tall and slender."
spine: "Anything resembling the spine or backbone; a ridge."
spinel: "Bleached yarn in making the linen tape called inkle; unwrought inkle."
spinose: "Full of spines; armed with thorns; thorny."
spinous: "Having the form of a spine or thorn; spinelike."
spiodea: "An extensive division of marine Annelida  including those that are without oral tentacles or cirri and have the gills when present mostly arranged along the sides of the body. They generally live in burrows or tubes."
spiraea: "A genus of shrubs or perennial herbs including the meadowsweet and the hardhack."
spiral: "Anything which has a spiral form  as a spiral shell."
spirant: "A term used differently by different authorities; -- by some as equivalent to fricative  -- that is as including all the continuous consonants except the nasals m n ng; with the further exception by others of the liquids r l and the semivowels w y; by others limited to f v
spire: "The part of a spiral generated in one revolution of the straight line about the pole. See Spiral  n."
spired: "Having a spire; being in the form of a spire; as  a spired steeple."
spiring: "Shooting up in a spire or spires."
spirit: "To convey rapidly and secretly  or mysteriously as if by the agency of a spirit; to kidnap; -- often with away or off."
spirula: "A genus of cephalopods having a multilocular  internal siphunculated shell in the form of a flat spiral the coils of which are not in contact."
spiry: "Of or pertaining to a spire; like a spire  tall slender and tapering; abounding in spires; as spiry turrets."
spitted: "p. p. of Spit  v. i. to eject to spit."
spite: "To fill with spite; to offend; to vex."
spitter: "A young deer whose antlers begin to shoot or become sharp; a brocket  or pricket."
spittle: "The thick  moist matter which is secreted by the salivary glands; saliva; spit."
splash: "A noise made by striking upon or in a liquid."
splashy: "Full of dirty water; wet and muddy  so as be easily splashed about; slushy."
splay: "A slope or bevel  especially of the sides of a door or window by which the opening is made larged at one face of the wall than at the other or larger at each of the faces than it is between them."
spleget: "A cloth dipped in a liquid for washing a sore."
splenic: "Of or pertaining to the spleen; lienal; as  the splenic vein."
splice: "A junction or joining made by splicing."
spline: "A long  flexble piece of wood sometimes used as a ruler."
splint: "To fasten or confine with splints  as a broken limb. See Splint n. 2."
splurge: "To make a great display in any way  especially in oratory."
spoil: "The slough  or cast skin of a serpent or other animal."
spoiler: "One who corrupts  mars or renders useless."
spondee: "A poetic foot of two long syllables  as in the Latin word leges."
spong: "An irregular  narrow projecting part of a field."
sponge: "To be converted  as dough into a light spongy mass by the agency of yeast or leaven."
spongin: "The chemical basis of sponge tissue  a nitrogenous hornlike substance which on decomposition with sulphuric acid yields leucin and glycocoll."
spongy: "Having the quality of imbibing fluids  like a sponge."
sponsal: "Relating to marriage  or to a spouse; spousal."
sponson: "One of the armored projections fitted with gun ports  used on modern war vessels."
sponsor: "One who at the baptism of an infant professore the christian faith in its name  and guarantees its religious education; a godfather or godmother."
spool: "To wind on a spool or spools."
spoom: "To be driven steadily and swiftly  as before a strong wind; to be driven before the wind without any sail or with only a part of the sails spread; to scud under bare poles."
spoon: "To act with demonstrative or foolish fondness  as one in love."
spooney: "A weak-minded or silly person; one who is foolishly fond."
spore: "One of the parts formed by fission in certain Protozoa. See Spore formation  belw."
sporran: "A large purse or pouch made of skin with the hair or fur on  worn in front of the kilt by Highlanders when in full dress."
sport: "To give utterance to in a sportive manner; to throw out in an easy and copious manner; -- with off; as  to sport off epigrams."
sportal: "Of or pertaining to sports; used in sports."
spotted: "Marked with spots; as  a spotted garment or character."
spousal: "Marriage; nuptials; espousal; -- generally used in the plural; as  the spousals of Hippolita."
spout: "A discharge or jet of water or other liquid  esp. when rising in a column; also a waterspout."
sprain: "The act or result of spraining; lameness caused by spraining; as  a bad sprain of the wrist."
sprat: "A California surf-fish (Rhacochilus toxotes); -- called also alfione  and perch."
sprawl: "To move  when lying down with awkward extension and motions of the limbs; to scramble in creeping."
srawls: "Small branches of a tree; twigs; sprays."
spray: "To throw spray upon; to treat with a liquid in the form of spray; as  to spray a wound or a surgical instrument with carbolic acid."
spree: "A merry frolic; especially  a drinking frolic; a carousal."
sprig: "To mark or adorn with the representation of small branches; to work with sprigs; as  to sprig muslin."
sprung: "Said of a spar that has been cracked or strained."
spring: "A line led from a vessel's quarter to her cable so that by tightening or slacking it she can be made to lie in any desired position; a line led diagonally from the bow or stern of a vessel to some point upon the wharf to which she is moored."
springy: "Abounding with springs or fountains; wet; spongy; as  springy land."
sprint: "The act of sprinting; a run of a short distance at full speed."
sprit: "A small boom  pole or spar which crosses the sail of a boat diagonally from the mast to the upper aftmost corner which it is used to extend and elevate."
spruce: "To dress one's self with affected neatness; as  to spruce up."
spuller: "One employed to inspect yarn  to see that it is well spun and fit for the loom."
spumy: "Consisting of  containing or covered with froth scum or foam; frothy; foamy."
spunk: "An inflammable temper; spirit; mettle; pluck; as  a man of spunk."
spurred: "Affected with spur  or ergot; as spurred rye."
spurge: "Any plant of the genus Euphorbia. See Euphorbia."
spurn: "A body of coal left to sustain an overhanding mass."
spurry: "An annual herb (Spergula arvensis) with whorled filiform leaves  sometimes grown in Europe for fodder."
spurt: "To make a sudden and violent exertion  as in an emergency."
sourt: "Fig.: A sudden outbreak; as  a spurt of jealousy."
spurtle: "To spurt or shoot in a scattering manner."
sputter: "Moist matter thrown out in small detached particles; also  confused and hasty speech."
sputum: "That which is expectorated; a salival discharge; spittle; saliva."
spyboat: "A boat sent to make discoveries and bring intelligence."
squab: "To fall plump; to strike at one dash  or with a heavy stroke."
squacco: "A heron (Ardea comata) found in Asia  Northern Africa and Southern Europe."
squail: "To throw sticls at cocks; to throw anything about awkwardly or irregularly."
squali: "The suborder of elasmobranch fishes which comprises the sharks."
