squalid: "Dirty through neglect; foul; filthy; extremely dirty."
squally: "Not equally good throughout; not uniform; uneven; faulty; -- said of cloth."
squama: "A scale cast off from the skin; a thin dry shred consisting of epithelium."
squame: "The scale  or exopodite of an antenna of a crustacean."
square: "To take a boxing attitude; -- often with up  sometimes with off."
squarer: "One who squares  or quarrels; a hot-headed contentious fellow."
squash: "A sudden fall of a heavy  soft body; also a shock of soft bodies."
squat: "A mineral consisting of tin ore and spar."
squaw: "A female; a woman; -- in the language of Indian tribes of the Algonquin family  correlative of sannup."
squawk: "The American night heron. See under Night."
squeak: "A sharp  shrill disagreeable sound suddenly utered either of the human voice or of any animal or instrument such as is made by carriage wheels when dry by the soles of leather shoes or by a pipe or reed."
squeeze: "A facsimile impression taken in some soft substance  as pulp from an inscription on stone."
squelch: "A heavy fall  as of something flat; hence also a crushing reply."
squib: "To throw squibs; to utter sarcatic or severe reflections; to contend in petty dispute; as  to squib a little debate."
squid: "A fishhook with a piece of bright lead  bone or other substance fastened on its shank to imitate a squid."
squiery: "A company of squires; the whole body of squires."
squilla: "Any one of numerous stomapod crustaceans of the genus Squilla and allied genera. They make burrows in mud or beneath stones on the seashore. Called also mantis shrimp. See Illust. under Stomapoda."
squinch: "A small arch thrown across the corner of a square room to support a superimposed mass  as where an octagonal spire or drum rests upon a square tower; -- called also sconce and sconcheon."
souir: "To throw with a jerk; to throw edge foremost."
squire: "To attend as a beau  or gallant for aid and protection; as to squire a lady."
squirm: "To twist about briskly with contor/ions like an eel or a worm; to wriggle; to writhe."
squiry: "The body of squires  collectively considered; squirarchy."
stable: "To dwell or lodge in a stable; to dwell in an inclosed place; to kennel."
stably: "In a stable manner; firmly; fixedly; steadily; as  a government stably settled."
stack: "To lay in a conical or other pile; to make into a large pile; as  to stack hay cornstalks or grain; to stack or place wood."
stacte: "One of the sweet spices used by the ancient Jews in the preparation of incense. It was perhaps an oil or other form of myrrh or cinnamon  or a kind of storax."
stadium: "A kind of telemeter for measuring the distance of an object of known dimensions  by observing the angle it subtends; especially (Surveying) a graduated rod used to measure the distance of the place where it stands from an instrument having a telescope by observing the number of the graduations of the rod that are seen between certain parallel wires (stadia wires) in the field of view of the telescope; -- also called stadia and stadia rod."
staff: "Hence: A body of assistants serving to carry into effect the plans of a superintendant or manager; as  the staff of a newspaper."
stage: "To exhibit upon a stage  or as upon a stage; to display publicly."
stagely: "Pertaining to a stage; becoming the theater; theatrical."
stager: "A horse used in drawing a stage."
staging: "The business of running stagecoaches; also  the act of journeying in stagecoaches."
stail: "A handle  as of a mop; a stale."
stainer: "A workman who stains; as  a stainer of wood."
stair: "A series of steps  as for passing from one story of a house to another; -- commonly used in the plural; but originally used in the singular only."
staith: "A landing place; an elevated staging upon a wharf for discharging coal  etc. as from railway cars into vessels."
stake: "To pierce or wound with a stake."
stalder: "A wooden frame to set casks on."
stalk: "A high  proud stately step or walk."
stalked: "Having a stalk or stem; borne upon a stem."
stalky: "Hard as a stalk; resembling a stalk."
stall: "To be tired of eating  as cattle."
stalled: "Put or kept in a stall; hence  fatted."
stallon: "A slip from a plant; a scion; a cutting."
stamina: "Whatever constitutes the principal strength or support of anything; power of endurance; backbone; vigor; as  the stamina of a constitution or of life; the stamina of a State."
stamen: "The male organ of flowers for secreting and furnishing the pollen or fecundating dust. It consists of the anther and filament."
stammel: "Of the color of stammel; having a red color  thought inferior to scarlet."
stammer: "Defective utterance  or involuntary interruption of utterance; a stutter."
stanch: "To prop; to make stanch  or strong."
stand: "A weight of from two hundred and fifty to three hundred pounds  -- used in weighing pitch."
standel: "A young tree  especially one reserved when others are cut."
stannel: "The kestrel; -- called also standgale  standgall stanchel stand hawk stannel hawk steingale stonegall."
stannic: "Of or pertaining to tin; derived from or containing tin; specifically  designating those compounds in which the element has a higher valence as contrasted with stannous compounds."
stanno-: "A combining form (also used adjectively) denoting relation to  or connection with tin or including tin as an ingredient."
stannum: "The technical name of tin. See Tin."
stanza: "An apartment or division in a building; a room or chamber."
stapes: "The innermost of the ossicles of the ear; the stirrup  or stirrup bone; -- so called from its form. See Illust. of Ear."
staple: "To sort according to its staple; as  to staple cotton."
stapler: "One employed to assort wool according to its staple."
starchy: "Consisting of starch; resembling starch; stiff; precise."
stare: "The act of staring; a fixed look with eyes wide open."
starry: "Arranged in rays like those of a star; stellate."
start: "The arm  or level of a gin drawn around by a horse."
startle: "A sudden motion or shock caused by an unexpected alarm  surprise or apprehension of danger."
starve: "To deprive of force or vigor; to disable."
stasis: "A slackening or arrest of the blood current in the vessels  due not to a lessening of the heart's beat but presumably to some abnormal resistance of the capillary walls. It is one of the phenomena observed in the capillaries in inflammation."
statal: "Of  pertaining to or existing with reference to a State of the American Union as distinguished from the general government."
statant: "In a standing position; as  a lion statant."
state: "A statement; also  a document containing a statement."
stated: "Recurring at regular time; not occasional; as  stated preaching; stated business hours."
stating: "The act of one who states anything; statement; as  the statingof one's opinions."
stater: "The principal gold coin of ancient Grece. It varied much in value  the stater best known at Athens being worth about ï¿½1 2s. or about $5.35. The Attic silver tetradrachm was in later times called stater."
statics: "That branch of mechanics which treats of the equilibrium of forces  or relates to bodies as held at rest by the forces acting on them; -- distinguished from dynamics."
station: "To place; to set; to appoint or assign to the occupation of a post  place or office; as to station troops on the right of an army; to station a sentinel on a rampart; to station ships on the coasts of Africa."
statism: "The art of governing a state; statecraft; policy."
stative: "Of or pertaining to a fixed camp  or military posts or quarters."
statue: "To place  as a statue; to form a statue of; to make into a statue."
stature: "The natural height of an animal body; -- generally used of the human body."
statute: "An assemblage of farming servants (held possibly by statute) for the purpose of being hired; -- called also statute fair."
stave: "To burst in pieces by striking against something; to dash into fragments."
stove: "To heat or dry  as in a stove; as to stove feathers."
staving: "A cassing or lining of staves; especially  one encircling a water wheel."
stayed: "Staid; fixed; settled; sober; -- now written staid. See Staid."
stayer: "One who upholds or supports that which props; one who  or that which stays stops or restrains; also colloquially a horse man etc. that has endurance an a race."
steady: "To become steady; to regain a steady position or state; to move steadily."
steak: "A slice of beef  broiled or cut for broiling; -- also extended to the meat of other large animals; as venison steak; bear steak; pork steak; turtle steak."
steal: "To withdraw  or pass privily; to slip in along or away unperceived; to go or come furtively."
stole: "A narrow band of silk or stuff  sometimes enriched with embroidery and jewels worn on the left shoulder of deacons and across both shoulders of bishops and priests pendent on each side nearly to the ground. At Mass it is worn crossed on the breast by priests. It is used in various sacred functions."
stealer: "The endmost plank of a strake which stops short of the stem or stern."
stealth: "The bringing to pass anything in a secret or concealed manner; a secret procedure; a clandestine practice or action; -- in either a good or a bad sense."
steam: "To expose to the action of steam; to apply steam to for softening  dressing or preparing; as to steam wood; to steamcloth; to steam food etc."
steamy: "Consisting of  or resembling steam; full of steam; vaporous; misty."
stearic: "Pertaining to  or obtained from stearin or tallow; resembling tallow."
stearin: "One of the constituents of animal fats and also of some vegetable fats  as the butter of cacao. It is especially characterized by its solidity so that when present in considerable quantity it materially increases the hardness or raises the melting point of the fat as in mutton tallow. Chemically it is a compound of glyceryl with three molecules of stearic acid and hence is technically called tristearin or glyceryl tristearate."
stearyl: "The hypothetical radical characteristic of stearic acid."
steed: "A horse  especially a spirited horse for state of war; -- used chiefly in poetry or stately prose."
steel: "To cover  as an electrotype plate with a thin layer of iron by electrolysis. The iron thus deposited is very hard like steel."
steely: "Resembling steel; hard; firm; having the color of steel."
steen: "To line  as a well with brick stone or other hard material."
steep: "A precipitous place  hill mountain rock or ascent; any elevated object sloping with a large angle to the plane of the horizon; a precipice."
steeper: "A vessel  vat or cistern in which things are steeped."
steeple: "A spire; also  the tower and spire taken together; the whole of a structure if the roof is of spire form. See Spire."
steeply: "In a steep manner; with steepness; with precipitous declivity."
steerer: "One who steers; as  a boat steerer."
steeve: "A spar  with a block at one end used in stowing cotton bales and similar kinds of cargo which need to be packed tightly."
stela: "A small column or pillar  used as a monument milestone etc."
stelene: "Resembling  or used as a stela; columnar."
stell: "A partial inclosure made by a wall or trees  to serve as a shelter for sheep or cattle."
stemma: "One of the facets of a compound eye of any arthropod."
stemmer: "One who  or that which stems (in any of the senses of the verbs)."
stemmy: "Abounding in stems  or mixed with stems; -- said of tea dried currants etc."
stemple: "A crossbar of wood in a shaft  serving as a step."
stemson: "A piece of curved timber bolted to the stem  keelson and apron in a ship's frame near the bow."
stench: "To cause to emit a disagreeable odor; to cause to stink."
stencil: "To mark  paint or color in figures with stencils; to form or print by means of a stencil."
stepped: "Provided with a step or steps; having a series of offsets or parts resembling the steps of stairs; as  a stepped key."
step-: "A prefix used before father  mother brother sister son daughter child etc. to indicate that the person thus spoken of is not a blood relative but is a relative by the marriage of a parent; as a stepmother to X is the wife of the father of X married by him after the death of the mother of X. See Stepchild
steppe: "One of the vast plains in Southeastern Europe and in Asia  generally elevated and free from wood analogous to many of the prairies in Western North America. See Savanna."
stepper: "One who  or that which steps; as a quick stepper."
stepson: "A son of one's husband or wife by a former marriage."
stereo-: "A combining form meaning solid  hard firm as in stereo-chemistry stereography."
sterile: "Fig.: Barren of ideas; destitute of sentiment; as  a sterile production or author."
sterlet: "A small sturgeon (Acipenser ruthenus) found in the Caspian Sea and its rivers  and highly esteemed for its flavor. The finest caviare is made from its roe."
stern: "Being in the stern  or being astern; as the stern davits."
sternal: "Of or pertaining to the sternum; in the region of the sternum."
sterned: "Having a stern of a particular shape; -- used in composition; as  square-sterned."
sterno-: "A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with  or relation to the sternum; as sternocostal sternoscapular."
sternum: "The ventral part of any one of the somites of an arthropod."
sterve: "To die  or cause to die; to perish. See Starve."
stethal: "One of the higher alcohols of the methane series  homologous with ethal and found in small quantities as an ethereal salt of stearic acid in spermaceti."
steve: "To pack or stow  as cargo in a ship's hold. See Steeve."
steven: "An outcry; a loud call; a clamor."
sthenic: "Strong; active; -- said especially of morbid states attended with excessive action of the heart and blood vessels  and characterized by strength and activity of the muscular and nervous system; as a sthenic fever."
stian: "A sty on the eye. See Styan."
stibial: "Like  or having the qualities of antimony; antimonial."
stibic: "Antimonic; -- used with reference to certain compounds of antimony."
stibine: "Antimony hydride  or hydrogen antimonide a colorless gas produced by the action of nascent hydrogen on antimony. It has a characteristic odor and burns with a characteristic greenish flame. Formerly called also antimoniureted hydrogen."
stich: "A row  line or rank of trees."
stichic: "Of or pertaining to stichs  or lines; consisting of stichs or lines."
stickle: "A shallow rapid in a river; also  the current below a waterfall."
sticky: "Having the quality of sticking to a surface; adhesive; gluey; viscous; viscid; glutinous; tenacious."
stiddy: "An anvil; also  a smith shop. See Stithy."
stiff: "Very large  strong or costly; powerful; as a stiff charge; a stiff price."
stiffen: "To become stiff or stiffer  in any sense of the adjective."
stifle: "To die by reason of obstruction of the breath  or because some noxious substance prevents respiration."
stigma: "Marks believed to have been supernaturally impressed upon the bodies of certain persons in imitation of the wounds on the crucified body of Christ. See def. 5  above."
stilar: "Of or pertaining to the style of a dial."
stile: "One of the upright pieces in a frame; one of the primary members of a frame  into which the secondary members are mortised."
still: "To drop  or flow in drops; to distill."
stilly: "In a still manner; quietly; silently; softly."
stilt: "To raise on stilts  or as if on stilts."
stilted: "Elevated as if on stilts; hence  pompous; bombastic; as a stilted style; stilted declamation."
stilty: "Unreasonably elevated; pompous; stilted; as  a stilty style."
stime: "A slight gleam or glimmer; a glimpse."
sting: "To goad; to incite  as by taunts or reproaches."
stingy: "Extremely close and covetous; meanly avaricious; niggardly; miserly; penurious; as  a stingy churl."
stink: "A strong  offensive smell; a disgusting odor; a stench."
stinker: "Any one of the several species of large antarctic petrels which feed on blubber and carrion and have an offensive odor  as the giant fulmar."
stipe: "The stem of a fungus or mushroom."
stipule: "An appendage at the base of petioles or leaves  usually somewhat resembling a small leaf in texture and appearance."
stirps: "A race  or a fixed and permanent variety."
stirrer: "One who  or that which stirs something; also one who moves about especially after sleep; as an early stirrer."
stirrup: "A rope secured to a yard  with a thimble in its lower end for supporting a footrope."
stive: "The floating dust in flour mills caused by the operation or grinding."
stiver: "A Dutch coin  and money of account of the value of two cents or about one penny sterling; hence figuratively anything of little worth."
stoat: "The ermine in its summer pelage  when it is reddish brown but with a black tip to the tail. The name is sometimes applied also to other brown weasels."
stock: "Used or employed for constant service or application  as if constituting a portion of a stock or supply; standard; permanent; standing; as a stock actor; a stock play; a stock sermon."
stocker: "One who makes or fits stocks  as of guns or gun carriages etc."
stoical: "Not affected by passion; manifesting indifference to pleasure or pain."
stoke: "To poke or stir up a fire; hence  to tend the fires of furnaces steamers etc."
stola: "A long garment  descending to the ankles worn by Roman women."
stolid: "Hopelessly insensible or stupid; not easily aroused or excited; dull; impassive; foolish."
stolon: "An extension of the integument of the body  or of the body wall from which buds are developed giving rise to new zooids and thus forming a compound animal in which the zooids usually remain united by the stolons. Such stolons are often present in Anthozoa Hydroidea Bryozoa and social ascidians. See Illust. under Scyphistoma."
stone: "To rub  scour or sharpen with a stone."
stony: "Inflexible; cruel; unrelenting; pitiless; obdurate; perverse; cold; morally hard; appearing as if petrified; as  a stony heart; a stony gaze."
stook: "To set up  as sheaves of grain in stooks."
stool: "Material  such as oyster shells spread on the sea bottom for oyster spat to adhere to."
stoop: "The fall of a bird on its prey; a swoop."
stopped: "Made by complete closure of the mouth organs; shut; -- said of certain consonants (p  b t d etc.)."
stoping: "The act of excavating in the form of stopes."
stopper: "To close or secure with a stopper."
stopple: "To close the mouth of anything with a stopple  or as with a stopple."
storage: "The price changed for keeping goods in a store."
storax: "Any one of a number of similar complex resins obtained from the bark of several trees and shrubs of the Styrax family. The most common of these is liquid storax  a brown or gray semifluid substance of an agreeable aromatic odor and balsamic taste sometimes used in perfumery and in medicine as an expectorant."
store: "To deposit in a store  warehouse or other building for preservation; to warehouse; as to store goods."
stored: "Collected or accumulated as a reserve supply; as  stored electricity."
storer: "One who lays up or forms a store."
storge: "Parental affection; the instinctive affection which animals have for their young."
storify: "To form or tell stories of; to narrate or describe in a story."
stork: "Any one of several species of large wading birds of the family Ciconidae  having long legs and a long pointed bill. They are found both in the Old World and in America and belong to Ciconia and several allied genera. The European white stork (Ciconia alba) is the best known. It commonly makes its nests on the top of a building a chimney a church spire or a pillar. The black stork (C. nigra) is native of Asia Africa and Europe."
storm: "To rage; to be in a violent passion; to fume."
story: "To tell in historical relation; to make the subject of a story; to narrate or describe in story."
stoup: "A basin at the entrance of Roman Catholic churches for containing the holy water with which those who enter  dipping their fingers in it cross themselves; -- called also holy-water stoup."
stoutly: "In a stout manner; lustily; boldly; obstinately; as  he stoutly defended himself."
stover: "Fodder for cattle  especially straw or coarse hay."
stowing: "A method of working in which the waste is packed into the space formed by excavating the vein."
stowce: "A wooden landmark  to indicate possession of mining land."
strake: "A trough for washing broken ore  gravel or sand; a launder."
strand: "To drift  or be driven on shore to run aground; as the ship stranded at high water."
strap: "To sharpen by rubbing on a strap  or strop; as to strap a razor."
strass: "A brilliant glass  used in the manufacture of artificial paste gems which consists essentially of a complex borosilicate of lead and potassium. Cf. Glass."
strath: "A valley of considerable size  through which a river runs; a valley bottom; -- often used in composition with the name of the river; as Strath Spey Strathdon Strathmore."
stratum: "A bed or layer artificially made; a course."
stratus: "A form of clouds in which they are arranged in a horizontal band or layer. See Cloud."
straw: "Anything proverbially worthless; the least possible thing; a mere trifle."
strawy: "Of or pertaining to straw; made of  or resembling straw."
stray: "The act of wandering or going astray."
streak: "With it as an object: To run swiftly."
streamy: "Resembling a stream; issuing in a stream."
streek: "To stretch; also  to lay out as a dead body. See Streak."
streel: "To trail along; to saunter or be drawn along  carelessly swaying in a kind of zigzag motion."
street: "Originally  a paved way or road; a public highway; now commonly a thoroughfare in a city or village bordered by dwellings or business houses."
stress: "To subject to stress  pressure or strain."
stretch: "Course; direction; as  the stretch of seams of coal."
stretto: "In an opera or oratorio  a coda or winding up in an accelerated time."
stria: "A fillet between the flutes of columns  pilasters or the like."
strick: "A bunch of hackled flax prepared for drawing into slivers."
strict: "Upright  or straight and narrow; -- said of the shape of the plants or their flower clusters."
stride: "The act of stridding; a long step; the space measured by a long step; as  a masculine stride."
strife: "That which is contended against; occasion of contest."
striges: "The tribe of birds which comprises the owls."
strigil: "An instrument of metal  ivory etc. used for scraping the skin at the bath."
strike: "The extortion of money  or the attempt to extort money by threat of injury; blackmailing."
striker: "A blackmailer in politics; also  one whose political influence can be bought."
string: "To deprive of strings; to strip the strings from; as  to string beans. See String n. 9."
stringy: "Capable of being drawn into a string  as a glutinous substance; ropy; viscid; gluely."
strip: "The issuing of a projectile from a rifled gun without acquiring the spiral motion."
strix: "One of the flutings of a column."
stroke: "To row the stroke oar of; as  to stroke a boat."
stroker: "One who strokes; also  one who pretends to cure by stroking."
stroll: "A wandering on foot; an idle and leisurely walk; a ramble."
stroma: "A layer or mass of cellular tissue  especially that part of the thallus of certain fungi which incloses the perithecia."
stromb: "Any marine univalve mollusk of the genus Strombus and allied genera. See Conch  and Strombus."
strong: "Applied to forms in Anglo-Saxon  etc. which retain the old declensional endings. In the Teutonic languages the vowel stems have held the original endings most firmly and are called strong; the stems in -n are called weak other constant stems conform or are irregular."
strop: "A piece of rope spliced into a circular wreath  and put round a block for hanging it."
strophe: "In Greek choruses and dances  the movement of the chorus while turning from the right to the left of the orchestra; hence the strain or part of the choral ode sung during this movement. Also sometimes used of a stanza of modern verse. See the Note under Antistrophe."
stroud: "A kind of coarse blanket or garment used by the North American Indians."
strout: "To cause to project or swell out; to enlarge affectedly; to strut."
strull: "A bar so placed as to resist weight."
strum: "To play on an instrument of music  or as on an instrument in an unskillful or noisy way; to thrum; as to strum a piano."
struma: "A cushionlike swelling on any organ; especially  that at the base of the capsule in many mosses."
struse: "A Russian river craft used for transporting freight."
stubble: "The stumps of wheat  rye barley oats or buckwheat left in the ground; the part of the stalk left by the scythe or sickle."
stubby: "Short and thick; short and strong  as bristles."
stucco: "To overlay or decorate with stucco  or fine plaster."
stuckle: "A number of sheaves set together in the field; a stook."
student: "One who studies or examines in any manner; an attentive and systematic observer; as  a student of human nature or of physical nature."
study: "To make an object of study; to aim at sedulously; to devote one's thoughts to; as  to study the welfare of others; to study variety in composition."
stufa: "A jet of steam issuing from a fissure in the earth."
stull: "A framework of timber covered with boards to support rubbish; also  a framework of boards to protect miners from falling stones."
stulm: "A shaft or gallery to drain a mine."
stulp: "A short  stout post used for any purpose a to mark a boundary."
stumble: "A blunder; a failure; a fall from rectitude."
stump: "To walk clumsily  as if on stumps."
stunner: "Something striking or amazing in quality; something of extraordinary excellence."
stunt: "Specifically: A whale two years old  which having been weaned is lean and yields but little blubber."
stupid: "Resulting from  or evincing stupidity; formed without skill or genius; dull; heavy; -- said of things."
stupor: "Intellectual insensibility; moral stupidity; heedlessness or inattention to one's interests."
stupose: "Composed of  or having tufted or matted filaments like tow; stupeous."
sturdy: "A disease in sheep and cattle  marked by great nervousness or by dullness and stupor."
sturt: "A bargain in tribute mining by which the tributor profits."
styca: "An anglo-Saxon copper coin of the lowest value  being worth half a farthing."
stygian: "Of or pertaining to the river Styx; hence  hellish; infernal. See Styx."
style: "To entitle; to term  name or call; to denominate."
stylet: "Any small  more or less rigid bristlelike organ; as the caudal stylets of certain insects; the ventral stylets of certain Infusoria."
stylish: "Having style or artistic quality; given to  or fond of the display of style; highly fashionable; modish; as a stylish dress house manner."
stylist: "One who is a master or a model of style  especially in writing or speaking; a critic of style."
stylite: "One of a sect of anchorites in the early church  who lived on the tops of pillars for the exercise of their patience; -- called also pillarist and pillar saint."
stylo-: "A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with  or relation to the styloid process of the temporal bone; as stylohyal stylomastoid stylomaxillary."
styloid: "Of or pertaining to the styloid process."
stylops: "A genus of minute insects parasitic  in their larval state on bees and wasps. It is the typical genus of the group Strepsiptera formerly considered a distinct order but now generally referred to the Coleoptera. See Strepsiptera."
stylus: "A pen-shaped pointing device used to specify the cursor position on a graphics tablet."
styrone: "A white crystalline substance having a sweet taste and a hyacinthlike odor  obtained by the decomposition of styracin; -- properly called cinnamic / styryl alcohol."
styryl: "A hypothetical radical found in certain derivatives of styrolene and cinnamic acid; -- called also cinnyl  or cinnamyl."
suable: "Capable of being sued; subject by law to be called to answer in court."
suant: "Spread equally over the surface; uniform; even."
suasion: "The act of persuading; persuasion; as  moral suasion."
suave: "Sweet; pleasant; delightful; gracious or agreeable in manner; bland."
suavity: "The quality of being sweet or pleasing to the mind; agreeableness; softness; pleasantness; gentleness; urbanity; as  suavity of manners; suavity of language conversation or address."
subash: "A province; a government  as of a viceroy; also a subahdar."
subaid: "To aid secretly; to assist in a private manner  or indirectly."
subatom: "A hypothetical component of a chemical atom  on the theory that the elements themselves are complex substances; -- called also atomicule."
subaud: "To understand or supply in an ellipsis."
subdean: "An under dean; the deputy or substitute of a dean."
subdial: "Of or pertaining to the open air; being under the open sky."
subduct: "To subtract by arithmetical operation; to deduct."
subdued: "Not glaring in color; soft in tone."
subdue: "To reduce the intensity or degree of; to tone down; to soften; as  to subdue the brilliancy of colors."
subduer: "One who  or that which subdues; a conqueror."
suberic: "Of or pertaining to cork; specifically  designating an acid C6H12.(CO2H)2 homologous with oxalic acid and obtained from cork and certain fatty oils as a white crystalline substance."
suberin: "A material found in the cell walls of cork. It is a modification of lignin."
subject: "To cause to undergo; as  to subject a substance to a white heat; to subject a person to a rigid test."
subjoin: "To add after something else has been said or written; to ANNEX; as  to subjoin an argument or reason."
sublate: "To take or carry away; to remove."
sublet: "To underlet; to lease  as when a lessee leases to another person."
sublime: "To pass off in vapor  with immediate condensation; specifically to evaporate or volatilize from the solid state without apparent melting; -- said of those substances like arsenic benzoic acid etc. which do not exhibit a liquid form on heating except under increased pressure."
submit: "To be submissive or resigned; to yield without murmuring."
subnect: "To tie or fasten beneath; to join beneath."
suborn: "To procure privately  or by collusion; to procure by indirect means; to incite secretly; to instigate."
subsalt: "A basic salt. See the Note under Salt."
subside: "To fall into a state of quiet; to cease to rage; to be calmed; to settle down; to become tranquil; to abate; as  the sea subsides; the tumults of war will subside; the fever has subsided."
subsidy: "A grant from the government  from a municipal corporation or the like to a private person or company to assist the establishment or support of an enterprise deemed advantageous to the public; a subvention; as a subsidy to the owners of a line of ocean steamships."
subsist: "To support with provisions; to feed; to maintain; as  to subsist one's family."
subsume: "To take up into or under  as individual under species species under genus or particular under universal; to place (any one cognition) under another as belonging to it; to include under something else."
subtend: "To extend under  or be opposed to; as the line of a triangle which subtends the right angle; the chord subtends an arc."
subtile: "Sly; artful; cunning; crafty; subtle; as  a subtile person; a subtile adversary; a subtile scheme."
suburb: "Hence  the confines; the outer part; the environment."
subvene: "To come under  as a support or stay; to happen."
subvert: "To overthrow anything from the foundation; to be subversive."
subway: "An underground way or gallery; especially  a passage under a street in which water mains gas mains telegraph wires etc. are conducted."
succade: "Sweetmeats  or preserves in sugar whether fruit vegetables or confections."
success: "That which meets with  or one who accomplishes favorable results as a play or a player."
succise: "Appearing as if a part were cut off at the extremity."
succor: "The person or thing that brings relief."
succory: "A plant of the genus Cichorium. See Chicory."
succuba: "A female demon or fiend. See Succubus."
succula: "A bare axis or cylinder with staves or levers in it to turn it round  but without any drum."
succumb: "To yield; to submit; to give up unresistingly; as  to succumb under calamities; to succumb to disease."
succus: "The expressed juice of a plant  for medicinal use."
sucking: "Drawing milk from the mother or dam; hence  colloquially young inexperienced as a sucking infant; a sucking calf."
sucken: "The jurisdiction of a mill  or that extent of ground astricted to it the tenants of which are bound to bring their grain thither to be ground."
sucker: "To form suckers; as  corn suckers abundantly."
suckler: "An animal that suckles its young; a mammal."
sucrate: "A compound of sucrose (or of some related carbohydrate) with some base  after the analogy of a salt; as sodium sucrate."
sucre: "A silver coin of Ecuador  worth 68 cents."
sucrose: "A common variety of sugar found in the juices of many plants  as the sugar cane sorghum sugar maple beet root etc. It is extracted as a sweet white crystalline substance which is valuable as a food product and being antiputrescent is largely used in the preservation of fruit. Called also saccharose cane sugar etc. By extension
suction: "The act or process of sucking; the act of drawing  as fluids by exhausting the air."
sudoral: "Of or pertaining to sweat; as  sudoral eruptions."
sudra: "The lowest of the four great castes among the Hindoos. See Caste."
suent: "Uniformly or evenly distributed or spread; even; smooth. See Suant."
suety: "Consisting of  or resembling suet; as a suety substance."
suffer: "To be injured; to sustain loss or damage."
suffix: "To add or annex to the end  as a letter or syllable to a word; to append."
suffuse: "To overspread  as with a fluid or tincture; to fill or cover as with something fluid; as eyes suffused with tears; cheeks suffused with blushes."
sufism: "A refined mysticism among certain classes of Mohammedans  particularly in Persia who hold to a kind of pantheism and practice extreme asceticism in their lives."
sugar: "To cover with soft words; to disguise by flattery; to compliment; to sweeten; as  to sugar reproof."
sugary: "Fond of sugar or sweet things; as  a sugary palate."
suine: "A mixture of oleomargarine with lard or other fatty ingredients. It is used as a substitute for butter. See Butterine."
suint: "A peculiar substance obtained from the wool of sheep  consisting largely of potash mixed with fatty and earthy matters. It is used as a source of potash and also for the manufacture of gas."
suist: "One who seeks for things which gratify merely himself; a selfish person; a selfist."
suiting: "Among tailors  cloth suitable for making entire suits of clothes."
suite: "One of the old musical forms  before the time of the more compact sonata consisting of a string or series of pieces all in the same key mostly in various dance rhythms with sometimes an elaborate prelude. Some composers of the present day affect the suite form."
suitor: "One who attends a court as plaintiff  defendant petitioner appellant witness juror or the like."
sulks: "The condition of being sulky; a sulky mood or humor; as  to be in the sulks."
sulky: "A light two-wheeled carriage for a single person."
sulpho-: "A prefix (also used adjectively) designating sulphur as an ingredient in certain compounds. Cf. Thio-."
sulphur: "Any one of numerous species of yellow or orange butterflies of the subfamily Pierinae; as  the clouded sulphur (Eurymus / Colias philodice) which is the common yellow butterfly of the Eastern United States."
sultan: "A ruler  or sovereign of a Mohammedan state; specifically the ruler of the Turks; the Padishah or Grand Seignior; -- officially so called."
sultana: "A kind of seedless raisin produced near Smyrna in Asiatic Turkey."
sultry: "Very hot and moist  or hot close stagnant and oppressive as air."
sumach: "The powdered leaves  peduncles and young branches of certain species of the sumac plant used in tanning and dyeing."
sumbul: "The musky root of an Asiatic umbelliferous plant  Ferula Sumbul. It is used in medicine as a stimulant."
sumless: "Not to be summed up or computed; so great that the amount can not be ascertained; incalculable; inestimable."
summary: "A general or comprehensive statement; an abridged account; an abstract  abridgment or compendium containing the sum or substance of a fuller account."
summer: "To keep or carry through the summer; to feed during the summer; as  to summer stock."
summery: "Of or pertaining to summer; like summer; as  a summery day."
summist: "One who sums up; one who forms an abridgment or summary."
summit: "The most elevated part of a bivalve shell  or the part in which the hinge is situated."
summon: "To call upon to surrender  as a fort."
sumpter: "Carrying pack or burdens on the back; as  a sumpter horse; a sumpter mule."
sunbeam: "A beam or ray of the sun."
sunburn: "The burning or discoloration produced on the skin by the heat of the sun; tan."
sunder: "To expose to the sun and wind."
sundew: "Any plant of the genus Drosera  low bog plants whose leaves are beset with pediceled glands which secrete a viscid fluid that glitters like dewdrops and attracts and detains insects. After an insect is caught the glands curve inward like tentacles and the leaf digests it. Called also lustwort."
sundial: "An instrument to show the time of day by means of the shadow of a gnomon  or style on a plate."
sundog: "A luminous spot occasionally seen a few degrees from the sun  supposed to be formed by the intersection of two or more halos or in a manner similar to that of halos."
sundown: "A kind of broad-brimmed sun hat worn by women."
sunglow: "A rosy flush in the sky seen after sunset."
sunless: "Destitute or deprived of the sun or its rays; shaded; shadowed."
sunna: "A collection of traditions received by the orthodox Mohammedans as of equal authority with the Koran."
sunnite: "One of the orthodox Mohammedans who receive the Sunna as of equal importance with the Koran."
sunnud: "A charter or warrant; also  a deed of gift."
sunwise: "In the direction of the sun's apparent motion  or from the east southward and westward and so around the circle; also in the same direction as the movement of the hands of a watch lying face upward."
super-: "A prefix formerly much used to denote that the ingredient to the name of which it was prefixed was present in a large  or unusually large proportion as compared with the other ingredients; as in calcium superphosphate. It has been superseded by per- bi- di- acid etc. (as peroxide bicarbonate disulphide and acid sulphate) which retain the old meanings of super- but with sharper definition. Cf. Acid
superb: "Showy; excellent; grand; as  a superb exhibition."
supine: "A verbal noun; or (according to C.F.Becker)  a case of the infinitive mood ending in -um and -u that in -um being sometimes called the former supine and that in -u the latter supine."
supply: "Serving to contain  deliver or regulate a supply of anything; as a supply tank or valve."
support: "That which maintains or preserves from being overcome  falling yielding sinking giving way or the like; subsistence; maintenance; assistance; reenforcement; as he gave his family a good support the support of national credit; the assaulting column had the support of a battery."
suppute: "To reckon; to compute; to suppose; to impute."
supra: "Over; above; before; also  beyond; besides; -- much used as a prefix."
supreme: "Situated at the highest part or point."
surah: "A soft twilled silk fabric much used for women's dresses; -- called also surah silk."
sural: "Of or pertaining to the calf of the leg; as  the sural arteries."
surbase: "A board or group of moldings running round a room on a level with the tops of the chair backs."
surbed: "To set edgewise  as a stone; that is to set it in a position different from that which it had in the quarry."
surcle: "A little shoot; a twig; a sucker."
surcoat: "A name given to the outer garment of either sex at different epochs of the Middle Ages."
suresby: "One to be sure of  or to be relied on."
surface: "To work over the surface or soil of  as ground in hunting for gold."
surfeit: "To fill to satiety and disgust; to cloy; as  he surfeits us with compliments."
surfle: "To wash  as the face with a cosmetic water said by some to be prepared from the sulphur."
surfman: "One who serves in a surfboat in the life-saving service."
surfoot: "Tired or sore of foot from travel; lamed."
surfy: "Consisting of  abounding in or resembling surf; as a surfy shore."
surge: "To let go or slacken suddenly  as a rope; as to surge a hawser or messenger; also to slacken the rope about (a capstan)."
surgeon: "Any one of numerous species of chaetodont fishes of the family Teuthidae  or Acanthuridae which have one or two sharp lancelike spines on each side of the base of the tail. Called also surgeon fish doctor fish lancet fish and sea surgeon."
surgy: "Rising in surges or billows; full of surges; resembling surges in motion or appearance; swelling."
surloin: "A loin of beef  or the upper part of the loin. See Sirloin the more usual but not etymologically preferable orthography."
surmark: "A mark made on the molds of a ship  when building to show where the angles of the timbers are to be placed."
surmise: "To imagine without certain knowledge; to infer on slight grounds; to suppose  conjecture or suspect; to guess."
surname: "To name or call by an appellation added to the original name; to give a surname to."
surpass: "To go beyond in anything good or bad; to exceed; to excel."
surplus: "Being or constituting a surplus; more than sufficient; as  surplus revenues; surplus population; surplus words."
surrey: "A four-wheeled pleasure carriage  (commonly two-seated) somewhat like a phaeton but having a straight bottom."
surtout: "A man's coat to be worn over his other garments; an overcoat  especially when long and fitting closely like a body coat."
survene: "To supervene upon; to come as an addition to."
survey: "The operation of finding the contour  dimensions position or other particulars of as any part of the earth's surface whether land or water; also a measured plan and description of any portion of country or of a road or line through it."
survive: "To remain alive; to continue to live."
suslik: "A ground squirrel (Spermophilus citillus) of Europe and Asia. It has large cheek pouches."
suspect: "To imagine guilt; to have a suspicion or suspicions; to be suspicious."
suspend: "To cease from operation or activity; esp.  to stop payment or be unable to meet obligations or engagements (said of a commercial firm or a bank)."
sustain: "One who  or that which upholds or sustains; a sustainer."
sutler: "A person who follows an army  and sells to the troops provisions liquors and the like."
sutling: "Belonging to sutlers; engaged in the occupation of a sutler."
sutor: "A kind of sirup made by the Indians of Arizona from the fruit of some cactaceous plant (probably the Cereus giganteus)."
sutra: "A body of Hindoo literature containing aphorisms on grammar  meter law and philosophy and forming a connecting link between the Vedic and later Sanscrit literature."
suttee: "The act of burning a widow on the funeral pile of her husband."
suttle: "To act as sutler; to supply provisions and other articles to troops."
sutural: "Taking place at a suture; as  a sutural de/iscence."
suture: "A seam  or impressed line as between the segments of a crustacean or between the whorls of a univalve shell."
sutured: "Having a suture or sutures; knit or united together."
swage: "To shape by means of a swage; to fashion  as a piece of iron by forcing it into a groove or mold having the required shape."
swagger: "The act or manner of a swaggerer."
swaggy: "Inclined to swag; sinking  hanging or leaning by its weight."
swain: "A young man dwelling in the country; a rustic; esp.  a cuntry gallant or lover; -- chiefly in poetry."
swallet: "Water breaking in upon the miners at their work; -- so called among tin miners."
swamp: "To become filled with water  as a boat; to founder; to capsize or sink; figuratively to be ruined; to be wrecked."
swampy: "Consisting of swamp; like a swamp; low  wet and spongy; as swampy land."
swanny: "Swanlike; as  a swanny glossiness of the neck."
sward: "To produce sward upon; to cover  or be covered with sward."
swarf: "The grit worn away from grindstones in grinding cutlery wet."
swart: "To make swart or tawny; as  to swart a living part."
swasher: "One who makes a blustering show of valor or force of arms."
swashy: "Soft  like fruit that is too ripe; quashy; swash."
swatch: "A piece  pattern or sample generally of cloth."
swather: "A device attached to a mowing machine for raising the uncut fallen grain and marking the limit of the swath."
swayed: "Bent down  and hollow in the back; sway-backed; -- said of a horse."
swaying: "An injury caused by violent strains or by overloading; -- said of the backs of horses."
sweal: "To singe; to scorch; to swale; as  to sweal a pig by singeing off the hair."
swearer: "A profane person; one who uses profane language."
sweat: "A short run by a race horse in exercise."
sweater: "An employer who oppresses his workmen by paying low wages."
sweeny: "An atrophy of the muscles of the shoulder in horses; also  atrophy of any muscle in horses."
sweep: "The sweeping of workshops where precious metals are worked  containing filings etc."
sweeper: "One who  or that which sweeps or cleans by sweeping; a sweep; as a carpet sweeper."
swollen: "Enlarged by swelling; immoderately increased; as  swollen eyes; swollen streams."
swell: "Having the characteristics of a person of rank and importance; showy; dandified; distinguished; as  a swell person; a swell neighborhood."
swelt: "To overpower  as with heat; to cause to faint; to swelter."
sweven: "A vision seen in sleep; a dream."
swift: "The main card cylinder of a flax-carding machine."
swifter: "To tighten  as slack standing rigging by bringing the opposite shrouds nearer."
swiftly: "In a swift manner; with quick motion or velocity; fleetly."
swill: "Large draughts of liquor; drink taken in excessive quantities."
swimbel: "A moaning or sighing sound or noise; a sough."
swimmer: "A swimming bird; one of the natatores."
swindle: "The act or process of swindling; a cheat."
swine: "Any animal of the hog kind  especially one of the domestical species. Swine secrete a large amount of subcutaneous fat which when extracted is known as lard. The male is specifically called boar the female sow and the young pig. See Hog."
swing: "Free course; unrestrained liberty or license; tendency."
swingel: "The swinging part of a flail which falls on the grain in thrashing; the swiple."
swinger: "A person who engages freely in sexual intercourse."
swingle: "A wooden instrument like a large knife  about two feet long with one thin edge used for beating and cleaning flax; a scutcher; -- called also swingling knife swingling staff and swingling wand."
swinish: "Of or pertaining to swine; befitting swine; like swine; hoggish; gross; beasty; as  a swinish drunkard or sot."
swiple: "That part of a flail which strikes the grain in thrashing; a swingel."
swirl: "A whirling motion; an eddy  as of water; a whirl."
swiss: "Of or pertaining to Switzerland  or the people of Switzerland."
switzer: "A native or inhabitant of Switzerland; a Swiss."
swivel: "To swing or turn  as on a pin or pivot."
swizzle: "Ale and beer mixed; also  drink generally."
swobber: "Four privileged cards  formerly used in betting at the game of whist."
swoop: "A falling on and seizing  as the prey of a rapacious bird; the act of swooping."
sword: "One of the end bars by which the lay of a hand loom is suspended."
sworder: "One who uses  or fights with a sword; a swordsman; a soldier; a cutthroat."
sycee: "Silver  pounded into ingots of the shape of a shoe and used as currency. The most common weight is about one pound troy."
sycite: "A nodule of flint  or a pebble which resembles a fig."
syconus: "A collective fleshy fruit  in which the ovaries are hidden within a hollow receptacle as in the fig."
sycosis: "A pustular eruption upon the scalp  or the beared part of the face whether due to ringworm acne or impetigo."
syenite: "A granular  crystalline ingeous rock composed of orthoclase and hornblende the latter often replaced or accompanied by pyroxene or mica. Syenite sometimes contains nephelite (elaeolite) or leucite and is then called nephelite (elaeolite) syenite or leucite syenite."
sylph: "Any one of several species of very brilliant South American humming birds  having a very long and deeply-forked tail; as the blue-tailed sylph (Cynanthus cyanurus)."
sylphid: "A little sylph; a young or diminutive sylph."
sylvan: "A liquid hydrocarbon obtained together with furfuran (tetrol) by the distillation of pine wood; -- called also methyl tetrol  or methyl furfuran."
sylvic: "Of  pertaining to or resembling pine or its products; specifically designating an acid called also abeitic acid which is the chief ingredient of common resin (obtained from Pinus sylvestris and other species)."
symptom: "A sign or token; that which indicates the existence of something else; as  corruption in elections is a symptom of the decay of public virtue."
synapta: "A genus of slender  transparent holothurians which have delicate calcareous anchors attached to the dermal plates. See Illustration in Appendix."
synaxis: "A congregation; also  formerly the Lord's Supper."
syncarp: "A kind of aggregate fruit in which the ovaries cohere in a solid mass  with a slender receptacle as in the magnolia; also a similar multiple fruit as a mulberry."
syndic: "An agent of a corporation  or of any body of men engaged in a business enterprise; an advocate or patron; an assignee."
synepy: "The interjunction  or joining of words in uttering the clauses of sentences."
synergy: "An effect of the interaction of the actions of two agents such that the result of the combined action is greater than expected as a simple additive combination of the two agents acting separately. Also synergism."
synocil: "A sense organ found in certain sponges. It consists of several filaments  each of which arises from a single cell."
synod: "A conjunction of two or more of the heavenly bodies."
synodal: "A constitution made in a provincial or diocesan synod."
synonym: "One of two or more words (commonly words of the same language) which are equivalents of each other; one of two or more words which have very nearly the same signification  and therefore may often be used interchangeably. See under Synonymous."
synovia: "A transparent  viscid lubricating fluid which contains mucin and secreted by synovial membranes; synovial fluid."
syntax: "That part of grammar which treats of the construction of sentences; the due arrangement of words in sentences in their necessary relations  according to established usage in any language."
syriac: "The language of Syria; especially  the ancient language of that country."
syriasm: "A Syrian idiom; a Syrianism; a Syriacism."
syringa: "The mock orange; -- popularly so called because its stems were formerly used as pipestems."
syringe: "To wash and clean by injection from a syringe."
syrma: "A long dress  trailing on the floor worn by tragic actors in Greek and Roman theaters."
syrtic: "Of or pertaining to a syrt; resembling syrt  or quicksand."
system: "One of the stellate or irregular clusters of intimately united zooids which are imbedded in  or scattered over the surface of the common tissue of many compound ascidians."
systole: "The contraction of the heart and arteries by which the blood is forced onward and the circulation kept up; -- correlative to diastole."
syzygy: "The immovable union of two joints of a crinoidal arm."
tabanus: "A genus of blood sucking flies  including the horseflies."
tabard: "A sort of tunic or mantle formerly worn for protection from the weather. When worn over the armor it was commonly emblazoned with the arms of the wearer  and from this the name was given to the garment adopted for heralds."
tabaret: "A stout silk having satin stripes  -- used for furniture."
tabby: "To water; to cause to look wavy  by the process of calendering; to calender; as to tabby silk mohair ribbon etc."
tabefy: "To cause to waste gradually  to emaciate."
tabes: "Progressive emaciation of the body  accompained with hectic fever with no well-marked logical symptoms."
table: "To live at the table of another; to board; to eat."
tableau: "A representation of some scene by means of persons grouped in the proper manner  placed in appropriate postures and remaining silent and motionless."
tablet: "A solid kind of electuary or confection  commonly made of dry ingredients with sugar and usually formed into little flat squares; -- called also lozenge and troche especially when of a round or rounded form."
tabling: "Act of playing at tables. See Table  n. 10."
taboo: "To put under taboo; to forbid  or to forbid the use of; to interdict approach to or use of; as to taboo the ground set apart as a sanctuary for criminals."
tabula: "One of the transverse plants found in the calicles of certain corals and hydroids."
tabular: "Derived from  or computed by the use of tables; as tabular right ascension."
tacet: "It is silent; -- a direction for a vocal or instrumental part to be silent during a whole movement."
tachina: "Any one of numerous species of Diptera belonging to Tachina and allied genera. Their larvae are external parasites of other insects."
tacit: "Done or made in silence; implied  but not expressed; silent; as tacit consent is consent by silence or by not interposing an objection."
tacking: "A union of securities given at different times  all of which must be redeemed before an intermediate purchaser can interpose his claim."
tackle: "To begin to deal with; as  to tackle the problem."
tacky: "Sticky; adhesive; raw; -- said of paint  varnish etc. when not well dried."
taconic: "Designating  or pertaining to the series of rocks forming the Taconic mountains in Western New England. They were once supposed to be older than the Cambrian but later proved to belong to the Lower Silurian and Cambrian."
tactics: "Hence  any system or method of procedure."
tactile: "Of or pertaining to the organs  or the sense of touch; perceiving or perceptible by the touch; capable of being touched; as tactile corpuscles; tactile sensations."
taction: "The act of touching; touch; contact; tangency."
tactual: "Of or pertaining to the sense  or the organs of touch; derived from touch."
ta'en: "p. p. of Ta  to take or a contraction of Taken."
taenia: "The fillet  or band at the bottom of a Doric frieze separating it from the architrave."
taffety: "A fine  smooth stuff of silk having usually the wavy luster called watering. The term has also been applied to different kinds of silk goods from the 16th century to modern times."
tagger: "A device for removing taglocks from sheep."
taglock: "An entangled lock  as of hair or wool."
tag-rag: "The lowest class of people; the rabble. Cf. Rag  tag and bobtail under Bobtail."
tagsore: "Adhesion of the tail of a sheep to the wool from excoriation produced by contact with the feces; -- called also tagbelt."
tagtail: "A person who attaches himself to another against the will of the latter; a hanger-on."
taguan: "A large flying squirrel (Pteromys petuarista). Its body becomes two feet long  with a large bushy tail nearly as long."
tailed: "Having a tail; having (such) a tail or (so many) tails; -- chiefly used in composition; as  bobtailed longtailed etc."
tailing: "The refuse part of stamped ore  thrown behind the tail of the buddle or washing apparatus. It is dressed over again to secure whatever metal may exist in it. Called also tails."
taille: "The French name for the tenor voice or part; also  for the tenor viol or viola."
tailor: "To practice making men's clothes; to follow the business of a tailor."
tailpin: "The center in the spindle of a turning lathe."
tailzie: "An entailment or deed whereby the legal course of succession is cut off  and an arbitrary one substituted."
taint: "A blemish on reputation; stain; spot; disgrace."
taker: "One who takes or receives; one who catches or apprehends."
take-up: "That which takes up or tightens; specifically  a device in a sewing machine for drawing up the slack thread as the needle rises in completing a stitch."
talaria: "Small wings or winged shoes represented as fastened to the ankles  -- chiefly used as an attribute of Mercury."
talbot: "A sort of dog  noted for quick scent and eager pursuit of game."
talcous: "Of or pertaining to talc; composed of  or resembling talc."
taled: "A kind of quadrangular piece of cloth put on by the Jews when repeating prayers in the synagogues."
talent: "Intellectual ability  natural or acquired; mental endowment or capacity; skill in accomplishing; a special gift particularly in business art or the like; faculty; a use of the word probably originating in the Scripture parable of the talents (Matt. xxv. 14-30)."
tales: "The writ by which such persons are summoned."
talipot: "A beautiful tropical palm tree (Corypha umbraculifera)  a native of Ceylon and the Malabar coast. It has a trunk sixty or seventy feet high bearing a crown of gigantic fan-shaped leaves which are used as umbrellas and as fans in ceremonial processions and when cut into strips as a substitute for writing paper."
talker: "A loquacious person  male or female; a prattler; a babbler; also a boaster; a braggart; -- used in contempt or reproach."
tallage: "To lay an impost upon; to cause to pay tallage."
tallow: "To cause to have a large quantity of tallow; to fatten; as  tallow sheep."
tallowy: "Of the nature of tallow; resembling tallow; greasy."
talma: "A similar garment worn formerly by gentlemen."
talmud: "The body of the Jewish civil and canonical law not comprised in the Pentateuch."
talon: "The shoulder of the bolt of a lock on which the key acts to shoot the bolt."
taluk: "A large estate; esp.  one constituting a revenue district or dependency the native proprietor of which is responsible for the collection and payment of the public revenue due from it."
talpa: "A genus of small insectivores including the common European mole."
talus: "A sloping heap of fragments of rock lying at the foot of a precipice."
tamable: "Capable of being tamed  subdued or reclaimed from wildness or savage ferociousness."
tamandu: "A small ant-eater (Tamandua tetradactyla) native of the tropical parts of South America."
tamaric: "A shrub or tree supposed to be the tamarisk  or perhaps some kind of heath."
tamarin: "Any one of several species of small squirrel-like South American monkeys of the genus Midas  especially M. ursulus."
tamias: "A genus of ground squirrels  including the chipmunk."
tamil: "The Tamil language  the most important of the Dravidian languages. See Dravidian a."
tammy: "A sieve  or strainer made of this material; a tamis."
tamping: "The material used in tamping. See Tamp  v. t. 1."
tamper: "To deal unfairly; to practice secretly; to use bribery."
tampion: "A plug for upper end of an organ pipe."
tampoe: "The edible fruit of an East Indian tree (Baccaurea Malayana) of the Spurge family. It somewhat resembles an apple."
tampoon: "The stopper of a barrel; a bung."
tanning: "The art or process of converting skins into leather. See Tan  v. t. 1."
tanager: "Any one of numerous species of bright-colored singing birds belonging to Tanagra  Piranga and allied genera. The scarlet tanager (Piranga erythromelas) and the summer redbird (Piranga rubra) are common species of the United States."
tanate: "An Asiatic wild dog (Canis procyonoides)  native of Japan and adjacent countries. It has a short bushy tail. Called also raccoon dog."
tandem: "A team of horses harnessed one before the other."
tangent: "meeting a curve or surface at a point and having at that point the same direction as the curve or surface; -- said of a straight line  curve or surface; as a line tangent to a curve; a curve tangent to a surface; tangent surfaces."
tangle: "An instrument consisting essentially of an iron bar to which are attached swabs  or bundles of frayed rope or other similar substances -- used to capture starfishes sea urchins and other similar creatures living at the bottom of the sea."
tangram: "A Chinese toy made by cutting a square of thin wood  or other suitable material into seven pieces as shown in the cut these pieces being capable of combination in various ways so as to form a great number of different figures. It is now often used in primary schools as a means of instruction."
tangun: "A piebald variety of the horse  native of Thibet."
tanier: "An aroid plant (Caladium sagittaefolium)  the leaves of which are boiled and eaten in the West Indies."
tanist: "In Ireland  a lord or proprietor of a tract of land or of a castle elected by a family under the system of tanistry."
tanite: "A firm composition of emery and a certain kind of cement  used for making grinding wheels slabs etc."
tanka: "A kind of boat used in Canton. It is about 25 feet long and is often rowed by women. Called also tankia."
tankard: "A large drinking vessel  especially one with a cover."
tannage: "A tanning; the act  operation or result of tanning."
tanner: "One whose occupation is to tan hides  or convert them into leather by the use of tan."
tannic: "Of or pertaining to tan; derived from  or resembling tan; as tannic acid."
tansy: "A dish common in the seventeenth century  made of eggs sugar rose water cream and the juice of herbs baked with butter in a shallow dish."
tantrum: "A whim  or burst of ill-humor; an affected air."
tanyard: "An inclosure where the tanning of leather is carried on; a tannery."
taoism: "One of the popular religions of China  sanctioned by the state."
tapered: "Lighted with a taper or tapers; as  a tapered choir."
tapetum: "An area in the pigmented layer of the choroid coat of the eye in many animals  which has an iridescent or metallic luster and helps to make the eye visible in the dark. Sometimes applied to the whole layer of pigmented epithelium of the choroid."
tapioca: "A coarsely granular substance obtained by heating  and thus partly changing the moistened starch obtained from the roots of the cassava. It is much used in puddings and as a thickening for soups. See Cassava."
tapir: "Any one of several species of large odd-toed ungulates belonging to Tapirus  Elasmognathus and allied genera. They have a long prehensile upper lip short ears short and stout legs a short thick tail and short close hair. They have three toes on the hind feet and four toes on the fore feet but the outermost toe is of little use."
tapis: "To cover or work with figures like tapestry."
tapish: "To lie close to the ground  so as to be concealed; to squat; to crouch; hence to hide one's self."
taplash: "Bad small beer; also  the refuse or dregs of liquor."
tappen: "An obstruction  or indigestible mass found in the intestine of bears and other animals during hibernation."
tapper: "The lesser spotted woodpecker (Dendrocopus minor); -- called also tapperer  tabberer little wood pie barred woodpecker wood tapper hickwall and pump borer."
tappet: "A lever or projection moved by some other piece  as a cam or intended to tap or touch something else with a view to produce change or regulate motion."
taproom: "A room where liquors are kept on tap; a barroom."
taproot: "The root of a plant which penetrates the earth directly downward to a considerable depth without dividing."
tapster: "One whose business is to tap or draw ale or other liquor."
taranis: "A Celtic divinity  regarded as the evil principle but confounded by the Romans with Jupiter."
tared: "Weighed; determined; reduced to equal or standard weight; as  tared filter papers used in weighing precipitates."
taring: "The common tern; -- called also tarret  and tarrock."
tarente: "A harmless lizard of the Gecko family (Platydactylus Mauritianicus) found in Southern Europe and adjacent countries  especially among old walls and ruins."
target: "A conspicuous disk attached to a switch lever to show its position  or for use as a signal."
targum: "A translation or paraphrase of some portion of the Old Testament Scriptures in the Chaldee or Aramaic language or dialect."
tariff: "To make a list of duties on  as goods."
tarnish: "A thin film on the surface of a metal  usually due to a slight alteration of the original color; as the steel tarnish in columbite."
tarot: "A game of cards; -- called also taroc."
tarpan: "A wild horse found in the region of the Caspian Sea."
tarpum: "A very large marine fish (Megapolis Atlanticus) of the Southern United States and the West Indies. It often becomes six or more feet in length  and has large silvery scales. The scales are a staple article of trade and are used in fancywork. Called also tarpon sabalo savanilla silverfish and jewfish."
tarre: "To set on  as a dog; to incite."
tarsale: "One of the bones or cartilages of the tarsus; esp.  one of the series articulating with the metatarsals."
tarsius: "A genus of nocturnal lemurine mammals having very large eyes and ears  a long tail and very long proximal tarsal bones; -- called also malmag spectral lemur podji and tarsier."
tarso-: "A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with  or relation to the tarsus; as tarsometatarsus."
tarsus: "The foot of an insect or a crustacean. It usually consists of form two to five joints."
tartan: "A small coasting vessel  used in the Mediterranean having one mast carrying large leteen sail and a bowsprit with staysail or jib."
tartro-: "A combining form (also used adjectively) used in chemistry to denote the presence of tartar or of some of its compounds or derivatives."
tartufe: "A hypocritical devotee. See the Dictionary of Noted Names in Fiction."
tarweed: "A name given to several resinous-glandular composite plants of California  esp. to the species of Grindelia Hemizonia and Madia."
tasco: "A kind of clay for making melting pots."
tasimer: "An instrument for detecting or measuring minute extension or movements of solid bodies. It consists essentially of a small rod  disk or button of carbon forming part of an electrical circuit the resistance of which being varied by the changes of pressure produced by the movements of the object to be measured causes variations in the strength of the current which variations are indicated by a sensitive galvanometer. It is also used for measuring minute changes of temperature."
tasker: "A laborer who receives his wages in kind."
taslet: "A piece of armor formerly worn to guard the things; a tasse."
tasse: "A piece of armor for the thighs  forming an appendage to the ancient corselet."
tasset: "A defense for the front of the thigh  consisting of one or more iron plates hanging from the belt on the lower edge of the corselet."
tasting: "The act of perceiving or tasting by the organs of taste; the faculty or sense by which we perceive or distinguish savors."
taste: "A kind of narrow and thin silk ribbon."
taster: "One of a peculiar kind of zooids situated on the polyp-stem of certain Siphonophora. They somewhat resemble the feeding zooids  but are destitute of mouths. See Siphonophora."
tasto: "A key or thing touched to produce a tone."
tasty: "Being in conformity to the principles of good taste; elegant; as  tasty furniture; a tasty dress."
tatch: "A spot or stain; also  a trick."
tatou: "The giant armadillo (Priodontes gigas) of tropical South America. It becomes nearly five feet long including the tail. It is noted for its burrowing powers  feeds largely upon dead animals and sometimes invades human graves."
tatouay: "An armadillo (Xenurus unicinctus)  native of the tropical parts of South America. It has about thirteen movable bands composed of small nearly square scales. The head is long; the tail is round and tapered and nearly destitute of scales; the claws of the fore feet are very large. Called also tatouary and broad-banded armadillo."
tatta: "A bamboo frame or trellis hung at a door or window of a house  over which water is suffered to trickle in order to moisten and cool the air as it enters."
tatter: "To rend or tear into rags; -- used chiefly in the past participle as an adjective."
tatting: "A kind of lace made from common sewing thread  with a peculiar stitch."
tattle: "Idle talk or chat; trifling talk; prate."
tattler: "Any one of several species of large  long-legged sandpipers belonging to the genus Totanus."
tattoo: "An indelible mark or figure made by puncturing the skin and introducing some pigment into the punctures; -- a mode of ornamentation practiced by various barbarous races  both in ancient and modern times and also by some among civilized nations especially by sailors."
taunt: "Upbraiding language; bitter or sarcastic reproach; insulting invective."
taurine: "A body occurring in small quantity in the juices of muscle  in the lungs and elsewhere but especially in the bile where it is found as a component part of taurocholic acid from which it can be prepared by decomposition of the acid. It crystallizes in colorless regular six-sided prisms and is especially characterized by containing both nitrogen and sulphur being chemically amido-isethionic acid C2H7NSO3."
taurus: "A genus of ruminants comprising the common domestic cattle."
tautog: "An edible labroid fish (Haitula onitis  or Tautoga onitis) of the Atlantic coast of the United States. When adult it is nearly black more or less irregularly barred with greenish gray. Called also blackfish oyster fish salt-water chub and moll."
tavern: "A public house where travelers and other transient guests are accomodated with rooms and meals; an inn; a hotel; especially  in modern times a public house licensed to sell liquor in small quantities."
tawdry: "A necklace of a rural fashion  bought at St. Audrey's fair; hence a necklace in general."
tawer: "One who taws; a dresser of white leather."
tawny: "Of a dull yellowish brown color  like things tanned or persons who are sunburnt; as tawny Moor or Spaniard; the tawny lion."
taxable: "That may be legally charged by a court against the plaintiff of defendant in a suit; as  taxable costs."
taxer: "One of two officers chosen yearly to regulate the assize of bread  and to see the true gauge of weights and measures is observed."
taxine: "A poisonous alkaloid of bitter taste extracted from the leaves and seeds of the European yew (Taxus baccata). Called also taxia."
taxis: "Manipulation applied to a hernial tumor  or to an intestinal obstruction for the purpose of reducing it."
tayra: "A South American carnivore (Galera barbara) allied to the grison. The tail is long and thick. The length  including the tail is about three feet."
tazza: "An ornamental cup or vase with a large  flat shallow bowl resting on a pedestal and often having handles."
teach: "To give instruction; to follow the business  or to perform the duties of a preceptor."
teache: "One of the series of boilers in which the cane juice is treated in making sugar; especially  the last boiler of the series."
teacher: "One who instructs others in religion; a preacher; a minister of the gospel; sometimes  one who preaches without regular ordination."
teacup: "A small cup from which to drink tea."
teagle: "A hoisting apparatus; an elevator; a crane; a lift."
teague: "An Irishman; -- a term used in contempt."
teamed: "Yoked in  or as in a team."
teapot: "A vessel with a spout  in which tea is made and from which it is poured into teacups."
teapoy: "An ornamental stand  usually with three legs having caddies for holding tea."
tearer: "One who tears or rends anything; also  one who rages or raves with violence."
tearful: "Abounding with tears; weeping; shedding tears; as  tearful eyes."
tearpit: "A cavity or pouch beneath the lower eyelid of most deer and antelope; the lachrymal sinus; larmier. It is capable of being opened at pleasure and secretes a waxy substance."
teary: "Consisting of tears  or drops like tears."
teasel: "To subject  as woolen cloth to the action of teasels or any substitute for them which has an effect to raise a nap."
teated: "Having protuberances resembling the teat of an animal."
teatish: "Peevish; tettish; fretful; -- said of a child. See Tettish."
teazer: "The stoker or fireman of a furnace  as in glass works."
tebeth: "The tenth month of the Jewish ecclesiastical year  answering to a part of December with a part of January."
technic: "Technical terms or objects; things pertaining to the practice of an art or science."
te deum: "A religious service in which the singing of the hymn forms a principal part."
tedge: "The gate of a mold  through which the melted metal is poured; runner geat."
tedious: "Involving tedium; tiresome from continuance  prolixity slowness or the like; wearisome."
teenage: "The longer wood for making or mending fences."
teenful: "Full of teen; harmful; grievous; grieving; afflicted."
teens: "The years of one's age having the termination -teen  beginning with thirteen and ending with nineteen; as a girl in her teens."
teeter: "To move up and down on the ends of a balanced plank  or the like as children do for sport; to seesaw; to titter; to titter-totter."
tegula: "A small appendage situated above the base of the wings of Hymenoptera and attached to the mesonotum."
tegular: "Of or pertaining to a tile; resembling a tile  or arranged like tiles; consisting of tiles; as a tegular pavement."
telary: "Of or pertaining to a web; hence  spinning webs; retiary."
teledu: "An East Indian carnivore (Mydaus meliceps) allied to the badger  and noted for the very offensive odor that it emits somewhat resembling that of a skunk. It is a native of the high mountains of Java and Sumatra and has long silky fur. Called also stinking badger and stinkard."
teleost: "One of the Teleosti. Also used adjectively."
telesm: "A kind of amulet or magical charm."
telic: "Denoting the final end or purpose  as distinguished from ecbatic. See Ecbatic."
telling: "Operating with great effect; effective; as  a telling speech."
teller: "One who is appointed to count the votes given in a legislative body  public meeting assembly etc."
tellina: "A genus of marine bivalve mollusks having thin  delicate and often handsomely colored shells."
telpher: "A contrivance for the conveyance of vehicles or loads by means of electricity."
telson: "The terminal joint or movable piece at the end of the abdomen of Crustacea and other articulates. See Thoracostraca."
telugu: "Of or pertaining to the Telugu language  or the Telugus."
tempean: "Of or pertaining to Temple  a valley in Thessaly celebrated by Greek poets on account of its beautiful scenery; resembling Temple; hence beautiful; delightful; charming."
temper: "To have or get a proper or desired state or quality; to grow soft and pliable."
tempera: "A mode or process of painting; distemper."
temple: "To build a temple for; to appropriate a temple to; as  to temple a god."
templed: "Supplied with a temple or temples  or with churches; inclosed in a temple."
templet: "A short piece of timber  iron or stone placed in a wall under a girder or other beam to distribute the weight or pressure."
tempo: "The rate or degree of movement in time."
tempt: "To endeavor to accomplish or reach; to attempt."
tempter: "One who tempts or entices; especially  Satan or the Devil regarded as the great enticer to evil."
tenable: "Capable of being held  naintained or defended as against an assailant or objector or againts attempts to take or process; as a tenable fortress a tenable argument."
tenace: "The holding by the fourth hand of the best and third best cards of a suit led; also  sometimes the combination of best with third best card of a suit in any hand."
tenancy: "A house for habitation  or place to live in held of another."
tenant: "To hold  occupy or possess as a tenant."
tench: "A European fresh-water fish (Tinca tinca  or T. vulgaris) allied to the carp. It is noted for its tenacity of life."
tender: "To have a care of; to be tender toward; hence  to regard; to esteem; to value."
tendon: "A tough insensible cord  bundle or band of fibrous connective tissue uniting a muscle with some other part; a sinew."
tendrac: "Any one of several species of small insectivores of the family Centetidae  belonging to Ericulus Echinope and related genera native of Madagascar. They are more or less spinose and resemble the hedgehog in habits. The rice tendrac (Oryzorictes hora) is very injurious to rice crops. Some of the species are called also tenrec."
teneral: "Of  pertaining to or designating a condition assumed by the imago of certain Neuroptera after exclusion from the pupa. In this state the insect is soft and has not fully attained its mature coloring."
tenet: "Any opinion  principle dogma belief or doctrine which a person holds or maintains as true; as the tenets of Plato or of Cicero."
tenfold: "In tens; consisting of ten in one; ten times repeated."
tenne: "A tincture  rarely employed which is considered as an orange color or bright brown. It is represented by diagonal lines from sinister to dexter crossed by vertical lines."
tennis: "To drive backward and forward  as a ball in playing tennis."
tenon: "To cut or fit for insertion into a mortise  as the end of a piece of timber."
tenor: "A person who sings the tenor  or the instrument that play it."
tenpins: "A game resembling ninepins  but played with ten pins. See Ninepins."
tenrec: "A small insectivore (Centetes ecaudatus)  native of Madagascar but introduced also into the islands of Bourbon and Mauritius; -- called also tanrec. The name is applied to other allied genera. See Tendrac."
tense: "Stretched tightly; strained to stiffness; rigid; not lax; as  a tense fiber."
tension: "The quality in consequence of which an electric charge tends to discharge itself  as into the air by a spark or to pass from a body of greater to one of less electrical potential. It varies as the quantity of electricity upon a given area."
tensity: "The quality or state of being tense  or strained to stiffness; tension; tenseness."
tensive: "Giving the sensation of tension  stiffness or contraction."
tensor: "The ratio of one vector to another in length  no regard being had to the direction of the two vectors; -- so called because considered as a stretching factor in changing one vector into another. See Versor."
tenter: "To hang or stretch on  or as on tenters."
tentful: "As much  or as many as a tent will hold."
tenth: "The tenth part of the annual profit of every living in the kingdom  formerly paid to the pope but afterward transferred to the crown. It now forms a part of the fund called Queen Anne's Bounty."
tentory: "The awning or covering of a tent."
tenuis: "One of the three surd mutes /  / /; -- so called in relation to their respective middle letters or medials / / / and their aspirates / / /. The term is also applied to the corresponding letters and articulate elements in other languages."
tenure: "Manner of holding  in general; as in absolute governments men hold their rights by a precarious tenure."
tepefy: "To make or become tepid  or moderately warm."
tepid: "Moderately warm; lukewarm; as  a tepid bath; tepid rays; tepid vapors."
tequila: "An intoxicating liquor made from the maguey in the district of Tequila  Mexico."
terbic: "Of  pertaining to or containing terbium; also designating certain of its compounds."
terbium: "A rare metallic element  of uncertain identification supposed to exist in certain minerals as gadolinite and samarskite with other rare ytterbium earth. Symbol Tr or Tb. Atomic weight 150."
tercet: "A triplet; a group of three lines."
